{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01JLzUAikdevKWBacFkcrUgN","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t000\n2\t001\n3\t002\n4\t003\n5\t004\n6\t005\n7\t006\n8\t007\n9\t008\n10\t009\n11\t010\n12\t011\n13\t012\n14\t013\n15\t014\n16\t015\n17\t016\n18\t017\n19\t018\n20\t019\n21\t020\n22\t021\n23\t022\n24\t023\n25\t024\n26\t025\n27\t026\n28\t027\n29\t028\n30\t029\n31\t030\n32\t031\n33\t032\n34\t033\n35\t034\n36\t035\n37\t036\n38\t037\n39\t038\n40\t039\n41\t040\n42\t041\n43\t042\n44\t043\n45\t044\n46\t045\n47\t046\n48\t047\n49\t048\n50\t049\n51\t050\n52\t051\n53\t052\n54\t053\n55\t054\n56\tFrom Storage to Steering:\n57\tMemory Control Flow Attacks on LLM Agents\n58\tAnonymous Authors1\n59\tAbstract\n60\tModern agentic systems allow Large Language\n61\tModel (LLM) agents to tackle complex tasks\n62\tthrough extensive tool usage, forming structured\n63\tcontrol flows of tool selection and execution. Ex-\n64\tisting security analyses often treat these control\n65\tflows as ephemeral, one-off sessions, overlooking\n66\tthe persistent influence of memory. This paper\n67\tidentifies a new threat from Memory Control Flow\n68\tAttacks (MCFA) that memory retrieval can dom-\n69\tinate the control flow,forcing unintended tool\n70\tusageeven against explicit user instructions and\n71\tinducingpersistent behavioral deviationsacross\n72\ttasks. To understand the impact of this vulnerabil-\n73\tity, we further design MEMFLOW, an automated\n74\tevaluation framework that systematically identi-\n75\tfies and quantifies MCFA across heterogeneous\n76\ttasks and long interaction horizons. To evaluate\n77\tMEMFLOW, we attack state-of-the-art LLMs, in-\n78\tcludingGPT-5 mini, Claude Sonnet 4.5 and Gem-\n79\tini 2.5 Flashon real-world tools from two major\n80\tLLM agent development frameworks, LangChain\n81\tand LlamaIndex. The results show that in general\n82\tover90%trials are vulnerable to MCFA even un-\n83\tder strict safety constraints, highlighting critical\n84\tsecurity risks that demand immediate attention.\n85\t1. Introduction\n86\tIn an agentic system empowered by Large Language Models\n87\t(LLM) (OpenAI, 2025; Google, 2025; Anthropic, 2025),\n88\teach LLM agent has substantially improved their ability to\n89\tsolve complex tasks through access to an increasing number\n90\tof tools (Fu et al., 2024; Patil et al., 2025). For example,\n91\twhen given a restaurant recommendation task, an LLM\n92\tagent may first invoke a web search tool to identify highly\n93\trated nearby restaurants and then call a mapping service to\n94\t1Anonymous Institution, Anonymous City, Anonymous Region,\n95\tAnonymous Country. Correspondence to: Anonymous Author\n96\t<anon.email@domain.com>.\n97\tPreliminary work. Under review by the International Conference\n98\ton Machine Learning (ICML). Do not distribute.\n99\tplan optimal routes to the selected candidates. As agents\n100\tincreasingly coordinate multiple tools to achieve a single\n101\tobjective, their behavior naturally induces structuredcontrol\n102\tflowsover tool selection and execution (Li et al., 2026).\n103\tThe presence of control flows over tool selection and execu-\n104\ttion in LLM-powered agentic systems introduces a series\n105\tof new security challenges (Debenedetti et al., 2024). Prior\n106\twork has demonstrated vulnerabilities that arise from ma-\n107\tnipulating agent control flow, including biased tool selection\n108\t(Xu et al., 2025), reordered or omitted safety-critical work-\n109\tflow steps (Jia et al., 2025), and the malicious instructions in-\n110\tjection through untrusted tool-ingested content (Seetharam\n111\tet al., 2025). These attacks can further lead to unintended\n112\ttool invocations, sensitive data exfiltration, and the execu-\n113\ttion of harmful actions (Lin et al., 2026).\n114\tHowever, existing analyses typically treat task execution as\n115\tisolated, one-off sessions, which limits the modeled interac-\n116\ttions between agents and tools and overlooks the persistent\n117\tinfluence of memory in agentic systems. In practice, LLM\n118\tagents store critical information as memory, including user\n119\tprofiles (Packer et al., 2023), user preferences (Chen et al.,\n120\t2024), and historical interaction context (Anwar et al., 2024).\n121\tSuch memory enables personalization across tasks and en-\n122\triches the quality and relevance of generated responses.\n123\tThe persistent presence of memory in agentic systems in-\n124\ttroduces a new security dimension. Specifically, memory is\n125\tretrieved during task execution and directly shapes tool-use\n126\tdecisions. Accordingly, an agent’s control flow over tool se-\n127\tlection and execution evolves from a single-task process into\n128\ta cross-task trajectory, continuously shaped by a recurring\n129\tRead[memory] → Plan[control flow] → Execute[control\n130\tflow]→Write[memory] loop (Wang et al., 2025b).\n131\tThis paper identifies this novel threat fromMemory Control\n132\tFlow Attacks(MCFA) which enables an adversary, without\n133\tprivileged access to system prompts, tool implementations,\n134\tor the memory store, to corrupt an agent’s memory via\n135\tstandard interaction, and then hijack control flow through\n136\tmemory retrieval,forcing unintended tool usagedespite ex-\n137\tplicit safe user instructions (see Figure 1). These control\n138\tflow deviations can present in two main forms, including\n139\ttool-choiceoverridesandreorderedworkflow. Particularly,\n140\t1\n141\t055\n142\t056\n143\t057\n144\t058\n145\t059\n146\t060\n147\t061\n148\t062\n149\t063\n150\t064\n151\t065\n152\t066\n153\t067\n154\t068\n155\t069\n156\t070\n157\t071\n158\t072\n159\t073\n160\t074\n161\t075\n162\t076\n163\t077\n164\t078\n165\t079\n166\t080\n167\t081\n168\t082\n169\t083\n170\t084\n171\t085\n172\t086\n173\t087\n174\t088\n175\t089\n176\t090\n177\t091\n178\t092\n179\t093\n180\t094\n181\t095\n182\t096\n183\t097\n184\t098\n185\t099\n186\t100\n187\t101\n188\t102\n189\t103\n190\t104\n191\t105\n192\t106\n193\t107\n194\t108\n195\t109\n196\tFrom Storage to Steering: Memory Control Flow Attacks on LLM Agents\n197\tFigure 1.Comparison between the standard execution path and our proposed attack. (a) Existing: Standard Path, where the LLM agent\n198\tinvokes tools (A, B, and C) in a predefined, benign sequence to generate correct outputs. (b) Ours: Memory Control Flow Attack, where\n199\tthe agent retrieves malicious context from memory, leading to areorderedworkflow (A → D → C) that skips critical steps (Tool B) and\n200\tultimately produces a malicious output.\n201\ttool-choice overrides possess three characteristics: they\n202\tpropagate across-tasks, exhibitlong -horizon persistence\n203\tand show strongresistance to mitigation.\n204\tTo understand the impact of this vulnerability, we fur-\n205\tther design we develop MEMFLOW, an automated evalua-\n206\ttion framework that systematically identifies and quantifies\n207\tMCFA. The framework operationalizes each attack asinject\n208\tmalicious memory → retrieve memory during benign tasks\n209\t→ audit control flow deviations,and supports evaluation\n210\tacross heterogeneous tasks and long interaction horizons.\n211\tTo evaluate MEMFLOW, we attack state-of-the-art LLMs,\n212\tincludingGPT-5 mini, Claude Sonnet 4.5 and Gemini 2.5\n213\tFlashon real-world tools from two major LLM agent de-\n214\tvelopment frameworks, LangChain and Llama-Index. The\n215\tresults show that over 90% are vulnerable to MCFA. In par-\n216\tticular, MCFA induces tool-choice overrides in 91.7∼100%\n217\tof trials, recorded workflow reordering in 52.8∼69.4%, and\n218\tacross-task scope expansion in 97.2∼100%, with 100% per-\n219\tsistence observed over long horizons. Moreover, we adopt a\n220\tproduction-style mitigation but more than half of the eval-\n221\tuated scenarios still exhibit more than 85% control -flow\n222\tdeviations. These results underscore the prevalence and\n223\tpersistence of memory control flow attacks, highlighting\n224\tcritical security risks that demands immediate attention.\n225\tOur Contributions: ❶ We first identifyMemory Control\n226\tFlow Attacks (MCFA), showing that retrieved memory can\n227\thijack LLM agent’s control flow of tool selection and ex-\n228\tecution via standard interactions. ❷ We then summarize\n229\tcontrol-flow deviations into two main types and discover\n230\tthree main characteristics. ❸ We design an automated evalu-\n231\tation framework MEMFLOWto systematically identifies and\n232\tquantifies MCFA.❹ We comprehensively evaluate MCFA at\n233\tscale against three state-of-the-art LLMs, including GPT-5\n234\tmini, Claude Sonnet 4.5 and Gemini 2.5 Flash on real-world\n235\ttools from LangChain and LlamaIndex.\n236\t2. Related Work\n237\tControl Flow Attacks in Agents.Modern agents rely\n238\ton external tools (Schick et al., 2023), making their be-\n239\thavior governed by the tool -call trace. Accordingly, con-\n240\ttrol flow attacks (Li et al., 2026) aim to manipulate this\n241\ttrace, steering tool selection and invocation sequences to in-\n242\tduce unintended actions. For example, attractive-metadata\n243\tattacks bias tool choice by manipulating tool descriptors\n244\t(Mo et al., 2025); obfuscated prompt attacks induce tool-\n245\tconnected agents to leak sensitive data(Fu et al., 2024);\n246\tTool-mediated prompt injection hijacks tool use via un-\n247\ttrusted tool outputs or tool-ingested content (Zhang et al.,\n248\t2025a). Security analyses further systematize these threats:\n249\tAgent Security Bench catalogs tool-based attack surfaces,\n250\tincluding indirect injections within tool responses (Zhang\n251\tet al., 2025b), while AGENT-SAFETYBENCH benchmarks\n252\tbehavior-level safety risks introduced by tool use (Zhang\n253\tet al., 2024). These threats can also be multimodal. For\n254\texample, adversarial images can trigger harmful tool calls\n255\t(Fu et al., 2023); INJECAGENT shows that indirect injec-\n256\ttions in tool-returned content can drive attacker -intended\n257\ttool calls (Zhan et al., 2024); and third-party API response\n258\tattacks demonstrate how subtle output manipulation can\n259\tpoison downstream agent behavior (Zhao et al., 2024).\n260\tMemory Poisoning and Long-Term Influence.Agent\n261\tmemory is increasingly central to planning and long-horizon\n262\tbehavior, making it a natural target for poisoning attacks\n263\t(Park et al., 2023). Prior work has explored several ways\n264\tadversaries can corrupt or exploit stored information. Agent-\n265\tPoison injects backdoors into agent knowledge bases (Chen\n266\tet al., 2024), while MINJA shows that interaction -driven\n267\tinjections can become self-reinforcing as corrupted prece-\n268\tdents accumulate over time (Dong et al., 2025). BadChain\n269\tdemonstrates that poisoning a small set of reasoning exem-\n270\tplars can create triggerable prompt-only backdoors (Xiang\n271\tet al., 2024). Beyond behavioral manipulation, MEXTRA\n272\t2\n273\t110\n274\t111\n275\t112\n276\t113\n277\t114\n278\t115\n279\t116\n280\t117\n281\t118\n282\t119\n283\t120\n284\t121\n285\t122\n286\t123\n287\t124\n288\t125\n289\t126\n290\t127\n291\t128\n292\t129\n293\t130\n294\t131\n295\t132\n296\t133\n297\t134\n298\t135\n299\t136\n300\t137"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e6527c94-f67f-47a9-849d-c5fe31116d02","uuid":"bef4e924-c800-48c1-a8f6-4aae77491ff1","timestamp":"2026-04-25T19:59:56.133Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/papers/e5e5467c-27e4-495d-9c20-f078ae58431e.txt","content":"000\n001\n002\n003\n004\n005\n006\n007\n008\n009\n010\n011\n012\n013\n014\n015\n016\n017\n018\n019\n020\n021\n022\n023\n024\n025\n026\n027\n028\n029\n030\n031\n032\n033\n034\n035\n036\n037\n038\n039\n040\n041\n042\n043\n044\n045\n046\n047\n048\n049\n050\n051\n052\n053\n054\nFrom Storage to Steering:\nMemory Control Flow Attacks on LLM Agents\nAnonymous Authors1\nAbstract\nModern agentic systems allow Large Language\nModel (LLM) agents to tackle complex tasks\nthrough extensive tool usage, forming structured\ncontrol flows of tool selection and execution. Ex-\nisting security analyses often treat these control\nflows as ephemeral, one-off sessions, overlooking\nthe persistent influence of memory. This paper\nidentifies a new threat from Memory Control Flow\nAttacks (MCFA) that memory retrieval can dom-\ninate the control flow,forcing unintended tool\nusageeven against explicit user instructions and\ninducingpersistent behavioral deviationsacross\ntasks. To understand the impact of this vulnerabil-\nity, we further design MEMFLOW, an automated\nevaluation framework that systematically identi-\nfies and quantifies MCFA across heterogeneous\ntasks and long interaction horizons. To evaluate\nMEMFLOW, we attack state-of-the-art LLMs, in-\ncludingGPT-5 mini, Claude Sonnet 4.5 and Gem-\nini 2.5 Flashon real-world tools from two major\nLLM agent development frameworks, LangChain\nand LlamaIndex. The results show that in general\nover90%trials are vulnerable to MCFA even un-\nder strict safety constraints, highlighting critical\nsecurity risks that demand immediate attention.\n1. Introduction\nIn an agentic system empowered by Large Language Models\n(LLM) (OpenAI, 2025; Google, 2025; Anthropic, 2025),\neach LLM agent has substantially improved their ability to\nsolve complex tasks through access to an increasing number\nof tools (Fu et al., 2024; Patil et al., 2025). For example,\nwhen given a restaurant recommendation task, an LLM\nagent may first invoke a web search tool to identify highly\nrated nearby restaurants and then call a mapping service to\n1Anonymous Institution, Anonymous City, Anonymous Region,\nAnonymous Country. Correspondence to: Anonymous Author\n<anon.email@domain.com>.\nPreliminary work. Under review by the International Conference\non Machine Learning (ICML). Do not distribute.\nplan optimal routes to the selected candidates. As agents\nincreasingly coordinate multiple tools to achieve a single\nobjective, their behavior naturally induces structuredcontrol\nflowsover tool selection and execution (Li et al., 2026).\nThe presence of control flows over tool selection and execu-\ntion in LLM-powered agentic systems introduces a series\nof new security challenges (Debenedetti et al., 2024). Prior\nwork has demonstrated vulnerabilities that arise from ma-\nnipulating agent control flow, including biased tool selection\n(Xu et al., 2025), reordered or omitted safety-critical work-\nflow steps (Jia et al., 2025), and the malicious instructions in-\njection through untrusted tool-ingested content (Seetharam\net al., 2025). These attacks can further lead to unintended\ntool invocations, sensitive data exfiltration, and the execu-\ntion of harmful actions (Lin et al., 2026).\nHowever, existing analyses typically treat task execution as\nisolated, one-off sessions, which limits the modeled interac-\ntions between agents and tools and overlooks the persistent\ninfluence of memory in agentic systems. In practice, LLM\nagents store critical information as memory, including user\nprofiles (Packer et al., 2023), user preferences (Chen et al.,\n2024), and historical interaction context (Anwar et al., 2024).\nSuch memory enables personalization across tasks and en-\nriches the quality and relevance of generated responses.\nThe persistent presence of memory in agentic systems in-\ntroduces a new security dimension. Specifically, memory is\nretrieved during task execution and directly shapes tool-use\ndecisions. Accordingly, an agent’s control flow over tool se-\nlection and execution evolves from a single-task process into\na cross-task trajectory, continuously shaped by a recurring\nRead[memory] → Plan[control flow] → Execute[control\nflow]→Write[memory] loop (Wang et al., 2025b).\nThis paper identifies this novel threat fromMemory Control\nFlow Attacks(MCFA) which enables an adversary, without\nprivileged access to system prompts, tool implementations,\nor the memory store, to corrupt an agent’s memory via\nstandard interaction, and then hijack control flow through\nmemory retrieval,forcing unintended tool usagedespite ex-\nplicit safe user instructions (see Figure 1). These control\nflow deviations can present in two main forms, including\ntool-choiceoverridesandreorderedworkflow. Particularly,\n1\n055\n056\n057\n058\n059\n060\n061\n062\n063\n064\n065\n066\n067\n068\n069\n070\n071\n072\n073\n074\n075\n076\n077\n078\n079\n080\n081\n082\n083\n084\n085\n086\n087\n088\n089\n090\n091\n092\n093\n094\n095\n096\n097\n098\n099\n100\n101\n102\n103\n104\n105\n106\n107\n108\n109\nFrom Storage to Steering: Memory Control Flow Attacks on LLM Agents\nFigure 1.Comparison between the standard execution path and our proposed attack. (a) Existing: Standard Path, where the LLM agent\ninvokes tools (A, B, and C) in a predefined, benign sequence to generate correct outputs. (b) Ours: Memory Control Flow Attack, where\nthe agent retrieves malicious context from memory, leading to areorderedworkflow (A → D → C) that skips critical steps (Tool B) and\nultimately produces a malicious output.\ntool-choice overrides possess three characteristics: they\npropagate across-tasks, exhibitlong -horizon persistence\nand show strongresistance to mitigation.\nTo understand the impact of this vulnerability, we fur-\nther design we develop MEMFLOW, an automated evalua-\ntion framework that systematically identifies and quantifies\nMCFA. The framework operationalizes each attack asinject\nmalicious memory → retrieve memory during benign tasks\n→ audit control flow deviations,and supports evaluation\nacross heterogeneous tasks and long interaction horizons.\nTo evaluate MEMFLOW, we attack state-of-the-art LLMs,\nincludingGPT-5 mini, Claude Sonnet 4.5 and Gemini 2.5\nFlashon real-world tools from two major LLM agent de-\nvelopment frameworks, LangChain and Llama-Index. The\nresults show that over 90% are vulnerable to MCFA. In par-\nticular, MCFA induces tool-choice overrides in 91.7∼100%\nof trials, recorded workflow reordering in 52.8∼69.4%, and\nacross-task scope expansion in 97.2∼100%, with 100% per-\nsistence observed over long horizons. Moreover, we adopt a\nproduction-style mitigation but more than half of the eval-\nuated scenarios still exhibit more than 85% control -flow\ndeviations. These results underscore the prevalence and\npersistence of memory control flow attacks, highlighting\ncritical security risks that demands immediate attention.\nOur Contributions: ❶ We first identifyMemory Control\nFlow Attacks (MCFA), showing that retrieved memory can\nhijack LLM agent’s control flow of tool selection and ex-\necution via standard interactions. ❷ We then summarize\ncontrol-flow deviations into two main types and discover\nthree main characteristics. ❸ We design an automated evalu-\nation framework MEMFLOWto systematically identifies and\nquantifies MCFA.❹ We comprehensively evaluate MCFA at\nscale against three state-of-the-art LLMs, including GPT-5\nmini, Claude Sonnet 4.5 and Gemini 2.5 Flash on real-world\ntools from LangChain and LlamaIndex.\n2. Related Work\nControl Flow Attacks in Agents.Modern agents rely\non external tools (Schick et al., 2023), making their be-\nhavior governed by the tool -call trace. Accordingly, con-\ntrol flow attacks (Li et al., 2026) aim to manipulate this\ntrace, steering tool selection and invocation sequences to in-\nduce unintended actions. For example, attractive-metadata\nattacks bias tool choice by manipulating tool descriptors\n(Mo et al., 2025); obfuscated prompt attacks induce tool-\nconnected agents to leak sensitive data(Fu et al., 2024);\nTool-mediated prompt injection hijacks tool use via un-\ntrusted tool outputs or tool-ingested content (Zhang et al.,\n2025a). Security analyses further systematize these threats:\nAgent Security Bench catalogs tool-based attack surfaces,\nincluding indirect injections within tool responses (Zhang\net al., 2025b), while AGENT-SAFETYBENCH benchmarks\nbehavior-level safety risks introduced by tool use (Zhang\net al., 2024). These threats can also be multimodal. For\nexample, adversarial images can trigger harmful tool calls\n(Fu et al., 2023); INJECAGENT shows that indirect injec-\ntions in tool-returned content can drive attacker -intended\ntool calls (Zhan et al., 2024); and third-party API response\nattacks demonstrate how subtle output manipulation can\npoison downstream agent behavior (Zhao et al., 2024).\nMemory Poisoning and Long-Term Influence.Agent\nmemory is increasingly central to planning and long-horizon\nbehavior, making it a natural target for poisoning attacks\n(Park et al., 2023). Prior work has explored several ways\nadversaries can corrupt or exploit stored information. Agent-\nPoison injects backdoors into agent knowledge bases (Chen\net al., 2024), while MINJA shows that interaction -driven\ninjections can become self-reinforcing as corrupted prece-\ndents accumulate over time (Dong et al., 2025). BadChain\ndemonstrates that poisoning a small set of reasoning exem-\nplars can create triggerable prompt-only backdoors (Xiang\net al., 2024). Beyond behavioral manipulation, MEXTRA\n2\n110\n111\n112\n113\n114\n115\n116\n117\n118\n119\n120\n121\n122\n123\n124\n125\n126\n127\n128\n129\n130\n131\n132\n133\n134\n135\n136\n137","numLines":300,"startLine":1,"totalLines":2433}}}
