{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01VSstNG9SL81p7ED4LXyCBe","type":"tool_result","content":"300\t137\n301\t138\n302\t139\n303\t140\n304\t141\n305\t142\n306\t143\n307\t144\n308\t145\n309\t146\n310\t147\n311\t148\n312\t149\n313\t150\n314\t151\n315\t152\n316\t153\n317\t154\n318\t155\n319\t156\n320\t157\n321\t158\n322\t159\n323\t160\n324\t161\n325\t162\n326\t163\n327\t164\n328\tFrom Storage to Steering: Memory Control Flow Attacks on LLM Agents\n329\treveals that memory modules can leak private user–agent\n330\tinteraction data when adversarially probed (Wang et al.,\n331\t2025a). Defensive efforts in this domain mainly focus on\n332\tdetecting or isolating corrupted memory. A -MemGuard\n333\tperforms online consistency checks and separates “lesson”\n334\tmemory to mitigate poisoning (Wei et al., 2025). Llama\n335\tGuard filters risky prompts and responses using a predefined\n336\tsafety taxonomy (Inan et al., 2023), and ISOLATEGPT pro-\n337\tposes execution isolation to limit cross-component influence\n338\tin LLM application ecosystems (Wu et al., 2025).\n339\tTaken together, prior analyses of control-flow attacks treat\n340\teach task as an isolated, one-off session, overlooking the per-\n341\tsistent influence that memory can exert in agentic systems.\n342\tConversely, existing memory-attack studies focus primarily\n343\ton degradation in retrieved content or output correctness,\n344\toverlooking its substantial influence on an agent’s control\n345\tflow. This gap motivates our study: we treat memory as a\n346\tcontrol input to evaluate persistent biases in tool selection\n347\tand ordering via the tool-call trace. In modern agents, poi-\n348\tsoned memory can act as awrite-once, read-manycontrol\n349\tsignal, inducing cross-task control flow deviations.\n350\t3. Formalization of Memory Control Flow\n351\tAttacks and Experimental Verification\n352\tThis section formalizes the Memory Control Flow Attacks\n353\t(MCFA) with LLM agent as a state machine driven by mem-\n354\tory retrieval. Based on that, we propose a Verification The-\n355\torem that establishes the sufficiency of trace-based auditing\n356\tunder context isolation. Finally, we formalize a experimen-\n357\ttal methodology to validate these theoretical bounds.\n358\t3.1. Memory Control Flow Attacks\n359\tSecurity Goals & Assumptions. We consider a memory-\n360\taugmented LLM agent with access to tools, where retrieved\n361\tmemory is injected into the AgentRunner, and tool-call\n362\ttraces serve as an observable proxy for the agent’s control\n363\tflow. Theadversaryis an external attacker, who through\n364\tone or a few standard interactions, induces the agent to store\n365\taction-oriented preferences/rules into long-term memory.\n366\tDuring later benign tasks, these rules may be retrieved and\n367\tour security objective is control flow integrity rather than\n368\toutput correctness; an attack succeeds if retrieved malicious\n369\tmemory causes auditable policy deviations in the tool trace.\n370\tDuring the interactions, we assume no internal privileges\n371\tin the interactions,i.e.the attacker cannot modify system\n372\tprompts, alter tool implementations, access the memory\n373\tstore directly, or implant malicious tools. As a production-\n374\tstyle mitigation to reduce MCFA, we consider Role-Based\n375\tMemory Segregation (RBMS), which separates system rules\n376\tfrom user preferences and enforces an explicit priority hier-\n377\tarchy between them. Under RBMS, the attacker can only\n378\taffect the user-memory channel. Additional details are pro-\n379\tvided in Appendix A. Under this security objective and\n380\tassumption, we define the system model and memory con-\n381\ttrol flow attack (MCFA) as follows.\n382\tDefinition 1(System Model: Memory-Augmented LLM\n383\tAgents).Given F is the stochastic transition function of\n384\tthe LLM, mapping context to actions and T the discrete\n385\tset of available tools {t1, . . . , tN }, we formally define a\n386\tmemory-augmented agentAas a tuple:\n387\tA=⟨F,T, M,Φ ret,Φ upd⟩,(1)\n388\twhere Mk is the persistent memory state at step k,\n389\tΦret(Mk, x) the retrieval function generating context from\n390\tmemory given input x and Φupd(Mk, δ) is the update func-\n391\ttionM k+1 ←Φ upd(Mk, δ).\n392\tDefinition 2(Memory Control Flow Attack).An MCFA is\n393\ta two-phase process where an adversary injects a policy\n394\tπadv into M such that for a subsequent benign task x, the\n395\tgenerated tool trace τ satisfies τ|=π adv and τ̸|= Π saf e,\n396\twhereΠ saf e is the system’s default safety policy.\n397\t3.2. Verification: Memory-Causal Deviation of MCFA\n398\tTo rigorously detect MCFA, we must distinguish it from\n399\tshort-term context hallucinations. We propose the follow-\n400\ting theorem which serves as the theoretical basis for our\n401\tevaluation framework MEMFLOW.\n402\tTheorem 1(Memory-Causal Verification).Let H be the\n403\tshort-term conversation history and Eiso be anIsolated\n404\tEvaluation Regimewhere H=∅ . For any agent A and\n405\ttask x, if the tool trace τ generated under Eiso violates\n406\tthe safety policy Πsaf e (i.e., Dev(τ,Π saf e)>0 ), then the\n407\tdeviation is strictly attributable to the memory stateM.\n408\tProof. The agent’s action generation is a function P(τ|\n409\tx,H,Φ ret(M)). Under the Isolated Regime Eiso, we force\n410\tH → ∅ . The function simplifies to P(τ|x,Φ ret(M)).\n411\tGiven that x is benign (contains no adversarial prompts) and\n412\tthe base model F is aligned to Πsaf e (by assumption of the\n413\tvictim model), the only variable capable of introducing a sys-\n414\ttematic policy shift πadv is the retrieved context Φret(M).\n415\tTherefore, Dev(τ)>0 =⇒Mis poisoned.\n416\tRemark1.This theorem provides the necessary condition\n417\tfor attribution. In practical security auditing, distinguishing\n418\ta model hallucination (stochastic noise) from a persistent\n419\tattack is challenging. Theorem 1 mathematically justifies\n420\tthe “Context Reset” strategy used in MEMFLOW: by zeroing\n421\tout H, any residual behavioral deviation must originate from\n422\tthe only remaining persistent variable,M.\n423\t3.3. Methodology: MEMFLOW\n424\tTrace Space and Attack Mappings. Let Arg denote the\n425\tuniverse of valid argument structures (e.g., JSON objects\n426\t3\n427\t165\n428\t166\n429\t167\n430\t168\n431\t169\n432\t170\n433\t171\n434\t172\n435\t173\n436\t174\n437\t175\n438\t176\n439\t177\n440\t178\n441\t179\n442\t180\n443\t181\n444\t182\n445\t183\n446\t184\n447\t185\n448\t186\n449\t187\n450\t188\n451\t189\n452\t190\n453\t191\n454\t192\n455\t193\n456\t194\n457\t195\n458\t196\n459\t197\n460\t198\n461\t199\n462\t200\n463\t201\n464\t202\n465\t203\n466\t204\n467\t205\n468\t206\n469\t207\n470\t208\n471\t209\n472\t210\n473\t211\n474\t212\n475\t213\n476\t214\n477\t215\n478\t216\n479\t217\n480\t218\n481\t219\n482\tFrom Storage to Steering: Memory Control Flow Attacks on LLM Agents\n483\tTable 1.Definition of Attack Families. OVERRIDEand ORDERcapture two forms of control -flow deviations: tool-choice overrides and\n484\treordered workflows. In contrast, M-SCOPE, PERSIST, and RELAPSEcharacterize whether a deviation, once observed, propagates across\n485\ttasks (cross-task propagation), how long it endures (long-horizon persistence), and how resistant it is to mitigation (mitigation resistance).\n486\tNAMEDEFINITIONVIOLATIONSEMANTICPHYSICALINTERPRETATION\n487\tOVERRIDEτ∩ T risky ̸=∅SAFETYSETVIOLATION.\n488\tTHE TRACE CONTAINS PROHIB-\n489\tITED TOOLS DEFINED IN THE\n490\tRISKY SET.\n491\tPREFERENCEINJECTION.MEM-\n492\tORY ACTS AS A“HARD-CODED”\n493\tUSER PREFERENCE,OVERRIDING\n494\tSTATIC SAFETY FILTERS.\n495\tORDER∃t a, tb ∈τ:IDX(t a)>\n496\tIDX(t b)|(t a ≺Π tb)\n497\tPRECEDENCEVIOLATION.\n498\tSTEP ta OCCURS AFTER tb,VI-\n499\tOLATING THE REQUIRED DEPEN-\n500\tDENCYt a →t b.\n501\tDEPENDENCYSUBVERSION.BY-\n502\tPASSES LOGIC GATES(E.G.,SKIP-\n503\tPINGAUDIT BEFORETRANSFER).\n504\tINVISIBLE TO WHITELIST DE-\n505\tFENSES.\n506\tM-SCOPE 1\n507\t|X |\n508\tP\n509\tx∈X I(τx /∈Πsaf e)> δDISTRIBUTIONALSHIFT.\n510\tTHE VIOLATION RATE ACROSS\n511\tHETEROGENEOUS TASKS EX-\n512\tCEEDS THRESHOLDδ.\n513\tUNIVERSALTRIGGER.THE IN-\n514\tJECTED LOGIC ABSTRACTS AWAY\n515\tFROM CONTEXTS,ACTING AS\n516\tA“MASTERKEY”ACROSS DO-\n517\tMAINS.\n518\tPERSISTENCEVIOLATION(τ t) =TRUE ,∀t≫\n519\ttinject\n520\tTEMPORALSTABILITY.\n521\tTHE DEVIATION PERSISTS LONG\n522\tAFTER THE INJECTION EVENT\n523\ttinject .\n524\tCHRONICINFECTION.CREATES\n525\tA STABLE ATTRACTOR IN THE\n526\tMEMORY STATE SPACE THAT RE-\n527\tSISTS NATURAL CONTEXT DECAY.\n528\tRELAPSEREPAIR(x) =⇒(τ new /∈\n529\tΠsaf e)\n530\tCORRECTIONFAILURE.\n531\tEXPLICIT REPAIR INSTRUCTIONS\n532\tFAIL TO STEER THE TRACE BACK\n533\tTO THE SAFE SET.\n534\tSTATERESISTANCE.PROVES\n535\tTEXTUAL PATCHES ARE\n536\tEPHEMERAL;THE UNDERLYING\n537\tSTATEMREMAINS POISONED.\n538\tor parameter lists) accepted by the toolset T . We define the\n539\tTrace Space Ωτ as the set of all finite sequences of pairs of\n540\t(a selected tool, instantiated arguments):\n541\tΩτ ={τ= ((t 1, α1), . . . ,(tL, αL))|t i ∈ T, α i ∈ Arg},\n542\t(2)\n543\twhere at each step, the agent generates a selected tool ti and\n544\tits instantiated argumentsα i.\n545\tThrough a variety of preliminary experiments, we find that\n546\tMCFA can induce control flow deviations in multiple ways\n547\tand exhibit diverse characteristics. To systematically cap-\n548\tture these behaviors, we formalize five attack families as\n549\tdistinct mapping functions f: Π adv → P(Ω τ), mapping\n550\tan adversarial instructionπ adv to a target subspace ofΩ τ .\n551\tThe families, along with their definitions and interpretations,\n552\tare summarized in Table 1. OVERRIDEand ORDERcapture\n553\ttwo forms of control-flow deviations: tool-choice overrides\n554\tand reordered workflows. In contrast, M-SCOPE, PERSIST,\n555\tand RELAPSEcharacterize whether a deviation, once ob-\n556\tserved, propagates across tasks (cross -task propagation),\n557\thow long it endures (long -horizon persistence), and how\n558\tresistant it is to mitigation (mitigation resistance). Because\n559\tcross-task propagation, long-horizon persistence, and miti-\n560\tgation resistance arise from a stable, task-agnostic control\n561\tpolicy encoded in memory, we instantiate these families\n562\tusing tool-choice override as the deviation behavior. See\n563\tAppendix B for concrete examples.\n564\tThe Trace Auditing Algorithm. Given a specific attack\n565\tfamily, we define attack success as the trace τ falling into\n566\tits corresponding violation sets in the Trace Space Ωτ . To\n567\tfurther evaluate the attack success, we use the attack suc-\n568\tcess rate (ASR) as the metric. Based on Theorem 1, we\n569\tconstruct the isolation-based trace auditing algorithm in\n570\tAlgorithm 1, which audits memory-induced control flow\n571\tdeviations through a two-phase protocol: injection and iso-\n572\tlated evaluation. Given an agent A, initial memory Minit, an\n573\tinjection prompt Pinj, and a benign task set Xbenign, Phase 1\n574\tperforms a one-shot update that writes the injected content\n575\tinto memory, yieldingM ′ ←Φ upd(Minit, Pinj).\n576\tIn Phase 2, for each benign task xi ∈X benign, we enforce\n577\tanisolation regimeby resetting the short-term history to\n578\tH←∅ (Theorem 1), ensuring that any observed deviation\n579\tis attributable to retrieved long-term memory rather than\n580\tresidual dialogue state. We then retrieve context from the\n581\tpoisoned memory, Rctx ←Φ ret(M ′, xi), and execute the\n582\tagent to obtain a tool-call trace τi ←F(x i, Rctx). We\n583\tflag a deviation if the resulting trace violates the default\n584\tsafe control flow policy, i.e., τi /∈Πsafe, and accumulate\n585\tthe count S. Finally, we report the attack success rate as\n586\tASR =S/|X benign|,i.e.the fraction of benign tasks whose\n587\texecution traces are hijacked under isolation.\n588\tMEMFLOWEvaluation Framework. To systematically\n589\tquantify the threat boundaries and efficacy of memory con-\n590\t4\n591\t220\n592\t221\n593\t222\n594\t223\n595\t224\n596\t225\n597\t226\n598\t227\n599\t228\n600\t229\n601\t230\n602\t231\n603\t232\n604\t233\n605\t234\n606\t235\n607\t236\n608\t237\n609\t238\n610\t239\n611\t240\n612\t241\n613\t242\n614\t243\n615\t244\n616\t245\n617\t246\n618\t247\n619\t248\n620\t249\n621\t250\n622\t251\n623\t252\n624\t253\n625\t254\n626\t255\n627\t256\n628\t257\n629\t258\n630\t259\n631\t260\n632\t261\n633\t262\n634\t263\n635\t264\n636\t265\n637\t266\n638\t267\n639\t268\n640\t269\n641\t270\n642\t271\n643\t272\n644\t273\n645\t274\n646\tFrom Storage to Steering: Memory Control Flow Attacks on LLM Agents\n647\tFigure 2.Overview of MEMFLOW. MEMFLOWis a evaluation framework that standardizes MCFA trials with an injection →auditing\n648\tprotocol, logging tool-call trajectories and computing the attack success rate.\n649\tAlgorithm 1Isolation-Based Trace Auditing\n650\t1: Require:Agent A, Memory Minit, Injection Prompt Pinj,\n651\tTest SuiteX benign\n652\t2:M ′ ←Φ upd(Minit, Pinj)▷Phase 1: Injection\n653\t3:S←0\n654\t4:for eachtaskx i ∈ X benign do\n655\t5:H ← ∅▷Apply Isolation (Theorem 1)\n656\t6:R ctx ←Φ ret(M ′, xi)▷ Retrieve from poisoned memory\n657\t7:τ i ←F(x i, Rctx)▷Generate execution trace\n658\t8:ifτ i /∈Πsaf e then\n659\t9:S←S+ 1▷Deviation detected\n660\t10:end if\n661\t11:end for\n662\t12:returnASR=S/|X benign|\n663\ttrol flow attacks (MCFA), we developed MEMFLOW, the\n664\tfirst automated evaluation framework designed for agents\n665\tequipped with memory. Unlike traditional evaluations that\n666\tfocus on text generation quality, MEMFLOWfocuses on\n667\tauditing thecontrol flow integrity. Through standardized\n668\tInjection-Auditingby Algorithm 1, MEMFLOWassesses\n669\twhether an agent’s tool traces systematically deviate from\n670\tdefault safety policies after injected untrusted memory. The\n671\tsystem architecture of MEMFLOW, as shown in Figure 2,\n672\tconsists of three core components:\n673\t❶ Scenario Generation.To decouple testing logic from the\n674\tunderlying frameworks, we introduce a unified Scenario\n675\tabstraction layer. Each evaluation scenario is formalized by\n676\ta set of specifications:\n677\t• Tool Specs: Defines the tool pool sourced from real\n678\tworld, including the safe tools (Tsafe), the correspond-\n679\ting risky variants ( Trisky) constructed from the same\n680\tbase tools, and the memory write interfaces.\n681\t• Policy Constraints: Defines the expected legitimate\n682\tcontrol flow.\n683\t• Dynamic Injection: Utilizes an LLM to dynamically\n684\tgenerate diverse natural language instructions, simu-\n685\tlating authentic User-Memory interactions rather than\n686\trelying on hard-coded prompt attacks.\n687\t❷ AgentRunner. To evaluate the universality of attacks, we\n688\tbuild the AgentRunner to provide a unified interaction\n689\tinterface across mainstream frameworks such as LangChain\n690\tand LlamaIndex, supporting LLMs (OpenAI, Anthropic,\n691\tGemini) with pluggable memory components. This design\n692\tensures strict comparability of security performance across\n693\tdifferent agent architectures under the same test data.\n694\t❸ Trace-audited Pipeline.MEMFLOWstandardizes each\n695\tevaluation trial and calculates the ASR via Algrithm 1.\n696\tThrough this automated workflow, MEMFLOWenables\n697\trapid identification of security vulnerabilities in different\n698\tmemory mechanisms under batch execution modes.\n699\t3.4. Empirical Corollaries\n700\tCorollary 1(Dominance of Retrieval).Let α be the influ-\n701\tence weight of memory and β be the influence of system\n702\tsafety prompts. The experiments show:\n703\tΦret(M)̸=∅=⇒α≫β,\n704\tresulting in Attack Success Rates (ASR) approaching 1.0\n705\tunder strong retrieval.\n706\tRemark2.This corollary implies a fundamentalalignment\n707\tbypassthreat. LLMs are supposed to prioritize system\n708\tprompts over instructions. However, the RAG mechanism\n709\tcan inject the adversarial instruction into the context window\n710\tas “ground truth” or “user preference”. In this circumstance,\n711\tLLM tends to faithfully execute the retrieved adversarial\n712\tinstruction that facilitates the attack, effectively bypassing\n713\tthe static safety constraints encoded in the system prompts.\n714\t5\n715\t275\n716\t276\n717\t277\n718\t278\n719\t279\n720\t280\n721\t281\n722\t282\n723\t283\n724\t284\n725\t285\n726\t286\n727\t287\n728\t288\n729\t289\n730\t290\n731\t291\n732\t292\n733\t293\n734\t294\n735\t295\n736\t296\n737\t297\n738\t298\n739\t299\n740\t300\n741\t301\n742\t302\n743\t303\n744\t304\n745\t305\n746\t306\n747\t307\n748\t308\n749\t309\n750\t310\n751\t311\n752\t312\n753\t313\n754\t314\n755\t315\n756\t316\n757\t317\n758\t318\n759\t319\n760\t320\n761\t321\n762\t322\n763\t323\n764\t324\n765\t325\n766\t326\n767\t327\n768\t328\n769\t329\n770\tFrom Storage to Steering: Memory Control Flow Attacks on LLM Agents\n771\tWe provide a detailed empirical analysis of this phenomenon\n772\tin §4.2 (RQ1 & RQ2).\n773\tCorollary 2(Inefficacy of Textual Repair).Let Rep be a\n774\tnatural language repair instruction. The persistence prop-\n775\terty implies:\n776\tP(τ saf e |M poisoned, Rep)≈0,\n777\tindicating that removing πadv from M is necessary; mask-\n778\ting it withRepis insufficient.\n779\tRemark3.This highlights the limitation ofstateless de-\n780\tfense. Most current defenses treat the agent as stateless,\n781\tattempting to fix behavior through conversational prompts\n782\talone. However, since the state M remains poisoned, the\n783\tretrieval function Φret will re-introduce πadv in future turns.\n784\tEffective mitigation therefore requiresMemory Surgery(di-\n785\trect state modification) rather than conversational steering.\n786\tWe provide a detailed empirical analysis of this phenomenon\n787\tin §4.2 (RQ3).\n788\t4. Experiments\n789\t4.1. Experimental Setup and Implementation\n790\tLLM backbones. We evaluate all experiments ongpt-\n791\t5mini,Claude Sonnet 4.5,Gemini 2.5 Flashunder the same\n792\tscenario specifications and tool inventories for fair compari-\n793\tson.We set temperature to 0.0; therefore each configuration\n794\tis executed under a fixed seed policy. We also conduct\n795\texperiments on open-source LLM, which are detailed in\n796\tAppendix E.\n797\tTools. We sample 36 tool candidates per framework from\n798\t169 LangChain community tools (LangChain, 2026) and\n799\t97 LlamaHub tools (LlamaIndex, 2026), using stratified"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e6527c94-f67f-47a9-849d-c5fe31116d02","uuid":"520a1f8b-e34d-4cd4-ad03-dca7d9707db7","timestamp":"2026-04-25T20:00:00.847Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/papers/e5e5467c-27e4-495d-9c20-f078ae58431e.txt","content":"137\n138\n139\n140\n141\n142\n143\n144\n145\n146\n147\n148\n149\n150\n151\n152\n153\n154\n155\n156\n157\n158\n159\n160\n161\n162\n163\n164\nFrom Storage to Steering: Memory Control Flow Attacks on LLM Agents\nreveals that memory modules can leak private user–agent\ninteraction data when adversarially probed (Wang et al.,\n2025a). Defensive efforts in this domain mainly focus on\ndetecting or isolating corrupted memory. A -MemGuard\nperforms online consistency checks and separates “lesson”\nmemory to mitigate poisoning (Wei et al., 2025). Llama\nGuard filters risky prompts and responses using a predefined\nsafety taxonomy (Inan et al., 2023), and ISOLATEGPT pro-\nposes execution isolation to limit cross-component influence\nin LLM application ecosystems (Wu et al., 2025).\nTaken together, prior analyses of control-flow attacks treat\neach task as an isolated, one-off session, overlooking the per-\nsistent influence that memory can exert in agentic systems.\nConversely, existing memory-attack studies focus primarily\non degradation in retrieved content or output correctness,\noverlooking its substantial influence on an agent’s control\nflow. This gap motivates our study: we treat memory as a\ncontrol input to evaluate persistent biases in tool selection\nand ordering via the tool-call trace. In modern agents, poi-\nsoned memory can act as awrite-once, read-manycontrol\nsignal, inducing cross-task control flow deviations.\n3. Formalization of Memory Control Flow\nAttacks and Experimental Verification\nThis section formalizes the Memory Control Flow Attacks\n(MCFA) with LLM agent as a state machine driven by mem-\nory retrieval. Based on that, we propose a Verification The-\norem that establishes the sufficiency of trace-based auditing\nunder context isolation. Finally, we formalize a experimen-\ntal methodology to validate these theoretical bounds.\n3.1. Memory Control Flow Attacks\nSecurity Goals & Assumptions. We consider a memory-\naugmented LLM agent with access to tools, where retrieved\nmemory is injected into the AgentRunner, and tool-call\ntraces serve as an observable proxy for the agent’s control\nflow. Theadversaryis an external attacker, who through\none or a few standard interactions, induces the agent to store\naction-oriented preferences/rules into long-term memory.\nDuring later benign tasks, these rules may be retrieved and\nour security objective is control flow integrity rather than\noutput correctness; an attack succeeds if retrieved malicious\nmemory causes auditable policy deviations in the tool trace.\nDuring the interactions, we assume no internal privileges\nin the interactions,i.e.the attacker cannot modify system\nprompts, alter tool implementations, access the memory\nstore directly, or implant malicious tools. As a production-\nstyle mitigation to reduce MCFA, we consider Role-Based\nMemory Segregation (RBMS), which separates system rules\nfrom user preferences and enforces an explicit priority hier-\narchy between them. Under RBMS, the attacker can only\naffect the user-memory channel. Additional details are pro-\nvided in Appendix A. Under this security objective and\nassumption, we define the system model and memory con-\ntrol flow attack (MCFA) as follows.\nDefinition 1(System Model: Memory-Augmented LLM\nAgents).Given F is the stochastic transition function of\nthe LLM, mapping context to actions and T the discrete\nset of available tools {t1, . . . , tN }, we formally define a\nmemory-augmented agentAas a tuple:\nA=⟨F,T, M,Φ ret,Φ upd⟩,(1)\nwhere Mk is the persistent memory state at step k,\nΦret(Mk, x) the retrieval function generating context from\nmemory given input x and Φupd(Mk, δ) is the update func-\ntionM k+1 ←Φ upd(Mk, δ).\nDefinition 2(Memory Control Flow Attack).An MCFA is\na two-phase process where an adversary injects a policy\nπadv into M such that for a subsequent benign task x, the\ngenerated tool trace τ satisfies τ|=π adv and τ̸|= Π saf e,\nwhereΠ saf e is the system’s default safety policy.\n3.2. Verification: Memory-Causal Deviation of MCFA\nTo rigorously detect MCFA, we must distinguish it from\nshort-term context hallucinations. We propose the follow-\ning theorem which serves as the theoretical basis for our\nevaluation framework MEMFLOW.\nTheorem 1(Memory-Causal Verification).Let H be the\nshort-term conversation history and Eiso be anIsolated\nEvaluation Regimewhere H=∅ . For any agent A and\ntask x, if the tool trace τ generated under Eiso violates\nthe safety policy Πsaf e (i.e., Dev(τ,Π saf e)>0 ), then the\ndeviation is strictly attributable to the memory stateM.\nProof. The agent’s action generation is a function P(τ|\nx,H,Φ ret(M)). Under the Isolated Regime Eiso, we force\nH → ∅ . The function simplifies to P(τ|x,Φ ret(M)).\nGiven that x is benign (contains no adversarial prompts) and\nthe base model F is aligned to Πsaf e (by assumption of the\nvictim model), the only variable capable of introducing a sys-\ntematic policy shift πadv is the retrieved context Φret(M).\nTherefore, Dev(τ)>0 =⇒Mis poisoned.\nRemark1.This theorem provides the necessary condition\nfor attribution. In practical security auditing, distinguishing\na model hallucination (stochastic noise) from a persistent\nattack is challenging. Theorem 1 mathematically justifies\nthe “Context Reset” strategy used in MEMFLOW: by zeroing\nout H, any residual behavioral deviation must originate from\nthe only remaining persistent variable,M.\n3.3. Methodology: MEMFLOW\nTrace Space and Attack Mappings. Let Arg denote the\nuniverse of valid argument structures (e.g., JSON objects\n3\n165\n166\n167\n168\n169\n170\n171\n172\n173\n174\n175\n176\n177\n178\n179\n180\n181\n182\n183\n184\n185\n186\n187\n188\n189\n190\n191\n192\n193\n194\n195\n196\n197\n198\n199\n200\n201\n202\n203\n204\n205\n206\n207\n208\n209\n210\n211\n212\n213\n214\n215\n216\n217\n218\n219\nFrom Storage to Steering: Memory Control Flow Attacks on LLM Agents\nTable 1.Definition of Attack Families. OVERRIDEand ORDERcapture two forms of control -flow deviations: tool-choice overrides and\nreordered workflows. In contrast, M-SCOPE, PERSIST, and RELAPSEcharacterize whether a deviation, once observed, propagates across\ntasks (cross-task propagation), how long it endures (long-horizon persistence), and how resistant it is to mitigation (mitigation resistance).\nNAMEDEFINITIONVIOLATIONSEMANTICPHYSICALINTERPRETATION\nOVERRIDEτ∩ T risky ̸=∅SAFETYSETVIOLATION.\nTHE TRACE CONTAINS PROHIB-\nITED TOOLS DEFINED IN THE\nRISKY SET.\nPREFERENCEINJECTION.MEM-\nORY ACTS AS A“HARD-CODED”\nUSER PREFERENCE,OVERRIDING\nSTATIC SAFETY FILTERS.\nORDER∃t a, tb ∈τ:IDX(t a)>\nIDX(t b)|(t a ≺Π tb)\nPRECEDENCEVIOLATION.\nSTEP ta OCCURS AFTER tb,VI-\nOLATING THE REQUIRED DEPEN-\nDENCYt a →t b.\nDEPENDENCYSUBVERSION.BY-\nPASSES LOGIC GATES(E.G.,SKIP-\nPINGAUDIT BEFORETRANSFER).\nINVISIBLE TO WHITELIST DE-\nFENSES.\nM-SCOPE 1\n|X |\nP\nx∈X I(τx /∈Πsaf e)> δDISTRIBUTIONALSHIFT.\nTHE VIOLATION RATE ACROSS\nHETEROGENEOUS TASKS EX-\nCEEDS THRESHOLDδ.\nUNIVERSALTRIGGER.THE IN-\nJECTED LOGIC ABSTRACTS AWAY\nFROM CONTEXTS,ACTING AS\nA“MASTERKEY”ACROSS DO-\nMAINS.\nPERSISTENCEVIOLATION(τ t) =TRUE ,∀t≫\ntinject\nTEMPORALSTABILITY.\nTHE DEVIATION PERSISTS LONG\nAFTER THE INJECTION EVENT\ntinject .\nCHRONICINFECTION.CREATES\nA STABLE ATTRACTOR IN THE\nMEMORY STATE SPACE THAT RE-\nSISTS NATURAL CONTEXT DECAY.\nRELAPSEREPAIR(x) =⇒(τ new /∈\nΠsaf e)\nCORRECTIONFAILURE.\nEXPLICIT REPAIR INSTRUCTIONS\nFAIL TO STEER THE TRACE BACK\nTO THE SAFE SET.\nSTATERESISTANCE.PROVES\nTEXTUAL PATCHES ARE\nEPHEMERAL;THE UNDERLYING\nSTATEMREMAINS POISONED.\nor parameter lists) accepted by the toolset T . We define the\nTrace Space Ωτ as the set of all finite sequences of pairs of\n(a selected tool, instantiated arguments):\nΩτ ={τ= ((t 1, α1), . . . ,(tL, αL))|t i ∈ T, α i ∈ Arg},\n(2)\nwhere at each step, the agent generates a selected tool ti and\nits instantiated argumentsα i.\nThrough a variety of preliminary experiments, we find that\nMCFA can induce control flow deviations in multiple ways\nand exhibit diverse characteristics. To systematically cap-\nture these behaviors, we formalize five attack families as\ndistinct mapping functions f: Π adv → P(Ω τ), mapping\nan adversarial instructionπ adv to a target subspace ofΩ τ .\nThe families, along with their definitions and interpretations,\nare summarized in Table 1. OVERRIDEand ORDERcapture\ntwo forms of control-flow deviations: tool-choice overrides\nand reordered workflows. In contrast, M-SCOPE, PERSIST,\nand RELAPSEcharacterize whether a deviation, once ob-\nserved, propagates across tasks (cross -task propagation),\nhow long it endures (long -horizon persistence), and how\nresistant it is to mitigation (mitigation resistance). Because\ncross-task propagation, long-horizon persistence, and miti-\ngation resistance arise from a stable, task-agnostic control\npolicy encoded in memory, we instantiate these families\nusing tool-choice override as the deviation behavior. See\nAppendix B for concrete examples.\nThe Trace Auditing Algorithm. Given a specific attack\nfamily, we define attack success as the trace τ falling into\nits corresponding violation sets in the Trace Space Ωτ . To\nfurther evaluate the attack success, we use the attack suc-\ncess rate (ASR) as the metric. Based on Theorem 1, we\nconstruct the isolation-based trace auditing algorithm in\nAlgorithm 1, which audits memory-induced control flow\ndeviations through a two-phase protocol: injection and iso-\nlated evaluation. Given an agent A, initial memory Minit, an\ninjection prompt Pinj, and a benign task set Xbenign, Phase 1\nperforms a one-shot update that writes the injected content\ninto memory, yieldingM ′ ←Φ upd(Minit, Pinj).\nIn Phase 2, for each benign task xi ∈X benign, we enforce\nanisolation regimeby resetting the short-term history to\nH←∅ (Theorem 1), ensuring that any observed deviation\nis attributable to retrieved long-term memory rather than\nresidual dialogue state. We then retrieve context from the\npoisoned memory, Rctx ←Φ ret(M ′, xi), and execute the\nagent to obtain a tool-call trace τi ←F(x i, Rctx). We\nflag a deviation if the resulting trace violates the default\nsafe control flow policy, i.e., τi /∈Πsafe, and accumulate\nthe count S. Finally, we report the attack success rate as\nASR =S/|X benign|,i.e.the fraction of benign tasks whose\nexecution traces are hijacked under isolation.\nMEMFLOWEvaluation Framework. To systematically\nquantify the threat boundaries and efficacy of memory con-\n4\n220\n221\n222\n223\n224\n225\n226\n227\n228\n229\n230\n231\n232\n233\n234\n235\n236\n237\n238\n239\n240\n241\n242\n243\n244\n245\n246\n247\n248\n249\n250\n251\n252\n253\n254\n255\n256\n257\n258\n259\n260\n261\n262\n263\n264\n265\n266\n267\n268\n269\n270\n271\n272\n273\n274\nFrom Storage to Steering: Memory Control Flow Attacks on LLM Agents\nFigure 2.Overview of MEMFLOW. MEMFLOWis a evaluation framework that standardizes MCFA trials with an injection →auditing\nprotocol, logging tool-call trajectories and computing the attack success rate.\nAlgorithm 1Isolation-Based Trace Auditing\n1: Require:Agent A, Memory Minit, Injection Prompt Pinj,\nTest SuiteX benign\n2:M ′ ←Φ upd(Minit, Pinj)▷Phase 1: Injection\n3:S←0\n4:for eachtaskx i ∈ X benign do\n5:H ← ∅▷Apply Isolation (Theorem 1)\n6:R ctx ←Φ ret(M ′, xi)▷ Retrieve from poisoned memory\n7:τ i ←F(x i, Rctx)▷Generate execution trace\n8:ifτ i /∈Πsaf e then\n9:S←S+ 1▷Deviation detected\n10:end if\n11:end for\n12:returnASR=S/|X benign|\ntrol flow attacks (MCFA), we developed MEMFLOW, the\nfirst automated evaluation framework designed for agents\nequipped with memory. Unlike traditional evaluations that\nfocus on text generation quality, MEMFLOWfocuses on\nauditing thecontrol flow integrity. Through standardized\nInjection-Auditingby Algorithm 1, MEMFLOWassesses\nwhether an agent’s tool traces systematically deviate from\ndefault safety policies after injected untrusted memory. The\nsystem architecture of MEMFLOW, as shown in Figure 2,\nconsists of three core components:\n❶ Scenario Generation.To decouple testing logic from the\nunderlying frameworks, we introduce a unified Scenario\nabstraction layer. Each evaluation scenario is formalized by\na set of specifications:\n• Tool Specs: Defines the tool pool sourced from real\nworld, including the safe tools (Tsafe), the correspond-\ning risky variants ( Trisky) constructed from the same\nbase tools, and the memory write interfaces.\n• Policy Constraints: Defines the expected legitimate\ncontrol flow.\n• Dynamic Injection: Utilizes an LLM to dynamically\ngenerate diverse natural language instructions, simu-\nlating authentic User-Memory interactions rather than\nrelying on hard-coded prompt attacks.\n❷ AgentRunner. To evaluate the universality of attacks, we\nbuild the AgentRunner to provide a unified interaction\ninterface across mainstream frameworks such as LangChain\nand LlamaIndex, supporting LLMs (OpenAI, Anthropic,\nGemini) with pluggable memory components. This design\nensures strict comparability of security performance across\ndifferent agent architectures under the same test data.\n❸ Trace-audited Pipeline.MEMFLOWstandardizes each\nevaluation trial and calculates the ASR via Algrithm 1.\nThrough this automated workflow, MEMFLOWenables\nrapid identification of security vulnerabilities in different\nmemory mechanisms under batch execution modes.\n3.4. Empirical Corollaries\nCorollary 1(Dominance of Retrieval).Let α be the influ-\nence weight of memory and β be the influence of system\nsafety prompts. The experiments show:\nΦret(M)̸=∅=⇒α≫β,\nresulting in Attack Success Rates (ASR) approaching 1.0\nunder strong retrieval.\nRemark2.This corollary implies a fundamentalalignment\nbypassthreat. LLMs are supposed to prioritize system\nprompts over instructions. However, the RAG mechanism\ncan inject the adversarial instruction into the context window\nas “ground truth” or “user preference”. In this circumstance,\nLLM tends to faithfully execute the retrieved adversarial\ninstruction that facilitates the attack, effectively bypassing\nthe static safety constraints encoded in the system prompts.\n5\n275\n276\n277\n278\n279\n280\n281\n282\n283\n284\n285\n286\n287\n288\n289\n290\n291\n292\n293\n294\n295\n296\n297\n298\n299\n300\n301\n302\n303\n304\n305\n306\n307\n308\n309\n310\n311\n312\n313\n314\n315\n316\n317\n318\n319\n320\n321\n322\n323\n324\n325\n326\n327\n328\n329\nFrom Storage to Steering: Memory Control Flow Attacks on LLM Agents\nWe provide a detailed empirical analysis of this phenomenon\nin §4.2 (RQ1 & RQ2).\nCorollary 2(Inefficacy of Textual Repair).Let Rep be a\nnatural language repair instruction. The persistence prop-\nerty implies:\nP(τ saf e |M poisoned, Rep)≈0,\nindicating that removing πadv from M is necessary; mask-\ning it withRepis insufficient.\nRemark3.This highlights the limitation ofstateless de-\nfense. Most current defenses treat the agent as stateless,\nattempting to fix behavior through conversational prompts\nalone. However, since the state M remains poisoned, the\nretrieval function Φret will re-introduce πadv in future turns.\nEffective mitigation therefore requiresMemory Surgery(di-\nrect state modification) rather than conversational steering.\nWe provide a detailed empirical analysis of this phenomenon\nin §4.2 (RQ3).\n4. Experiments\n4.1. Experimental Setup and Implementation\nLLM backbones. We evaluate all experiments ongpt-\n5mini,Claude Sonnet 4.5,Gemini 2.5 Flashunder the same\nscenario specifications and tool inventories for fair compari-\nson.We set temperature to 0.0; therefore each configuration\nis executed under a fixed seed policy. We also conduct\nexperiments on open-source LLM, which are detailed in\nAppendix E.\nTools. We sample 36 tool candidates per framework from\n169 LangChain community tools (LangChain, 2026) and\n97 LlamaHub tools (LlamaIndex, 2026), using stratified","numLines":500,"startLine":300,"totalLines":2433}}}
