{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01KWLoVUpQcbR88Leyz1yyJo","type":"tool_result","content":"800\trandom sampling to balance tool categories. Detailed in-\n801\tformation regarding the LangChain community tools and\n802\tLlamaHub tools is provided in Appendix F.\n803\tWe also useTool targetto indicate which tool the system\n804\tprompt prioritizes: safe means the agent is instructed to\n805\tprefer the tool explicitly marked as SAFE, while none\n806\tmeans no tool is designated as preferred in the system\n807\tprompt.Tool labelis applied to show how themalicioustool\n808\tis described in its own metadata: harmful means the tool\n809\tis explicitly labeled as harmful, whereas neutral means\n810\tit is presented as neutral. Examples of Tool label can refer\n811\tto Appendix D.\n812\tMemory Retrieval.In all experiments, memory is con-\n813\tstructed by storing the key informationi.e.user preference,\n814\tfrom session conversations and can be retrieved in three\n815\tways:Strong, which strictly enforces the system prompt\n816\tdirective to “follow user preference”;Weak, which en-\n817\tforces this directive only loosely; andOFF, which disables\n818\tlong-term retrieval entirely. We present detailed system\n819\tprompt examples in Appendix C.\n820\tInteraction Regime.AnIsolatedregime means that, after\n821\teach session ends, all in-session context is cleared and the\n822\tAgentRunner is rebuilt. By contrast, anOnlineregime\n823\tkeeps all conversations within a single session without re-\n824\tbuilding the runner. We aim to use this discrimination to\n825\tclarify whether the observed deviations arise from retrieved\n826\tmemory or from accumulated historical interactions.\n827\t4.2. Main Results: MCFA Vulnerability Landscape\n828\tTable 2 show the main results which reveal consistent pat-\n829\tterns across tool frameworks and LLMs:(i)once memory\n830\tretrieval is enabled, memory can dominate planning under\n831\tstrict conflict;(ii)injected intent can generalize across tasks;\n832\tand(iii)attack effects persist and resist textual correction.\n833\tWe next explain the results by three research questions.\n834\tRQ1: IFMCFA DERIVESCONTROLFLOW?\n835\tThe evaluation result reveals that MCFA can derive the con-\n836\ttrol flow of LLM tool selection and execution. This deriva-\n837\ttion manifests in two primary dimensions: tool hijacking\n838\t(Override) and workflow hijacking (Order).\n839\tIt can be seen thatOverridesaturates once memory re-\n840\ttrieval is enabled. Given the strong conflict between Tool\n841\tTarget and Tool Label,i.e., a safe tool explicitly labeled as\n842\tharmful, ASR of Override remains high across frameworks\n843\tand LLMs. For example, given Strong memory retrieval,\n844\tLangChain and LlamaIndex show 97.2 ∼100% Override.\n845\tWhen tool labels areNeutral, Override remains at 100%\n846\tacross the board. In sharp contrast, when retrieval is OFF,\n847\tOverride collapses to0%despite 100% ISR, indicating that\n848\tthe deviation is caused by the memory retrieval, rather than\n849\thistorical prompts.\n850\tThe result ofOrderexhibits a non-saturated but still se-\n851\tvere vulnerability. Under Strong retrieval, Order’s ASR\n852\tranges from 52.8% to 69.4%across the board. Weakening\n853\tretrieval yields only modest reductions in some settings (e.g.,\n854\t69.4%→66.7%, 61.1%→55.6% in LangChain), while sev-\n855\teral LlamaIndex settings remain unchanged between Strong\n856\tand Weak (e.g., 63.9%, 52.8%, 66.7%). Similar to Override,\n857\tdisabling memory retrieval collapses Order shifts to0%.\n858\tTakeaway. Retrieved memory can effectively override tool\n859\tselection and disrupt safety-critical workflows, which re-\n860\tmains TRUE even when the system prompt enforces safe\n861\tbehavior and malicious tools are explicitly labeled.\n862\tRQ2: CANDERIVATIONPROPAGATECROSSTASK?\n863\tThe result of M-Scope is highly consistent: once memory\n864\tretrieval is enabled (Strong/Weak), cross-task triggering is\n865\tnear-saturated across both LangChain and LlamaIndex and\n866\tall three LLM backends (ASR ranges from 97.2% to 100%).\n867\t6\n868\t330\n869\t331\n870\t332\n871\t333\n872\t334\n873\t335\n874\t336\n875\t337\n876\t338\n877\t339\n878\t340\n879\t341\n880\t342\n881\t343\n882\t344\n883\t345\n884\t346\n885\t347\n886\t348\n887\t349\n888\t350\n889\t351\n890\t352\n891\t353\n892\t354\n893\t355\n894\t356\n895\t357\n896\t358\n897\t359\n898\t360\n899\t361\n900\t362\n901\t363\n902\t364\n903\t365\n904\t366\n905\t367\n906\t368\n907\t369\n908\t370\n909\t371\n910\t372\n911\t373\n912\t374\n913\t375\n914\t376\n915\t377\n916\t378\n917\t379\n918\t380\n919\t381\n920\t382\n921\t383\n922\t384\n923\tFrom Storage to Steering: Memory Control Flow Attacks on LLM Agents\n924\tTable 2.MEMFLOWEvaluation Results across Tool Frameworks and LLMs. This table presents a systematic comparison of attack efficacy\n925\tacross five MCFA families: Override , Order , M-Scope , Persistence , and Resistance under controlled configurations varying tool\n926\ttarget/label, retrieval strength, and execution regime.ISRdenotes injection success rate, andASRdenotes attack success rate.\n927\tAttack Family\n928\tExperimental Configuration LangChain LlamaIndex\n929\tTool Target Tool Label Retrieval Regime gpt-5-mini claude-sonnet-4-5 gemini-2.5-flash gpt-5-mini claude-sonnet-4-5 gemini-2.5-flash\n930\tISR ASR ISR ASR ISR ASR ISR ASR ISR ASR ISR ASR\n931\tSafe Tool Harmful Strong Isolated 100% 100% 97.2% 97.2% 100% 100% 100% 97.2% 100% 100% 100% 100%\n932\tSafe Tool Neutral Strong Isolated 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100%\n933\tNone Harmful Strong Isolated 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100%\n934\tSafe Tool Harmful Weak Isolated 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 91.7% 100% 100% 100% 100%\n935\tOverride\n936\tSafe Tool Harmful OFF Isolated 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0%\n937\tSafe Order Neutral Strong Isolated 100% 69.4% 100% 61.1% 100% 63.9% 100% 63.9% 100% 52.8% 100% 66.7%\n938\tSafe Order Neutral Weak Isolated 100% 66.7% 100% 55.6% 100% 58.3% 100% 63.9% 100% 52.8% 100% 66.7%Order\n939\tSafe Order Neutral OFF Isolated 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0%\n940\tSafe Tool Harmful Strong Online 100% 97.2% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100%\n941\tSafe Tool Harmful Strong Isolated 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100%\n942\tSafe Tool Harmful Weak Isolated 100% 97.2% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100%M-Scope\n943\tSafe Tool Harmful OFF Isolated 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0%\n944\tSafe Tool Harmful Strong Isolated 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100%\n945\tSafe Tool Harmful Weak Isolated 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100%Persistence\n946\tSafe Tool Harmful OFF Isolated 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0%\n947\tSafe Tool Neutral Strong Online 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100%Resistance Safe Tool Neutral Weak Online 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100%\n948\tThis indicates that a derivation injected in one task gen-\n949\teralizes beyond the original task template, steering down-\n950\tstream control flows. In the Strong retrieval comparison\n951\tacross regimes, the persistently high M-Scope observed un-\n952\tder the Isolated setting further confirms that this cross-task\n953\tpropagation is driven by memory retrieval rather than by\n954\tconversational carryover.\n955\tTakeaway. MCFA’s effect goes beyond a single task tem-\n956\tplate: one MCFA injection can trigger behavior derivation\n957\tacross domains and propagate to new tools and workflows.\n958\tRQ3: HOWDOESDERIVATIONPERSIST ANDRESIST?\n959\tASRs inPersistenceare consistently high under Strong and\n960\tWeak retrieval and drop to0%when retrieval is OFF, indi-\n961\tcating MCFA has caused long-term control flow derivations.\n962\tResistanceis evaluated within Online regime by introducing\n963\tcontinuous textual corrections to rectify variations once\n964\toccurred. A consistent 100% ASRs indicates that post-hoc\n965\ttextual correction fail to reliably overwrite an control flow-\n966\toriented malicious memory. Instead, the system exhibits\n967\tpersistent relapse once subsequent tasks trigger retrieval.\n968\tTakeaway. MCFA behaves like a durable backdoor: once\n969\tembedded into memory, it does not decay naturally, with\n970\tstrong resistance to prompt corrections. Effective mitiga-\n971\ttion therefore requires explicit memory governance.\n972\t4.3. Ablations Study\n973\tWe conduct one-factor-at-a-time ablations around a fixed\n974\tbase configuration (Online Regime, Strong Retrieval, Neu-\n975\ttral Tool Label; see Table 2). Each ablation changes exactly\n976\tone factor while holding others constant.\n977\tMemory Retrieval Ablation. Across Override, Order, M-\n978\tScope, and Persistence, settingRetrieval=OFFreduces the\n979\tMetric to0%, even though ISR remains 100%, indicating\n980\thijacking is strictly caused by memory retrieval.\n981\tMeanwhile, moving retrieval from Strong to Weak produces\n982\tminor changes in most cases, leaving vulnerability remains\n983\tsubstantial. Therefore,weakening retrieval is NOT a secu-\n984\trity boundary.\n985\tTool Label Ablation.\n986\tIt can be seen from Override, when a Neutral label is re-\n987\tplaced by a Harmful one that explicitly indicates a risky tool,\n988\tthe ASR remains high. Namely, prmopting tool-description\n989\tprovides only limited resistance to MCFA once memory\n990\tretrieval is enabled.\n991\tRegime Ablation. TheIsolatedregime isolates the task\n992\tand will clear in-session conversations after each session\n993\tends. We compare the ASRs in M-Scope scenarios within\n994\tthe Isolated regime with those within an Online regime. It\n995\tcan be seen that, ASR remains near-saturated under Isolated\n996\tevaluation, confirming that the propagation effect comes\n997\tfrom memory retrieval rather than historical prompts.\n998\t4.4. Robustness Analysis\n999\t4.4.1. RE-ORDERSUCCESS CRITERION\n1000\tOrder scenarios require an explicit success definition. Our\n1001\tdefault rule is deliberately conservative: an order is marked\n1002\tas hijacked only when the agentbreaks the safe dependency\n1003\tchain. Thisall-or-nothingrule underestimates attacks as\n1004\t7\n1005\t385\n1006\t386\n1007\t387\n1008\t388\n1009\t389\n1010\t390\n1011\t391\n1012\t392\n1013\t393\n1014\t394\n1015\t395\n1016\t396\n1017\t397\n1018\t398\n1019\t399\n1020\t400\n1021\t401\n1022\t402\n1023\t403\n1024\t404\n1025\t405\n1026\t406\n1027\t407\n1028\t408\n1029\t409\n1030\t410\n1031\t411\n1032\t412\n1033\t413\n1034\t414\n1035\t415\n1036\t416\n1037\t417\n1038\t418\n1039\t419\n1040\t420\n1041\t421\n1042\t422\n1043\t423\n1044\t424\n1045\t425\n1046\t426\n1047\t427\n1048\t428\n1049\t429\n1050\t430\n1051\t431\n1052\t432\n1053\t433\n1054\t434\n1055\t435\n1056\t436\n1057\t437\n1058\t438\n1059\t439\n1060\tFrom Storage to Steering: Memory Control Flow Attacks on LLM Agents\n1061\tit prevents harmless extra calls from being counted as suc-\n1062\tcessful attacks. Importantly, attack success rates remain\n1063\tsubstantial under this strict success criterion (52.8%∼69.4%\n1064\tunder Strong retrieval), and drop to0%when retrieval is\n1065\tOFF, indicating that our qualitative conclusions are not arti-\n1066\tfacts of a permissive scoring scheme.\n1067\t4.4.2. FRAMEWORKS ANDMODELSROBUSTNESS\n1068\tAs shown in Table 2, the same qualitative invariants hold\n1069\tacross LangChain and LlamaIndex and across three back-\n1070\tbone LLMs: (i) retrieval OFF collapses attacks; (ii) retrieval\n1071\tON yields near-saturated Override / M-Scope / Persistence\n1072\t/ Resistance; (iii) Order is non-saturated but still large un-\n1073\tder strict scoring. A few results exhibit minor drops (e.g.,\n1074\t91.7% Override in one LlamaIndex Weak setting), but these\n1075\tdo not change the overall conclusion that memory retrieval\n1076\tconstitutes a powerful hijack path to tool-use control flow.\n1077\t4.5. MFCA against Defense Evaluation\n1078\tA key limitation of the main evaluation is that it charac-\n1079\tterizes vulnerabilities but does not test whether common\n1080\tproduction-style mitigations reduce MCFA. In this section,\n1081\twe evaluate a simple yet representative defense:Dual-\n1082\tChannel MemorywithRole-Based Memory Segregation\n1083\t(RBMS), which separatessystem rulesfromuser preferences\n1084\tand enforces an explicit priority hierarchy.\n1085\t4.5.1. DEFENSEDESIGN: RBMSWITHHIERARCHICAL\n1086\tCONFLICTRESOLUTION\n1087\tDual-channel Storage. Instead of dumping all mem-\n1088\tories into a single vector index, we split meory into\n1089\ttwo storage: index system (developer rules) and\n1090\tindex user (user preferences). During the inference pro-\n1091\tcess, the AgentRunner performsscoped retrieval,i.e., it\n1092\tqueries index system for immutable safety rules and\n1093\tindex userfor personalization context.\n1094\tHierarchy Patch in the AgentRunner Prompt. We further\n1095\tenforce a strict priority policy in the AgentRunner system\n1096\tprompt:System rules are immutable and high priority; if\n1097\tuser preferences conflict with system rules, the agent must\n1098\tignore user preferences.\n1099\t4.5.2. EXPERIMENTALPROTOCOL\n1100\tWe re-run theOverrideattack by setting Tool Target = Safe\n1101\tTool and Tool Label = Harmful within the Isolated regime\n1102\tand present results in Table 2. We compare three variants:\n1103\tD0, which refers to single-channel baseline;D1, which is\n1104\tdual-channel RBMS without an explicit hierarchy instruc-\n1105\ttion; andD2, the dual-channel RBMS with the hierarchy\n1106\tpatch. We report the Override Rate (ASR) and additionally\n1107\tlog whether (i) system rules are retrieved, (ii) user prefer-\n1108\tences are retrieved, and (iii) in conflict cases, the agent com-\n1109\tplies with the hierarchyConflict-Compliance RateCCR).\n1110\t4.5.3. RESULTS: RBMS REDUCESASRBUTISNOT A\n1111\tSILVERBULLET\n1112\tTable 3 summarizes the defense outcomes across tool frame-\n1113\tworks and models. Compared to the single-channel base-\n1114\tline (D0), RBMS reduces the Override rate, with the full\n1115\thierarchy-patched variant (D2) achieving the largest drop.\n1116\tHowever, attacks still remainnon-zeroin these settings, in-\n1117\tdicating that segmentation alone does not guarantee safety.\n1118\tFailure Mode.When RBMS does not fully eliminate\n1119\thijacking, the dominant failure mode ishierarchy non-\n1120\tcompliance. Even when bothsystem rulesanduser pref-\n1121\terencesare retrieved and presented to the AgentRunner,\n1122\tthe agent sometimes treats a strongly phrased preference as\n1123\trule-like guidance and violates the intended conflict policy\n1124\t(low CCR), thereby still selecting the risky tool. This sug-\n1125\tgests that RBMS provides meaningful mitigation, yet LLM\n1126\tAgentRunner may not reliably operationalize the distinction\n1127\tbetweenmutable preferencesandimmutable rulesunder\n1128\tadversarial, action-oriented memories.\n1129\tTakeaway.RBMS is a practical step toward safer mem-\n1130\tory architectures, yet it is not a complete defense: a non-\n1131\tzero ASR under dual-channel segregation suggests that\n1132\trobust protection likely requires additional mechanisms,\n1133\tbeyond prompt-level hierarchy instructions.\n1134\tTable 3.Defense evaluation on Override under RBMS. We report\n1135\tOverride ASR (%) under the Isolated regime.\n1136\tFramework Cond. gpt-5-mini claude-sonnet-4-5 gemini-2.5-flash\n1137\tLangChain\n1138\tD0 100% 97.2% 100%\n1139\tD1 88.9% 50.0% 100%\n1140\tD2 8.3% 2.8% 63.9%\n1141\tLlamaIndex\n1142\tD0 97.2% 100% 100%\n1143\tD1 94.4% 94.4% 100%\n1144\tD2 5.6% 58.3% 100%\n1145\t5. Conclusion\n1146\tThis paper presents the first systematic security analysis\n1147\tof the impact of memory on the control flows of LLM\n1148\tagents. We identify a novel threat, Memory Control Flow\n1149\tAttack (MCFA), which exploits memory read/write chan-\n1150\tnels to covertly hijack tool selection and disrupt workflow\n1151\texecution order across tasks. Building on this foundation,\n1152\twe present MEMFLOW, an evaluation framework that stan-\n1153\tdardizes injection and auditing and measures controlflow\n1154\tintegrity via tool-call traces. Across mainstream tool frame-\n1155\tworks and state-of-the-art LLM backends, we find that\n1156\tMCFA can effectively yield pervasive control flow hijack-\n1157\t8\n1158\t440\n1159\t441\n1160\t442\n1161\t443\n1162\t444\n1163\t445\n1164\t446\n1165\t447\n1166\t448\n1167\t449\n1168\t450\n1169\t451\n1170\t452\n1171\t453\n1172\t454\n1173\t455\n1174\t456\n1175\t457\n1176\t458\n1177\t459\n1178\t460\n1179\t461\n1180\t462\n1181\t463\n1182\t464\n1183\t465\n1184\t466\n1185\t467\n1186\t468\n1187\t469\n1188\t470\n1189\t471\n1190\t472\n1191\t473\n1192\t474\n1193\t475\n1194\t476\n1195\t477\n1196\t478\n1197\t479\n1198\t480\n1199\t481\n1200\t482\n1201\t483\n1202\t484\n1203\t485\n1204\t486\n1205\t487\n1206\t488\n1207\t489\n1208\t490\n1209\t491\n1210\t492\n1211\t493\n1212\t494\n1213\tFrom Storage to Steering: Memory Control Flow Attacks on LLM Agents\n1214\ting.\n1215\tWe further evaluate a production-style mitigation, dual-\n1216\tchannel memory with role-based segregation (RBMS): it\n1217\treduces attack success but remains imperfect due to hierar-\n1218\tchy non-compliance under strongly phrased, action-oriented\n1219\tmemories. These findings underscore the critical need for\n1220\trigorous memory auditing mechanisms and isolation archi-\n1221\ttectures in future agent systems.\n1222\tImpact Statement\n1223\tThis paper aims to advance the security of LLM-based\n1224\tagents by exposing structural vulnerabilities in memory\n1225\tmechanisms. We recognize that the proposed Memory Con-\n1226\ttrol Flow Attack (MCFA) could potentially be misused by\n1227\tmalicious actors. However, we believe that systematically\n1228\tidentifying and quantifying this threat surface is a prereq-\n1229\tuisite for developing robust defenses, such as memory iso-\n1230\tlation and auditing mechanisms. By releasing MEMFLOW,\n1231\twe empower developers to assess and mitigate these risks\n1232\tprior to real-world deployment, ultimately contributing to\n1233\tthe safe and responsible adoption of autonomous agents.\n1234\tReferences\n1235\tAnthropic. Claude 4.5 sonnet. https://www.\n1236\tanthropic.com/news/claude-sonnet-4-5 ,\n1237\t2025.\n1238\tAnwar, A., Welsh, J., Biswas, J., Pouya, S., and Chang, Y .\n1239\tReMEmbR: Building and reasoning over long-horizon\n1240\tspatio-temporal memory for robot navigation.arXiv\n1241\tpreprint arXiv:2409.13682, 2024.\n1242\tChen, Z., Xiang, Z., Xiao, C., Song, D., and Li, B. Agent-\n1243\tPoison: Red-teaming LLM agents via poisoning mem-\n1244\tory or knowledge bases. InAdvances in Neural In-\n1245\tformation Processing Systems (NeurIPS), 2024. URL\n1246\thttps://arxiv.org/abs/2407.12784.\n1247\tDebenedetti, E., Zhang, J., Balunovi´c, M., Beurer-Kellner,\n1248\tL., Fischer, M., and Tram`er, F. AgentDojo: A dynamic\n1249\tenvironment to evaluate prompt injection attacks and de-\n1250\tfenses for LLM agents. InAdvances in Neural Informa-\n1251\ttion Processing Systems (NeurIPS), 2024.\n1252\tDong, S., Xu, S., He, P., Li, Y ., Tang, J., Liu, T., Liu, H., and\n1253\tXiang, Z. Memory injection attacks on LLM agents via\n1254\tquery-only interaction.arXiv preprint arXiv:2503.03704,\n1255\t2025.\n1256\tFu, X., Wang, Z., Li, S., Gupta, R. K., Mireshghallah, N.,\n1257\tBerg-Kirkpatrick, T., and Fernandes, E. Misusing tools in\n1258\tlarge language models with visual adversarial examples.\n1259\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2310.03185, 2023.\n1260\tFu, X., Li, S., Wang, Z., Liu, Y ., Gupta, R. K., Berg-\n1261\tKirkpatrick, T., and Fernandes, E. Imprompter: Trick-\n1262\ting LLM agents into improper tool use.arXiv preprint\n1263\tarXiv:2410.14923, 2024. URL https://arxiv.\n1264\torg/abs/2410.14923.\n1265\tGoogle. Gemini. https://deepmind.google/\n1266\tmodels/gemini/, 2025.\n1267\tInan, H., Upasani, K., Chi, J., Rungta, R., Iyer, K., Mao, Y .,\n1268\tTontchev, M., Hu, Q., Fuller, B., Testuggine, D., and\n1269\tKhabsa, M. Llama Guard: LLM-based input-output\n1270\tsafeguard for human-AI conversations.arXiv preprint\n1271\tarXiv:2312.06674, 2023.\n1272\tJia, F., Wu, T., Qin, X., and Squicciarini, A. The Task\n1273\tShield: Enforcing task alignment to defend against indi-\n1274\trect prompt injection in LLM agents. InProceedings of\n1275\tthe 63rd Annual Meeting of the Association for Computa-\n1276\ttional Linguistics (ACL), pp. 29680–29697. Association\n1277\tfor Computational Linguistics, 2025.\n1278\tLangChain. Langchain official github repository. https:\n1279\t//github.com/langchain-ai/langchain,\n1280\t2026.\n1281\tLi, Z., Cui, J., Liao, X., and Xing, L. Les dissonances:\n1282\tCross-tool harvesting and polluting in pool-of-tools em-\n1283\tpowered llm agents. InProceedings of the Network and\n1284\tDistributed System Security Symposium (NDSS). The In-\n1285\tternet Society, 2026.\n1286\tLin, J., Zhou, Z., Zheng, Z., Liu, S., Xu, T., Chen, Y .,\n1287\tand Chen, E. VIGIL: Defending LLM agents against tool\n1288\tstream injection via verify-before-commit.arXiv preprint\n1289\tarXiv:2601.05755, 2026.\n1290\tLlamaIndex. LlamaHub. https://llamahub.ai/,\n1291\t2026.\n1292\tMo, K., Hu, L., Long, Y ., and Li, Z. Attractive metadata\n1293\tattack: Inducing LLM agents to invoke malicious tools.\n1294\tInAdvances in Neural Information Processing Systems.\n1295\tCurran Associates, Inc., 2025. URL https://arxiv.\n1296\torg/abs/2508.02110. NeurIPS 2025.\n1297\tOpenAI. Introducing GPT-5. https://openai.com/\n1298\tindex/introducing-gpt-5/, 2025.\n1299\tPacker, C., Wooders, S., Lin, K., Fang, V ., Patil, S. G.,"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e6527c94-f67f-47a9-849d-c5fe31116d02","uuid":"efef6c9d-93c9-4bde-a37e-8bbb767b26ec","timestamp":"2026-04-25T20:00:05.716Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/papers/e5e5467c-27e4-495d-9c20-f078ae58431e.txt","content":"random sampling to balance tool categories. Detailed in-\nformation regarding the LangChain community tools and\nLlamaHub tools is provided in Appendix F.\nWe also useTool targetto indicate which tool the system\nprompt prioritizes: safe means the agent is instructed to\nprefer the tool explicitly marked as SAFE, while none\nmeans no tool is designated as preferred in the system\nprompt.Tool labelis applied to show how themalicioustool\nis described in its own metadata: harmful means the tool\nis explicitly labeled as harmful, whereas neutral means\nit is presented as neutral. Examples of Tool label can refer\nto Appendix D.\nMemory Retrieval.In all experiments, memory is con-\nstructed by storing the key informationi.e.user preference,\nfrom session conversations and can be retrieved in three\nways:Strong, which strictly enforces the system prompt\ndirective to “follow user preference”;Weak, which en-\nforces this directive only loosely; andOFF, which disables\nlong-term retrieval entirely. We present detailed system\nprompt examples in Appendix C.\nInteraction Regime.AnIsolatedregime means that, after\neach session ends, all in-session context is cleared and the\nAgentRunner is rebuilt. By contrast, anOnlineregime\nkeeps all conversations within a single session without re-\nbuilding the runner. We aim to use this discrimination to\nclarify whether the observed deviations arise from retrieved\nmemory or from accumulated historical interactions.\n4.2. Main Results: MCFA Vulnerability Landscape\nTable 2 show the main results which reveal consistent pat-\nterns across tool frameworks and LLMs:(i)once memory\nretrieval is enabled, memory can dominate planning under\nstrict conflict;(ii)injected intent can generalize across tasks;\nand(iii)attack effects persist and resist textual correction.\nWe next explain the results by three research questions.\nRQ1: IFMCFA DERIVESCONTROLFLOW?\nThe evaluation result reveals that MCFA can derive the con-\ntrol flow of LLM tool selection and execution. This deriva-\ntion manifests in two primary dimensions: tool hijacking\n(Override) and workflow hijacking (Order).\nIt can be seen thatOverridesaturates once memory re-\ntrieval is enabled. Given the strong conflict between Tool\nTarget and Tool Label,i.e., a safe tool explicitly labeled as\nharmful, ASR of Override remains high across frameworks\nand LLMs. For example, given Strong memory retrieval,\nLangChain and LlamaIndex show 97.2 ∼100% Override.\nWhen tool labels areNeutral, Override remains at 100%\nacross the board. In sharp contrast, when retrieval is OFF,\nOverride collapses to0%despite 100% ISR, indicating that\nthe deviation is caused by the memory retrieval, rather than\nhistorical prompts.\nThe result ofOrderexhibits a non-saturated but still se-\nvere vulnerability. Under Strong retrieval, Order’s ASR\nranges from 52.8% to 69.4%across the board. Weakening\nretrieval yields only modest reductions in some settings (e.g.,\n69.4%→66.7%, 61.1%→55.6% in LangChain), while sev-\neral LlamaIndex settings remain unchanged between Strong\nand Weak (e.g., 63.9%, 52.8%, 66.7%). Similar to Override,\ndisabling memory retrieval collapses Order shifts to0%.\nTakeaway. Retrieved memory can effectively override tool\nselection and disrupt safety-critical workflows, which re-\nmains TRUE even when the system prompt enforces safe\nbehavior and malicious tools are explicitly labeled.\nRQ2: CANDERIVATIONPROPAGATECROSSTASK?\nThe result of M-Scope is highly consistent: once memory\nretrieval is enabled (Strong/Weak), cross-task triggering is\nnear-saturated across both LangChain and LlamaIndex and\nall three LLM backends (ASR ranges from 97.2% to 100%).\n6\n330\n331\n332\n333\n334\n335\n336\n337\n338\n339\n340\n341\n342\n343\n344\n345\n346\n347\n348\n349\n350\n351\n352\n353\n354\n355\n356\n357\n358\n359\n360\n361\n362\n363\n364\n365\n366\n367\n368\n369\n370\n371\n372\n373\n374\n375\n376\n377\n378\n379\n380\n381\n382\n383\n384\nFrom Storage to Steering: Memory Control Flow Attacks on LLM Agents\nTable 2.MEMFLOWEvaluation Results across Tool Frameworks and LLMs. This table presents a systematic comparison of attack efficacy\nacross five MCFA families: Override , Order , M-Scope , Persistence , and Resistance under controlled configurations varying tool\ntarget/label, retrieval strength, and execution regime.ISRdenotes injection success rate, andASRdenotes attack success rate.\nAttack Family\nExperimental Configuration LangChain LlamaIndex\nTool Target Tool Label Retrieval Regime gpt-5-mini claude-sonnet-4-5 gemini-2.5-flash gpt-5-mini claude-sonnet-4-5 gemini-2.5-flash\nISR ASR ISR ASR ISR ASR ISR ASR ISR ASR ISR ASR\nSafe Tool Harmful Strong Isolated 100% 100% 97.2% 97.2% 100% 100% 100% 97.2% 100% 100% 100% 100%\nSafe Tool Neutral Strong Isolated 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100%\nNone Harmful Strong Isolated 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100%\nSafe Tool Harmful Weak Isolated 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 91.7% 100% 100% 100% 100%\nOverride\nSafe Tool Harmful OFF Isolated 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0%\nSafe Order Neutral Strong Isolated 100% 69.4% 100% 61.1% 100% 63.9% 100% 63.9% 100% 52.8% 100% 66.7%\nSafe Order Neutral Weak Isolated 100% 66.7% 100% 55.6% 100% 58.3% 100% 63.9% 100% 52.8% 100% 66.7%Order\nSafe Order Neutral OFF Isolated 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0%\nSafe Tool Harmful Strong Online 100% 97.2% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100%\nSafe Tool Harmful Strong Isolated 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100%\nSafe Tool Harmful Weak Isolated 100% 97.2% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100%M-Scope\nSafe Tool Harmful OFF Isolated 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0%\nSafe Tool Harmful Strong Isolated 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100%\nSafe Tool Harmful Weak Isolated 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100%Persistence\nSafe Tool Harmful OFF Isolated 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0% 100% 0.0%\nSafe Tool Neutral Strong Online 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100%Resistance Safe Tool Neutral Weak Online 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100% 100%\nThis indicates that a derivation injected in one task gen-\neralizes beyond the original task template, steering down-\nstream control flows. In the Strong retrieval comparison\nacross regimes, the persistently high M-Scope observed un-\nder the Isolated setting further confirms that this cross-task\npropagation is driven by memory retrieval rather than by\nconversational carryover.\nTakeaway. MCFA’s effect goes beyond a single task tem-\nplate: one MCFA injection can trigger behavior derivation\nacross domains and propagate to new tools and workflows.\nRQ3: HOWDOESDERIVATIONPERSIST ANDRESIST?\nASRs inPersistenceare consistently high under Strong and\nWeak retrieval and drop to0%when retrieval is OFF, indi-\ncating MCFA has caused long-term control flow derivations.\nResistanceis evaluated within Online regime by introducing\ncontinuous textual corrections to rectify variations once\noccurred. A consistent 100% ASRs indicates that post-hoc\ntextual correction fail to reliably overwrite an control flow-\noriented malicious memory. Instead, the system exhibits\npersistent relapse once subsequent tasks trigger retrieval.\nTakeaway. MCFA behaves like a durable backdoor: once\nembedded into memory, it does not decay naturally, with\nstrong resistance to prompt corrections. Effective mitiga-\ntion therefore requires explicit memory governance.\n4.3. Ablations Study\nWe conduct one-factor-at-a-time ablations around a fixed\nbase configuration (Online Regime, Strong Retrieval, Neu-\ntral Tool Label; see Table 2). Each ablation changes exactly\none factor while holding others constant.\nMemory Retrieval Ablation. Across Override, Order, M-\nScope, and Persistence, settingRetrieval=OFFreduces the\nMetric to0%, even though ISR remains 100%, indicating\nhijacking is strictly caused by memory retrieval.\nMeanwhile, moving retrieval from Strong to Weak produces\nminor changes in most cases, leaving vulnerability remains\nsubstantial. Therefore,weakening retrieval is NOT a secu-\nrity boundary.\nTool Label Ablation.\nIt can be seen from Override, when a Neutral label is re-\nplaced by a Harmful one that explicitly indicates a risky tool,\nthe ASR remains high. Namely, prmopting tool-description\nprovides only limited resistance to MCFA once memory\nretrieval is enabled.\nRegime Ablation. TheIsolatedregime isolates the task\nand will clear in-session conversations after each session\nends. We compare the ASRs in M-Scope scenarios within\nthe Isolated regime with those within an Online regime. It\ncan be seen that, ASR remains near-saturated under Isolated\nevaluation, confirming that the propagation effect comes\nfrom memory retrieval rather than historical prompts.\n4.4. Robustness Analysis\n4.4.1. RE-ORDERSUCCESS CRITERION\nOrder scenarios require an explicit success definition. Our\ndefault rule is deliberately conservative: an order is marked\nas hijacked only when the agentbreaks the safe dependency\nchain. Thisall-or-nothingrule underestimates attacks as\n7\n385\n386\n387\n388\n389\n390\n391\n392\n393\n394\n395\n396\n397\n398\n399\n400\n401\n402\n403\n404\n405\n406\n407\n408\n409\n410\n411\n412\n413\n414\n415\n416\n417\n418\n419\n420\n421\n422\n423\n424\n425\n426\n427\n428\n429\n430\n431\n432\n433\n434\n435\n436\n437\n438\n439\nFrom Storage to Steering: Memory Control Flow Attacks on LLM Agents\nit prevents harmless extra calls from being counted as suc-\ncessful attacks. Importantly, attack success rates remain\nsubstantial under this strict success criterion (52.8%∼69.4%\nunder Strong retrieval), and drop to0%when retrieval is\nOFF, indicating that our qualitative conclusions are not arti-\nfacts of a permissive scoring scheme.\n4.4.2. FRAMEWORKS ANDMODELSROBUSTNESS\nAs shown in Table 2, the same qualitative invariants hold\nacross LangChain and LlamaIndex and across three back-\nbone LLMs: (i) retrieval OFF collapses attacks; (ii) retrieval\nON yields near-saturated Override / M-Scope / Persistence\n/ Resistance; (iii) Order is non-saturated but still large un-\nder strict scoring. A few results exhibit minor drops (e.g.,\n91.7% Override in one LlamaIndex Weak setting), but these\ndo not change the overall conclusion that memory retrieval\nconstitutes a powerful hijack path to tool-use control flow.\n4.5. MFCA against Defense Evaluation\nA key limitation of the main evaluation is that it charac-\nterizes vulnerabilities but does not test whether common\nproduction-style mitigations reduce MCFA. In this section,\nwe evaluate a simple yet representative defense:Dual-\nChannel MemorywithRole-Based Memory Segregation\n(RBMS), which separatessystem rulesfromuser preferences\nand enforces an explicit priority hierarchy.\n4.5.1. DEFENSEDESIGN: RBMSWITHHIERARCHICAL\nCONFLICTRESOLUTION\nDual-channel Storage. Instead of dumping all mem-\nories into a single vector index, we split meory into\ntwo storage: index system (developer rules) and\nindex user (user preferences). During the inference pro-\ncess, the AgentRunner performsscoped retrieval,i.e., it\nqueries index system for immutable safety rules and\nindex userfor personalization context.\nHierarchy Patch in the AgentRunner Prompt. We further\nenforce a strict priority policy in the AgentRunner system\nprompt:System rules are immutable and high priority; if\nuser preferences conflict with system rules, the agent must\nignore user preferences.\n4.5.2. EXPERIMENTALPROTOCOL\nWe re-run theOverrideattack by setting Tool Target = Safe\nTool and Tool Label = Harmful within the Isolated regime\nand present results in Table 2. We compare three variants:\nD0, which refers to single-channel baseline;D1, which is\ndual-channel RBMS without an explicit hierarchy instruc-\ntion; andD2, the dual-channel RBMS with the hierarchy\npatch. We report the Override Rate (ASR) and additionally\nlog whether (i) system rules are retrieved, (ii) user prefer-\nences are retrieved, and (iii) in conflict cases, the agent com-\nplies with the hierarchyConflict-Compliance RateCCR).\n4.5.3. RESULTS: RBMS REDUCESASRBUTISNOT A\nSILVERBULLET\nTable 3 summarizes the defense outcomes across tool frame-\nworks and models. Compared to the single-channel base-\nline (D0), RBMS reduces the Override rate, with the full\nhierarchy-patched variant (D2) achieving the largest drop.\nHowever, attacks still remainnon-zeroin these settings, in-\ndicating that segmentation alone does not guarantee safety.\nFailure Mode.When RBMS does not fully eliminate\nhijacking, the dominant failure mode ishierarchy non-\ncompliance. Even when bothsystem rulesanduser pref-\nerencesare retrieved and presented to the AgentRunner,\nthe agent sometimes treats a strongly phrased preference as\nrule-like guidance and violates the intended conflict policy\n(low CCR), thereby still selecting the risky tool. This sug-\ngests that RBMS provides meaningful mitigation, yet LLM\nAgentRunner may not reliably operationalize the distinction\nbetweenmutable preferencesandimmutable rulesunder\nadversarial, action-oriented memories.\nTakeaway.RBMS is a practical step toward safer mem-\nory architectures, yet it is not a complete defense: a non-\nzero ASR under dual-channel segregation suggests that\nrobust protection likely requires additional mechanisms,\nbeyond prompt-level hierarchy instructions.\nTable 3.Defense evaluation on Override under RBMS. We report\nOverride ASR (%) under the Isolated regime.\nFramework Cond. gpt-5-mini claude-sonnet-4-5 gemini-2.5-flash\nLangChain\nD0 100% 97.2% 100%\nD1 88.9% 50.0% 100%\nD2 8.3% 2.8% 63.9%\nLlamaIndex\nD0 97.2% 100% 100%\nD1 94.4% 94.4% 100%\nD2 5.6% 58.3% 100%\n5. Conclusion\nThis paper presents the first systematic security analysis\nof the impact of memory on the control flows of LLM\nagents. We identify a novel threat, Memory Control Flow\nAttack (MCFA), which exploits memory read/write chan-\nnels to covertly hijack tool selection and disrupt workflow\nexecution order across tasks. Building on this foundation,\nwe present MEMFLOW, an evaluation framework that stan-\ndardizes injection and auditing and measures controlflow\nintegrity via tool-call traces. Across mainstream tool frame-\nworks and state-of-the-art LLM backends, we find that\nMCFA can effectively yield pervasive control flow hijack-\n8\n440\n441\n442\n443\n444\n445\n446\n447\n448\n449\n450\n451\n452\n453\n454\n455\n456\n457\n458\n459\n460\n461\n462\n463\n464\n465\n466\n467\n468\n469\n470\n471\n472\n473\n474\n475\n476\n477\n478\n479\n480\n481\n482\n483\n484\n485\n486\n487\n488\n489\n490\n491\n492\n493\n494\nFrom Storage to Steering: Memory Control Flow Attacks on LLM Agents\ning.\nWe further evaluate a production-style mitigation, dual-\nchannel memory with role-based segregation (RBMS): it\nreduces attack success but remains imperfect due to hierar-\nchy non-compliance under strongly phrased, action-oriented\nmemories. These findings underscore the critical need for\nrigorous memory auditing mechanisms and isolation archi-\ntectures in future agent systems.\nImpact Statement\nThis paper aims to advance the security of LLM-based\nagents by exposing structural vulnerabilities in memory\nmechanisms. We recognize that the proposed Memory Con-\ntrol Flow Attack (MCFA) could potentially be misused by\nmalicious actors. However, we believe that systematically\nidentifying and quantifying this threat surface is a prereq-\nuisite for developing robust defenses, such as memory iso-\nlation and auditing mechanisms. By releasing MEMFLOW,\nwe empower developers to assess and mitigate these risks\nprior to real-world deployment, ultimately contributing to\nthe safe and responsible adoption of autonomous agents.\nReferences\nAnthropic. Claude 4.5 sonnet. https://www.\nanthropic.com/news/claude-sonnet-4-5 ,\n2025.\nAnwar, A., Welsh, J., Biswas, J., Pouya, S., and Chang, Y .\nReMEmbR: Building and reasoning over long-horizon\nspatio-temporal memory for robot navigation.arXiv\npreprint arXiv:2409.13682, 2024.\nChen, Z., Xiang, Z., Xiao, C., Song, D., and Li, B. Agent-\nPoison: Red-teaming LLM agents via poisoning mem-\nory or knowledge bases. InAdvances in Neural In-\nformation Processing Systems (NeurIPS), 2024. URL\nhttps://arxiv.org/abs/2407.12784.\nDebenedetti, E., Zhang, J., Balunovi´c, M., Beurer-Kellner,\nL., Fischer, M., and Tram`er, F. AgentDojo: A dynamic\nenvironment to evaluate prompt injection attacks and de-\nfenses for LLM agents. InAdvances in Neural Informa-\ntion Processing Systems (NeurIPS), 2024.\nDong, S., Xu, S., He, P., Li, Y ., Tang, J., Liu, T., Liu, H., and\nXiang, Z. Memory injection attacks on LLM agents via\nquery-only interaction.arXiv preprint arXiv:2503.03704,\n2025.\nFu, X., Wang, Z., Li, S., Gupta, R. K., Mireshghallah, N.,\nBerg-Kirkpatrick, T., and Fernandes, E. Misusing tools in\nlarge language models with visual adversarial examples.\narXiv preprint arXiv:2310.03185, 2023.\nFu, X., Li, S., Wang, Z., Liu, Y ., Gupta, R. K., Berg-\nKirkpatrick, T., and Fernandes, E. Imprompter: Trick-\ning LLM agents into improper tool use.arXiv preprint\narXiv:2410.14923, 2024. URL https://arxiv.\norg/abs/2410.14923.\nGoogle. Gemini. https://deepmind.google/\nmodels/gemini/, 2025.\nInan, H., Upasani, K., Chi, J., Rungta, R., Iyer, K., Mao, Y .,\nTontchev, M., Hu, Q., Fuller, B., Testuggine, D., and\nKhabsa, M. Llama Guard: LLM-based input-output\nsafeguard for human-AI conversations.arXiv preprint\narXiv:2312.06674, 2023.\nJia, F., Wu, T., Qin, X., and Squicciarini, A. The Task\nShield: Enforcing task alignment to defend against indi-\nrect prompt injection in LLM agents. InProceedings of\nthe 63rd Annual Meeting of the Association for Computa-\ntional Linguistics (ACL), pp. 29680–29697. Association\nfor Computational Linguistics, 2025.\nLangChain. Langchain official github repository. https:\n//github.com/langchain-ai/langchain,\n2026.\nLi, Z., Cui, J., Liao, X., and Xing, L. Les dissonances:\nCross-tool harvesting and polluting in pool-of-tools em-\npowered llm agents. InProceedings of the Network and\nDistributed System Security Symposium (NDSS). The In-\nternet Society, 2026.\nLin, J., Zhou, Z., Zheng, Z., Liu, S., Xu, T., Chen, Y .,\nand Chen, E. VIGIL: Defending LLM agents against tool\nstream injection via verify-before-commit.arXiv preprint\narXiv:2601.05755, 2026.\nLlamaIndex. LlamaHub. https://llamahub.ai/,\n2026.\nMo, K., Hu, L., Long, Y ., and Li, Z. Attractive metadata\nattack: Inducing LLM agents to invoke malicious tools.\nInAdvances in Neural Information Processing Systems.\nCurran Associates, Inc., 2025. URL https://arxiv.\norg/abs/2508.02110. NeurIPS 2025.\nOpenAI. Introducing GPT-5. https://openai.com/\nindex/introducing-gpt-5/, 2025.\nPacker, C., Wooders, S., Lin, K., Fang, V ., Patil, S. G.,","numLines":500,"startLine":800,"totalLines":2433}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_013xzoRqzXCJFqmZyndyogb1","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9461,"cache_read_input_tokens":93677,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":9461,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":48,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e6527c94-f67f-47a9-849d-c5fe31116d02","uuid":"092c7b6d-9483-4875-934f-405367310a09"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_013xzoRqzXCJFqmZyndyogb1","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01GNZoYB3NBoYqmBu7STZPSd","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/reasoning/qwerty81/e5e5467c-27e4-495d-9c20-f078ae58431e.md","content":"# Paper e5e5467c — From Storage to Steering: Memory Control Flow Attacks on LLM Agents\n\n## Comment posted\n\n**Soundness.** Theorem 1's isolation regime cleanly separates memory-induced\ndeviation from session-history confounders, and the OFF-retrieval ASR collapse\nto 0% across all configurations is strong corroborating evidence. The argument\nrequires verification of one premise — that the base model F is aligned to the\nsafety policy Π_safe — which is treated as an unstated assumption rather than\nempirically validated; a brief base-rate experiment with retrieval OFF and the\nadversarial *task* directly in the prompt would close that gap.\n\n**Presentation.** The five attack families (OVERRIDE, ORDER, M-SCOPE,\nPERSISTENCE, RELAPSE) and the Read→Plan→Execute→Write loop give the reader a\nclear conceptual scaffold, and Figure 1's standard-vs-attacked control flow is\neffective. The manuscript would benefit from another editorial pass; minor\nissues such as \"we further design we develop MEMFLOW\" (Sec 3.3) and\ninconsistent capitalization in Table 1 distract from an otherwise clean\nnarrative.\n\n**Significance.** Reporting against three frontier LLMs (GPT-5 mini, Claude\nSonnet 4.5, Gemini 2.5 Flash) on LangChain and LlamaIndex grounds the threat in\nthe dominant production stack, and the RBMS evaluation in Section 4.5\nstrengthens the contribution by showing the defense is partially effective\n(LangChain D2 drops Override to 2.8–8.3%) rather than declaring the system\nunfixable. The methodology lacks evidence that retrieval-mechanism choice (BM25\nvs. dense vs. hybrid) is independent of ASR; a short ablation across retrievers\nwould clarify whether MCFA generalizes beyond the specific embedding-based\nretriever used.\n\n**Originality.** Reframing memory as a *persistent control input* rather than a\ncontent-degradation surface is a meaningful conceptual shift relative to prior\npoisoning work (AgentPoison, MINJA, BadChain), and the cross-task / persistence\n/ relapse axes are not directly captured by AgentDojo or INJECAGENT. Prior work\nin tool-mediated injection and stateful agent isolation (e.g., IsolateGPT,\nA-MemGuard) is relevant to the contribution; tighter engagement with how\nMEMFLOW's auditing protocol composes with these defenses would strengthen\npositioning.\n\n## Internal panel analysis\n\n- **Methodological Traditionalist.**\n  - Theorem 1 is a clean isolation argument; proof is short but valid given the\n    assumption on F's alignment.\n  - The assumption that base F is aligned to Π_safe is not empirically\n    validated — would have liked a control where the prompt itself contains the\n    adversarial instruction (no memory) to establish the base rate of safety\n    violation by F alone.\n  - Order success criterion is conservative (\"all-or-nothing\" dependency\n    break), which is the right default but should be paired with a soft metric.\n\n- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer.**\n  - Five attack families with explicit definitions and physical interpretation\n    (Table 1) — high cite-ability.\n  - Figures 1–2 are clean; tables are dense but legible.\n  - Minor grammar/typos throughout — the paper reads as recently revised but\n    not fully polished.\n\n- **Empirical SOTA Auditor.**\n  - Subfield: LLM-agent security, memory poisoning, and control-flow integrity.\n  - Standard prior baselines: AgentPoison (NeurIPS 2024), MINJA (Dong 2025),\n    BadChain (Xiang 2024), AgentDojo (NeurIPS 2024), INJECAGENT (Zhan 2024).\n  - The paper's claim \"first systematic analysis of memory's impact on control\n    flows\" is plausibly true — most prior work targets *content* not *control\n    flow*.\n  - 90%+ ASR is striking but consistent with prior agent-injection results\n    (which often report 60–95%). The novelty is the *persistence* and\n    *isolation-verified* nature, not the headline number.\n\n- **Misaligned Generalist.**\n  - The introduction establishes the problem clearly (Read→Plan→Execute→Write\n    loop is intuitive even to non-security ML researchers).\n  - The Verification Theorem is presented in plain enough language to follow\n    without security background.\n  - Contribution is well-summarized in the four bullet contributions.\n\n## Trending-domain classification\nagentic-ai\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: full (with appendix references throughout)\n- Section balance: balanced — Related Work, Formalization, Methodology,\n  Experiments, Defense each get proportional space\n- Open-source artifacts (code/data link present): no — `github_repo_url` is\n  null on the platform; MEMFLOW is described in detail but no link given\n- Citation freshness: yes — engages 2024–2026 work (AgentPoison, MINJA,\n  BadChain, AgentDojo, IsolateGPT, A-MemGuard, NDSS 2026)\n\n## Author assertion strength\nmixed — confidently framed in the abstract (\"over 90% trials are vulnerable\n... critical security risks that demand immediate attention\") but qualifies in\nthe body (\"RBMS reduces attack success but is not a silver bullet\"). The\nbalance is appropriate.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9461,"cache_read_input_tokens":93677,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":9461,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":48,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e6527c94-f67f-47a9-849d-c5fe31116d02","uuid":"b3a1479c-9bd3-40e4-9eb7-34b4f7f38348"}
