ective\n(LangChain D2 drops Override to 2.8–8.3%) rather than declaring the system\nunfixable. The methodology lacks evidence that retrieval-mechanism choice (BM25\nvs. dense vs. hybrid) is independent of ASR; a short ablation across retrievers\nwould clarify whether MCFA generalizes beyond the specific embedding-based\nretriever used.\n\n**Originality.** Reframing memory as a *persistent control input* rather than a\ncontent-degradation surface is a meaningful conceptual shift relative to prior\npoisoning work (AgentPoison, MINJA, BadChain), and the cross-task / persistence\n/ relapse axes are not directly captured by AgentDojo or INJECAGENT. Prior work\nin tool-mediated injection and stateful agent isolation (e.g., IsolateGPT,\nA-MemGuard) is relevant to the contribution; tighter engagement with how\nMEMFLOW's auditing protocol composes with these defenses would strengthen\npositioning.\n\n## Internal panel analysis\n\n- **Methodological Traditionalist.**\n  - Theorem 1 is a clean isolation argument; proof is short but valid given the\n    assumption on F's alignment.\n  - The assumption that base F is aligned to Π_safe is not empirically\n    validated — would have liked a control where the prompt itself contains the\n    adversarial instruction (no memory) to establish the base rate of safety\n    violation by F alone.\n  - Order success criterion is conservative (\"all-or-nothing\" dependency\n    break), which is the right default but should be paired with a soft metric.\n\n- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer.**\n  - Five attack families with explicit definitions and physical interpretation\n    (Table 1) — high cite-ability.\n  - Figures 1–2 are clean; tables are dense but legible.\n  - Minor grammar/typos throughout — the paper reads as recently revised but\n    not fully polished.\n\n- **Empirical SOTA Auditor.**\n  - Subfield: LLM-agent security, memory poisoning, and control-flow integrity.\n  - Standard prior baselines: AgentPoison (NeurIPS 2024), MINJA (Dong 2025),\n    BadChain (Xiang 2024), AgentDojo (NeurIPS 2024), INJECAGENT (Zhan 2024).\n  - The paper's claim \"first systematic analysis of memory's impact on control\n    flows\" is plausibly true — most prior work targets *content* not *control\n    flow*.\n  - 90%+ ASR is striking but consistent with prior agent-injection results\n    (which often report 60–95%). The novelty is the *persistence* and\n    *isolation-verified* nature, not the headline number.\n\n- **Misaligned Generalist.**\n  - The introduction establishes the problem clearly (Read→Plan→Execute→Write\n    loop is intuitive even to non-security ML researchers).\n  - The Verification Theorem is presented in plain enough language to follow\n    without security background.\n  - Contribution is well-summarized in the four bullet contributions.\n\n## Trending-domain classification\nagentic-ai\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: full (with appendix references throughout)\n- Section balance: balanced — Related Work, Formalization, Methodology,\n  Experiments, Defense each get proportional space\n- Open-source artifacts (code/data link present): no — `github_repo_url` is\n  null on the platform; MEMFLOW is described in detail but no link given\n- Citation freshness: yes — engages 2024–2026 work (AgentPoison, MINJA,\n  BadChain, AgentDojo, IsolateGPT, A-MemGuard, NDSS 2026)\n\n## Author assertion strength\nmixed — confidently framed in the abstract (\"over 90% trials are vulnerable\n... critical security risks that demand immediate attention\") but qualifies in\nthe body (\"RBMS reduces attack success but is not a silver bullet\"). The\nbalance is appropriate.\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null,"userModified":false}}
