{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011n5Va2qJ3TxrgiW17EJR99","type":"tool_result","content":"50\t049\n51\t050\n52\t051\n53\t052\n54\t053\n55\t054\n56\tHeiSD: Hybrid Speculative Decoding for Embodied\n57\tVision-Language-Action Models with Kinematic Awareness\n58\tAnonymous Authors1\n59\tAbstract\n60\tVision-Language-Action (VLA) Models have be-\n61\tcome the mainstream solution for robot control,\n62\tbut suffer from slow inference speeds. Specula-\n63\ttive Decoding (SD) is a promising acceleration\n64\tmethod which can be divided into two categories:\n65\tdrafter-based SD and retrieval-based SD. Exist-\n66\ting methods fail to analyze the advantages and\n67\tdisadvantages of these two types of SD in VLA\n68\tmodels, leading to their sole application or op-\n69\ttimization. In this paper, we analyze the trajec-\n70\ttory patterns of robots controlled by the VLA\n71\tmodel and derive a key insight: the two types\n72\tof SD should be used in a hybrid manner. How-\n73\tever, achieving hybrid SD in VLA models poses\n74\tseveral challenges: (1) draft rejection and per-\n75\tsistent errors in retrieval-based SD; (2) difficulty\n76\tin determining the hybrid boundary. To address\n77\tthese, we propose theHeiSDframework. We pro-\n78\tpose a retrieval-based SD optimization method in\n79\tHeiSD,which contains a verify-skip mechanism\n80\tand a sequence-wise relaxed acceptance strategy.\n81\tMoreover, we proposed a kinematic-based fused\n82\tmetric inHeiSDto automatically determine the\n83\thybrid boundary. Experimental results demon-\n84\tstrate thatHeiSDattains a speedup of up to 2.45 ×\n85\tin simulation benchmarks and 2.06×∼2.41× in\n86\treal-world scenarios, while sustaining a high task\n87\tsuccess rate.\n88\t1. Introduction\n89\tVision-Language-Action (VLA) models have emerged as\n90\tthe mainstream solution for Embodied Intelligence (Ma\n91\tet al., 2024; Zhang et al., 2024). Despite their impressive per-\n92\tformance, the heavy computational demands of VLA mod-\n93\tels limit their inference speed, preventing them from meet-\n94\t1Anonymous Institution, Anonymous City, Anonymous Region,\n95\tAnonymous Country. Correspondence to: Anonymous Author\n96\t<anon.email@domain.com>.\n97\tPreliminary work. Under review by the International Conference\n98\ton Machine Learning (ICML). Do not distribute.\n99\ting real-time requirements (Wen et al., 2025; Budzianowski\n100\tet al., 2025). To boost the inference speed of VLA models,\n101\texisting work has integrated large-model inference optimiza-\n102\ttion techniques into VLAs, covering: model architecture in-\n103\tnovation (Liu et al., 2024a; Wen et al., 2025; Budzianowski\n104\tet al., 2025; Pertsch et al., 2025), model compression (Zheng\n105\tet al., 2025; 2026a; Park et al., 2024; Li et al., 2025), run-\n106\ttime optimization (Zhang et al., 2025; Song et al., 2025; Yue\n107\tet al., 2024) and deployment design (Zheng et al., 2026c). In\n108\tsuch runtime optimization methods, Speculative Decoding\n109\t(SD) (Wang et al., 2025; Zheng et al., 2026b) is a promising\n110\tmethod that can accelerate inference.\n111\tThe essence of SD lies in employing low-cost methods to\n112\trapidly generate token sequences. These sequences then\n113\tundergo parallel verification and selective acceptance by\n114\tLarge Language Models (LLMs), thereby enhancing infer-\n115\tence speed. Existing SD methods can be categorized into\n116\ttwo types: drafter-based SD (Wen et al., 2024; Yan et al.,\n117\t2025) and retrieval-based SD (Cho et al., 2025; He et al.,\n118\t2024; Lee et al., 2025). Drafter-based SD leverages a small\n119\tmodel (trained from scratch or fine-tuned) to generate draft\n120\ttoken sequences. In contrast, retrieval-based SD does not\n121\trely on a dedicated draft model; instead, it uses a prebuilt\n122\tvector database and retrieves relevant content from it to\n123\tobtain draft token sequences.\n124\tWhen being adapted for VLA models, both drafter-based\n125\tand retrieval-based SD approaches exhibit distinct advan-\n126\ttages and limitations. As Fig. 1 (a) shows, drafter-based\n127\tSD can provide high-quality drafts with a high probability\n128\tof passing verification. But it needs to bear the inference\n129\toverhead of the draft model. Retrieval-based SD eliminates\n130\tthe overhead of the draft model and has a higher theoretical\n131\tspeedup, but suffers from low draft quality.\n132\tIn this study, we first construct a database and develop an\n133\tanalysis of retrieval drafts. Our analysis reveals that some\n134\ttrajectory segments guided by retrieval drafts highly align\n135\twith VLA inference, while others exhibit deviations. Based\n136\ton this observation, we derive a key insight: employing\n137\tretrieval-based SD for the overlapping segments and drafter-\n138\tbased SD for the non-overlapping segments enables leverag-\n139\ting the advantages of both SD approaches simultaneously.\n140\t1\n141\t055\n142\t056\n143\t057\n144\t058\n145\t059\n146\t060\n147\t061\n148\t062\n149\t063\n150\t064\n151\t065\n152\t066\n153\t067\n154\t068\n155\t069\n156\t070\n157\t071\n158\t072\n159\t073\n160\t074\n161\t075\n162\t076\n163\t077\n164\t078\n165\t079\n166\t080\n167\t081\n168\t082\n169\t083\n170\t084\n171\t085\n172\t086\n173\t087\n174\t088\n175\t089\n176\t090\n177\t091\n178\t092\n179\t093\n180\t094\n181\t095\n182\t096\n183\t097\n184\t098\n185\t099\n186\t100\n187\t101\n188\t102\n189\t103\n190\t104\n191\t105\n192\t106\n193\t107\n194\t108\n195\t109\n196\tSubmission and Formatting Instructions for ICML 2026\n197\tGeneration\n198\tDraft QualityTheoreticalSpeedOverheadDraft-Based SDHighLowHighRetrieval-Based SDLowHighLow\n199\t(b)\n200\tVLAModel\n201\ta1a2a3a4\n202\ta'2a'3a'4a'1a'0\n203\tDraft ModelDrafterInputDraft-Based SD\n204\tVLAModel\n205\ta1a2a3a4\n206\ta'2a'3a'4a'1a'0\n207\tDatabaseNo Drafter\n208\tRetrievalInputRetrieval-Based SD\n209\tStep\n210\t(a) StepStepStepStepStep\n211\tRobotControl\n212\tMulti-StepInferenceofVLAModels\n213\tRetrieval-Based SDDraft-Based SDRetrieval-Based SD\n214\tRetrieval-BasedSDNeedsOptimizationChallenge1 HardtoDetermineHybridBoundaryChallenge2\n215\tHeiSDFrameworkHybrid SDEmbodiedIntelligence=+Solution1 Solution2AdaptiveVerify-SkipSeq-WiseRelaxedAcceptKinematic-BasedFusedMetricforDetermineBoundary\n216\tFigure 1.Overview of the ProposedHeiSDFramework\n217\tHowever, achieving this kind of hybrid SD in VLA mod-\n218\tels faces challenges. First, retrieval-based SD suffers from\n219\tlow-quality drafts, which are hard to pass the verification\n220\tprocess and cause persistent errors. Thus, specific optimiza-\n221\ttion is needed for retrieval-based SD. Second, it is hard\n222\tto determine the hybrid boundary, i.e., identifying which\n223\tstep should employ drafter-based SD and which should use\n224\tretrieval-based SD.\n225\tTo address these challenges, we first propose an optimiza-\n226\ttion method for retrieval-based SD. We propose an adaptive\n227\tverify-skip mechanism that selectively skips the verification\n228\tprocess for certain drafts to avoid strict rejection. Further-\n229\tmore, we propose a sequence-wise relaxed acceptance strat-\n230\tegy to enhance the diversity of drafts during verification\n231\tand accept drafts with minor bias without compromising\n232\taccuracy, to avoid persistent errors.\n233\tAfter that, we developed a kinematic-based fused metric\n234\tto automatically determine the hybrid boundary, enabling\n235\tautomatic decision and automatic switching during VLA\n236\tmulti-step inference. These designs form an end-to-end\n237\thybrid SD framework for VLA models, calledHeiSD. We\n238\tbelieveHeiSDwill play a role in the future development\n239\tof embodied intelligence and community building. In sum-\n240\tmary, our contributions are below:\n241\t• We conducted a detailed analysis and gained key in-\n242\tsights: hybrid using drafter-based SD and retrieval-\n243\tbased SD in VLA models leads to better performance.\n244\t• We optimize retrieval-based SD and propose an adap-\n245\ttive verify-skip mechanism along with a sequence-wise\n246\trelaxed acceptance strategy.\n247\t• We developed a kinematic-based fused metric to auto-\n248\tmatically determine the hybrid boundary, thus forming\n249\ttheHeiSDframework.\n250\tExperimental results demonstrate thatHeiSDattains a\n251\tspeedup of up to 2.45 × in simulation benchmarks and\n252\t2.06×∼2.41× in real-world scenarios, while sustaining a\n253\thigh task success rate.\n254\t2. Preliminary\n255\t2.1. Vision-Language-Action Models\n256\tVLA models usually comprise three core components (Kim\n257\tet al., 2024; Zitkovich et al., 2023): vision encoders (convert-\n258\ting visual modality into tokens), an LLM backbone (fusing\n259\tmulti-modal information and enabling reasoning), and an\n260\taction de-tokenizer (decoding output tokens into actions).\n261\taj = arg max\n262\taj\n263\t\u0002\n264\tP(a j |a 0:j−1,O,P,W)\n265\t\u0003\n266\t.(1)\n267\tEach VLA generation outputs an action slice, which is a\n268\t7-dimensional vector representing 7 Degrees of Freedom\n269\t(DoF): position X, Y, Z of the end gripper, joint rotation an-\n270\tgles rX , rY , rZ, and a binary gripper control signalG. Each\n271\tDoF is encoded as a tokenaj. VLA models autoregressively\n272\tpredict the most probable token aj based on the previously\n273\ttokens a0:j−1, visual observations O, language prompts P,\n274\tand the learnable model parametersW, as Eq. (1) shown.\n275\t2.2. Speculative Decoding\n276\tThe core idea of SD is to use low-cost methods for rapid to-\n277\tken sequence acquisition and employ LLMs for parallel ver-\n278\tification of these tokens, thus avoiding slow autoregressive\n279\tgeneration. Existing SD falls into two categories: drafter-\n280\tbased and retrieval-based. The former leverages a small\n281\tdraft model MD to generate token sequences, and uses the\n282\tLLM as a verification model MV . This process can be writ-\n283\tten as Eq. (2), in which aj means the tokens, ft means the\n284\thidden features, ande t means the token embeddings.\n285\tDraft:a j =M D(f1:t, e0:t, at+1:j−1).\n286\tVerify:ˆaj =M V(a0:j−1,P,W),\n287\t(\n288\tˆaj =a j,Acpt.\n289\tˆaj ̸=a j,Disc.\n290\t(2)\n291\tDraft:a j =\n292\t\b\n293\tRetri(f1:t, e0:t, at+1:j−1)\n294\t\f\f ∈DB\n295\t\t\n296\t.(3)\n297\t2\n298\t110\n299\t111\n300\t112\n301\t113\n302\t114\n303\t115\n304\t116\n305\t117\n306\t118\n307\t119\n308\t120\n309\t121\n310\t122\n311\t123\n312\t124\n313\t125\n314\t126\n315\t127\n316\t128\n317\t129\n318\t130\n319\t131\n320\t132\n321\t133\n322\t134\n323\t135\n324\t136\n325\t137\n326\t138\n327\t139\n328\t140\n329\t141\n330\t142\n331\t143\n332\t144\n333\t145\n334\t146\n335\t147\n336\t148\n337\t149\n338\t150\n339\t151\n340\t152\n341\t153\n342\t154\n343\t155\n344\t156\n345\t157\n346\t158\n347\t159\n348\t160\n349\t161\n350\t162\n351\t163\n352\t164\n353\tSubmission and Formatting Instructions for ICML 2026\n354\tTrajectoryOverlap\n355\tY-Dim\n356\tZ-Dim\n357\tSmallTrajectory Deviation\n358\tEnd PointMatch\n359\tVLA InferenceDB RetrievalTrajectory ofFailed Case(a)\n360\tX-DimY-Dim\n361\tZ-Dim\n362\tTrajectory of SuccessfulCase\n363\tTrajectoryOverlap\n364\tEnvironment: LIBERO-GoalTask: Push Plate to the Front of the Stove\n365\t(b)VLA InferenceDB Retrieval\n366\tEnvironment: LIBERO-GoalTask: Push Plate to the Front of the Stove\n367\tVLA Inference: SuccessDB Retrieval: Success\n368\tLargeTrajectory Deviation\n369\tEnd PointMismatchX-Dim\n370\tVLA Inference: SuccessDB Retrieval: Failure\n371\tInReal-World\n372\tTrajectory\n373\tTrajectory\n374\tTrajectoryFragment\n375\tInSimulation\n376\tTrajectory\n377\tTrajectoryAction\n378\tViTLLMDe-Token\n379\tInReal-WorldInSimulationRetrieval\n380\tVectorDB\n381\tAction\n382\tHighSimilarity !\n383\t(c)\n384\tTrajectoryFragment\n385\tFigure 2.Kinematic-Based Trajectory Analysis and Real-world/Simulation Validation for both VLA Inference and Database Retrieval\n386\tIn contrast, retrieval-based SD does not need a draft model;\n387\tinstead, it uses a database to retrieve draft token sequences.\n388\tIts draft process can be written as Eq.(3), where DB means\n389\tthe prebuilt database. When applied to VLA models, the\n390\ttwo types of SD each have distinct advantages and draw-\n391\tbacks. Drafter-based SD necessitates online maintenance\n392\tof a draft model: while smaller than a VLA model, this\n393\tdrafter still incurs memory consumption and additional com-\n394\tputational overhead/latency, though its high-quality drafts\n395\tsupport longer acceptable sequences and achieve actual ac-\n396\tceleration. In contrast, retrieval-based SD eliminates the\n397\toverhead associated with the drafter model and offers theo-\n398\tretical performance benefits; however, the retrieved drafts\n399\tsuffer from distribution mismatch, which hinders verifica-\n400\ttion and restricts the theoretical acceleration.\n401\t3. Observation and Motivation\n402\tThis section first details the construction of the database\n403\tand its performance test, then presents a database retrieval\n404\ttrajectory analysis. Based on analysis results, we derive\n405\tinsights into achieving hybrid SD in VLA inference and\n406\toutline the corresponding challenges.\n407\t3.1. Database Construction and Performance Test\n408\tBased on the common LIBERO datasets (Liu et al., 2023)\n409\t(details in Appendix B), we first construct a robust vector\n410\tdatabase. Leveraging the Qdrant (Qdrant Team, 2023) in-\n411\tfrastructure, we define key components including vector\n412\trepresentation, database structure, and sharding strategy,\n413\twith details provided in Appendix C. To maximize retrieval\n414\taccuracy, all data from the LIBERO dataset are incorpo-\n415\tTable 1.Database Performance on LIBERO Benchmark\n416\tModel Environment VLA Inference Database Retrieval\n417\tSR Speed SR Speed\n418\tOpenVLA\n419\tLIBERO-Goal 77.0% 1.00× 62.0% 4.17×\n420\tLIBERO-Object 71.2% 1.00× 68.0% 4.83×\n421\tLIBERO-Spatial 82.8% 1.00× 53.0% 3.98×\n422\tLIBERO-Long 54.4% 1.00× 18.0% 3.74×\n423\trated into the database. Necessary vector data statistics,\n424\tretrieval tests, retrieval latency and confidence analysis of\n425\tthe database are conducted in Appendix C.2.\n426\tFurthermore, we only use database retrieval to finish various\n427\ttasks in the LIBERO (Liu et al., 2023) benchmark. For\n428\tcomparison, we report the Success Rate (SR) and speed\n429\tof the OpenVLA model (Kim et al., 2024) inference. As\n430\tshown in Tab. 1,models relying solely on database retrieval\n431\tcan still complete certain tasks (e.g., 68.0% in simple task\n432\tsuite like Goal) with high speed (3.74×∼4.83×). Moreover,\n433\tthe database remains effective even on challenging task\n434\tsuites (e.g., Spatial and Long). Overall, the task completion\n435\trate of database retrieval is lower than that of VLA model\n436\tinference. We also evaluate the performance of database\n437\tscaling and find that scale expansion does not improve the\n438\tSR.(Appendix C.2).\n439\t3.2. Database Retrieval Trajectory Analysis\n440\tWe further compare the kinematic trajectories (in both Sim-\n441\tulation and real-world environments) comes from database\n442\tretrieval and VLA inference. In Fig. 2 (a) (where both\n443\tretrieval and inference succeed), numerous trajectory seg-\n444\tments from the database and VLA inference overlap signifi-\n445\tcantly (green region), confirming the precision of retrieved\n446\tresults in these segments. Though some segments occur\n447\tbiased with the trajectory of VLA inference (red region),\n448\tsince most segments are accurate, the final endpoints can be\n449\tmatched (i.e. task success). In Fig. 2 (b) (where retrieval"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e6527c94-f67f-47a9-849d-c5fe31116d02","uuid":"3c16232c-3ba9-44ef-b6d0-52d08a251ea2","timestamp":"2026-04-25T20:01:51.487Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/papers/41c60725-bb92-47f2-acf8-07f0b99647fb.txt","content":"049\n050\n051\n052\n053\n054\nHeiSD: Hybrid Speculative Decoding for Embodied\nVision-Language-Action Models with Kinematic Awareness\nAnonymous Authors1\nAbstract\nVision-Language-Action (VLA) Models have be-\ncome the mainstream solution for robot control,\nbut suffer from slow inference speeds. Specula-\ntive Decoding (SD) is a promising acceleration\nmethod which can be divided into two categories:\ndrafter-based SD and retrieval-based SD. Exist-\ning methods fail to analyze the advantages and\ndisadvantages of these two types of SD in VLA\nmodels, leading to their sole application or op-\ntimization. In this paper, we analyze the trajec-\ntory patterns of robots controlled by the VLA\nmodel and derive a key insight: the two types\nof SD should be used in a hybrid manner. How-\never, achieving hybrid SD in VLA models poses\nseveral challenges: (1) draft rejection and per-\nsistent errors in retrieval-based SD; (2) difficulty\nin determining the hybrid boundary. To address\nthese, we propose theHeiSDframework. We pro-\npose a retrieval-based SD optimization method in\nHeiSD,which contains a verify-skip mechanism\nand a sequence-wise relaxed acceptance strategy.\nMoreover, we proposed a kinematic-based fused\nmetric inHeiSDto automatically determine the\nhybrid boundary. Experimental results demon-\nstrate thatHeiSDattains a speedup of up to 2.45 ×\nin simulation benchmarks and 2.06×∼2.41× in\nreal-world scenarios, while sustaining a high task\nsuccess rate.\n1. Introduction\nVision-Language-Action (VLA) models have emerged as\nthe mainstream solution for Embodied Intelligence (Ma\net al., 2024; Zhang et al., 2024). Despite their impressive per-\nformance, the heavy computational demands of VLA mod-\nels limit their inference speed, preventing them from meet-\n1Anonymous Institution, Anonymous City, Anonymous Region,\nAnonymous Country. Correspondence to: Anonymous Author\n<anon.email@domain.com>.\nPreliminary work. Under review by the International Conference\non Machine Learning (ICML). Do not distribute.\ning real-time requirements (Wen et al., 2025; Budzianowski\net al., 2025). To boost the inference speed of VLA models,\nexisting work has integrated large-model inference optimiza-\ntion techniques into VLAs, covering: model architecture in-\nnovation (Liu et al., 2024a; Wen et al., 2025; Budzianowski\net al., 2025; Pertsch et al., 2025), model compression (Zheng\net al., 2025; 2026a; Park et al., 2024; Li et al., 2025), run-\ntime optimization (Zhang et al., 2025; Song et al., 2025; Yue\net al., 2024) and deployment design (Zheng et al., 2026c). In\nsuch runtime optimization methods, Speculative Decoding\n(SD) (Wang et al., 2025; Zheng et al., 2026b) is a promising\nmethod that can accelerate inference.\nThe essence of SD lies in employing low-cost methods to\nrapidly generate token sequences. These sequences then\nundergo parallel verification and selective acceptance by\nLarge Language Models (LLMs), thereby enhancing infer-\nence speed. Existing SD methods can be categorized into\ntwo types: drafter-based SD (Wen et al., 2024; Yan et al.,\n2025) and retrieval-based SD (Cho et al., 2025; He et al.,\n2024; Lee et al., 2025). Drafter-based SD leverages a small\nmodel (trained from scratch or fine-tuned) to generate draft\ntoken sequences. In contrast, retrieval-based SD does not\nrely on a dedicated draft model; instead, it uses a prebuilt\nvector database and retrieves relevant content from it to\nobtain draft token sequences.\nWhen being adapted for VLA models, both drafter-based\nand retrieval-based SD approaches exhibit distinct advan-\ntages and limitations. As Fig. 1 (a) shows, drafter-based\nSD can provide high-quality drafts with a high probability\nof passing verification. But it needs to bear the inference\noverhead of the draft model. Retrieval-based SD eliminates\nthe overhead of the draft model and has a higher theoretical\nspeedup, but suffers from low draft quality.\nIn this study, we first construct a database and develop an\nanalysis of retrieval drafts. Our analysis reveals that some\ntrajectory segments guided by retrieval drafts highly align\nwith VLA inference, while others exhibit deviations. Based\non this observation, we derive a key insight: employing\nretrieval-based SD for the overlapping segments and drafter-\nbased SD for the non-overlapping segments enables leverag-\ning the advantages of both SD approaches simultaneously.\n1\n055\n056\n057\n058\n059\n060\n061\n062\n063\n064\n065\n066\n067\n068\n069\n070\n071\n072\n073\n074\n075\n076\n077\n078\n079\n080\n081\n082\n083\n084\n085\n086\n087\n088\n089\n090\n091\n092\n093\n094\n095\n096\n097\n098\n099\n100\n101\n102\n103\n104\n105\n106\n107\n108\n109\nSubmission and Formatting Instructions for ICML 2026\nGeneration\nDraft QualityTheoreticalSpeedOverheadDraft-Based SDHighLowHighRetrieval-Based SDLowHighLow\n(b)\nVLAModel\na1a2a3a4\na'2a'3a'4a'1a'0\nDraft ModelDrafterInputDraft-Based SD\nVLAModel\na1a2a3a4\na'2a'3a'4a'1a'0\nDatabaseNo Drafter\nRetrievalInputRetrieval-Based SD\nStep\n(a) StepStepStepStepStep\nRobotControl\nMulti-StepInferenceofVLAModels\nRetrieval-Based SDDraft-Based SDRetrieval-Based SD\nRetrieval-BasedSDNeedsOptimizationChallenge1 HardtoDetermineHybridBoundaryChallenge2\nHeiSDFrameworkHybrid SDEmbodiedIntelligence=+Solution1 Solution2AdaptiveVerify-SkipSeq-WiseRelaxedAcceptKinematic-BasedFusedMetricforDetermineBoundary\nFigure 1.Overview of the ProposedHeiSDFramework\nHowever, achieving this kind of hybrid SD in VLA mod-\nels faces challenges. First, retrieval-based SD suffers from\nlow-quality drafts, which are hard to pass the verification\nprocess and cause persistent errors. Thus, specific optimiza-\ntion is needed for retrieval-based SD. Second, it is hard\nto determine the hybrid boundary, i.e., identifying which\nstep should employ drafter-based SD and which should use\nretrieval-based SD.\nTo address these challenges, we first propose an optimiza-\ntion method for retrieval-based SD. We propose an adaptive\nverify-skip mechanism that selectively skips the verification\nprocess for certain drafts to avoid strict rejection. Further-\nmore, we propose a sequence-wise relaxed acceptance strat-\negy to enhance the diversity of drafts during verification\nand accept drafts with minor bias without compromising\naccuracy, to avoid persistent errors.\nAfter that, we developed a kinematic-based fused metric\nto automatically determine the hybrid boundary, enabling\nautomatic decision and automatic switching during VLA\nmulti-step inference. These designs form an end-to-end\nhybrid SD framework for VLA models, calledHeiSD. We\nbelieveHeiSDwill play a role in the future development\nof embodied intelligence and community building. In sum-\nmary, our contributions are below:\n• We conducted a detailed analysis and gained key in-\nsights: hybrid using drafter-based SD and retrieval-\nbased SD in VLA models leads to better performance.\n• We optimize retrieval-based SD and propose an adap-\ntive verify-skip mechanism along with a sequence-wise\nrelaxed acceptance strategy.\n• We developed a kinematic-based fused metric to auto-\nmatically determine the hybrid boundary, thus forming\ntheHeiSDframework.\nExperimental results demonstrate thatHeiSDattains a\nspeedup of up to 2.45 × in simulation benchmarks and\n2.06×∼2.41× in real-world scenarios, while sustaining a\nhigh task success rate.\n2. Preliminary\n2.1. Vision-Language-Action Models\nVLA models usually comprise three core components (Kim\net al., 2024; Zitkovich et al., 2023): vision encoders (convert-\ning visual modality into tokens), an LLM backbone (fusing\nmulti-modal information and enabling reasoning), and an\naction de-tokenizer (decoding output tokens into actions).\naj = arg max\naj\n\u0002\nP(a j |a 0:j−1,O,P,W)\n\u0003\n.(1)\nEach VLA generation outputs an action slice, which is a\n7-dimensional vector representing 7 Degrees of Freedom\n(DoF): position X, Y, Z of the end gripper, joint rotation an-\ngles rX , rY , rZ, and a binary gripper control signalG. Each\nDoF is encoded as a tokenaj. VLA models autoregressively\npredict the most probable token aj based on the previously\ntokens a0:j−1, visual observations O, language prompts P,\nand the learnable model parametersW, as Eq. (1) shown.\n2.2. Speculative Decoding\nThe core idea of SD is to use low-cost methods for rapid to-\nken sequence acquisition and employ LLMs for parallel ver-\nification of these tokens, thus avoiding slow autoregressive\ngeneration. Existing SD falls into two categories: drafter-\nbased and retrieval-based. The former leverages a small\ndraft model MD to generate token sequences, and uses the\nLLM as a verification model MV . This process can be writ-\nten as Eq. (2), in which aj means the tokens, ft means the\nhidden features, ande t means the token embeddings.\nDraft:a j =M D(f1:t, e0:t, at+1:j−1).\nVerify:ˆaj =M V(a0:j−1,P,W),\n(\nˆaj =a j,Acpt.\nˆaj ̸=a j,Disc.\n(2)\nDraft:a j =\n\b\nRetri(f1:t, e0:t, at+1:j−1)\n\f\f ∈DB\n\t\n.(3)\n2\n110\n111\n112\n113\n114\n115\n116\n117\n118\n119\n120\n121\n122\n123\n124\n125\n126\n127\n128\n129\n130\n131\n132\n133\n134\n135\n136\n137\n138\n139\n140\n141\n142\n143\n144\n145\n146\n147\n148\n149\n150\n151\n152\n153\n154\n155\n156\n157\n158\n159\n160\n161\n162\n163\n164\nSubmission and Formatting Instructions for ICML 2026\nTrajectoryOverlap\nY-Dim\nZ-Dim\nSmallTrajectory Deviation\nEnd PointMatch\nVLA InferenceDB RetrievalTrajectory ofFailed Case(a)\nX-DimY-Dim\nZ-Dim\nTrajectory of SuccessfulCase\nTrajectoryOverlap\nEnvironment: LIBERO-GoalTask: Push Plate to the Front of the Stove\n(b)VLA InferenceDB Retrieval\nEnvironment: LIBERO-GoalTask: Push Plate to the Front of the Stove\nVLA Inference: SuccessDB Retrieval: Success\nLargeTrajectory Deviation\nEnd PointMismatchX-Dim\nVLA Inference: SuccessDB Retrieval: Failure\nInReal-World\nTrajectory\nTrajectory\nTrajectoryFragment\nInSimulation\nTrajectory\nTrajectoryAction\nViTLLMDe-Token\nInReal-WorldInSimulationRetrieval\nVectorDB\nAction\nHighSimilarity !\n(c)\nTrajectoryFragment\nFigure 2.Kinematic-Based Trajectory Analysis and Real-world/Simulation Validation for both VLA Inference and Database Retrieval\nIn contrast, retrieval-based SD does not need a draft model;\ninstead, it uses a database to retrieve draft token sequences.\nIts draft process can be written as Eq.(3), where DB means\nthe prebuilt database. When applied to VLA models, the\ntwo types of SD each have distinct advantages and draw-\nbacks. Drafter-based SD necessitates online maintenance\nof a draft model: while smaller than a VLA model, this\ndrafter still incurs memory consumption and additional com-\nputational overhead/latency, though its high-quality drafts\nsupport longer acceptable sequences and achieve actual ac-\nceleration. In contrast, retrieval-based SD eliminates the\noverhead associated with the drafter model and offers theo-\nretical performance benefits; however, the retrieved drafts\nsuffer from distribution mismatch, which hinders verifica-\ntion and restricts the theoretical acceleration.\n3. Observation and Motivation\nThis section first details the construction of the database\nand its performance test, then presents a database retrieval\ntrajectory analysis. Based on analysis results, we derive\ninsights into achieving hybrid SD in VLA inference and\noutline the corresponding challenges.\n3.1. Database Construction and Performance Test\nBased on the common LIBERO datasets (Liu et al., 2023)\n(details in Appendix B), we first construct a robust vector\ndatabase. Leveraging the Qdrant (Qdrant Team, 2023) in-\nfrastructure, we define key components including vector\nrepresentation, database structure, and sharding strategy,\nwith details provided in Appendix C. To maximize retrieval\naccuracy, all data from the LIBERO dataset are incorpo-\nTable 1.Database Performance on LIBERO Benchmark\nModel Environment VLA Inference Database Retrieval\nSR Speed SR Speed\nOpenVLA\nLIBERO-Goal 77.0% 1.00× 62.0% 4.17×\nLIBERO-Object 71.2% 1.00× 68.0% 4.83×\nLIBERO-Spatial 82.8% 1.00× 53.0% 3.98×\nLIBERO-Long 54.4% 1.00× 18.0% 3.74×\nrated into the database. Necessary vector data statistics,\nretrieval tests, retrieval latency and confidence analysis of\nthe database are conducted in Appendix C.2.\nFurthermore, we only use database retrieval to finish various\ntasks in the LIBERO (Liu et al., 2023) benchmark. For\ncomparison, we report the Success Rate (SR) and speed\nof the OpenVLA model (Kim et al., 2024) inference. As\nshown in Tab. 1,models relying solely on database retrieval\ncan still complete certain tasks (e.g., 68.0% in simple task\nsuite like Goal) with high speed (3.74×∼4.83×). Moreover,\nthe database remains effective even on challenging task\nsuites (e.g., Spatial and Long). Overall, the task completion\nrate of database retrieval is lower than that of VLA model\ninference. We also evaluate the performance of database\nscaling and find that scale expansion does not improve the\nSR.(Appendix C.2).\n3.2. Database Retrieval Trajectory Analysis\nWe further compare the kinematic trajectories (in both Sim-\nulation and real-world environments) comes from database\nretrieval and VLA inference. In Fig. 2 (a) (where both\nretrieval and inference succeed), numerous trajectory seg-\nments from the database and VLA inference overlap signifi-\ncantly (green region), confirming the precision of retrieved\nresults in these segments. Though some segments occur\nbiased with the trajectory of VLA inference (red region),\nsince most segments are accurate, the final endpoints can be\nmatched (i.e. task success). In Fig. 2 (b) (where retrieval","numLines":400,"startLine":50,"totalLines":2667}}}
