ure 3.Adaptive Verify-Skip Mechanism\n542\tfor overlapping trajectory segments, while VLA inference\n543\tis suitable for non-overlapping parts. The effectiveness of\n544\tdatabase retrieval for overlapping segments is validated in\n545\tboth simulated and real-world environments. As shown in\n546\tFig. 2 (c), database retrieval results for overlapping segments\n547\texhibit high similarity to those from VLA inference in terms\n548\tof start points, end points, and motion trajectories, but with\n549\thigher speed. Guided by this conclusion, implementing\n550\thybrid SD in VLA inference is a promising approach: it\n551\temploys retrieval-based SD in green regions and drafter-\n552\tbased SD in red regions, thereby preserving accuracy while\n553\tfurther enhancing speed to achieve a new Pareto Frontier.\n554\t3.3. Challenges of Achieving Hybrid SD\n555\tHowever, achieving hybrid SD in VLA inference is non-\n556\ttrivial, facing several challenges. First, as shown in Tab. 2,\n557\tachieving theoretical acceleration with retrieval-based SD\n558\tfor VLA models is hard, due to the following reasons: (1)\n559\tThe distribution of retrieved drafts mismatches that of VLA\n560\tinference results; thus, even if the trajectories overlap, re-\n561\ttrieved drafts rarely pass strict verification, leading to low\n562\taccept length (AL) and poor speedup. (2) Furthermore, due\n563\tto the absence of a drafter, the system repeatedly retrieves\n564\tidentical results from the database, leading to persistent re-\n565\tjects. Second, automatically determining the boundary of\n566\thybrid SD remains challenging. Although trajectory seg-\n567\tmentation is highly effective, the inability to predict the\n568\tcomplete trajectory during inference complicates the deter-\n569\tmination of segmentation boundaries.\n570\t4. Retrieval-Based SD Optimization\n571\tIn this section, we propose a novel verify-skip mechanism\n572\tand a seq-wise relax acceptance strategy, aiming to boost\n573\tretrieval-based SD to its theoretical speed.\n574\t4.1. Adaptive Verify-Skip Mechanism\n575\tDue to distributional misalignment with VLA inference\n576\toutputs, retrieved drafts often fail verification. Given the in-\n577\therent multi-solution nature of embodied tasks, we propose\n578\tomitting specific verification processes when such drafts are\n579\tsufficiently accurate. Therefore, a model-free selection strat-\n580\tegy is required in retrieval-based SD to identify which steps’\n581\tverification should be skipped. To achieve this, we capture\n582\tthe input features of the final layer (denoted as lm head)\n583\tduring the verification process of each retrieved draft. Exist-\n584\ting work (Zhang et al., 2025) proves that the input features\n585\tof the final layer in VLA models are the most critical and\n586\tmost relevant to downstream robotic tasks.\n587\tAs shown in Fig. 3 (a), the feature similarity of trajectory\n588\tpoints correlates with their distance: closer trajectory points\n589\texhibit higher feature similarity and should theoretically\n590\tbe directly accepted without verification, whereas farther\n591\ttrajectory points show lower similarity and should be less\n592\tlikely to skip verification. Inspired by these, we conduct\n593\ta verify-skip mechanism based on the feature similarity\n594\tpatterns of trajectory points. Specifically, we calculate the\n595\tfeature similarity for each track point based on the historical\n596\ttracks in the database. During this process, we collect the\n597\tminimum acceptable similarity and its corresponding point\n598\tdistance, as illustrated in the offline stage of Alg. 1.\n599\tWhen confronting a new task, we reuse the minimum accept-\n600\table similarity and point distance from historical informa-\n601\ttion to automatically determine which trajectory points in\n602\tthe new task are excessively similar and thus can be skipped.\n603\tMeanwhile, feedback signals are incorporated based on task\n604\tcompletion performance. Using these signals, the algorithm\n605\tautomatically updates the minimum acceptable similarity\n606\tAlgorithm 1Adaptive Verify-Skip Mechanism\n607\t①Offline Stage:\n608\tInput:Historical Trajectory Point P h\n609\ti , Number of Trajectory\n610\tPoint n, Distance d, Input Feature of lm head Layer F eatP h\n611\ti\n612\t,\n613\tPre-Sampling Similarity BoundaryT.\n614\tInit: F eatph\n615\ti\n616\t←Hook(lm head) after Inf er(P h\n617\ti |P h\n618\t1∼i−1);\n619\tInitializeS(·,·) = 0,min S = 0andO dist = 0.\n620\tfori= 1ton−1\n621\tford=iton−1\n622\tComputeS(F eat P h\n623\ti\n624\t, F eatP h\n625\ti+d\n626\t).\n627\tifmin S > S(F eat P h\n628\ti\n629\t, F eatP h\n630\ti+d\n631\t)> Tthen\n632\tminS, Odist ←S(F eat P h\n633\ti\n634\t, F eatP h\n635\ti+d\n636\t), d\n637\t②Online Stage:\n638\tInput:Total Task Trials ttotal, Trajectory Points of Current\n639\tTask P c\n640\ti , Number of Trajectory Points n, Last Task Feedback\n641\tBool SignalB t\n642\tInit:InitializeB n =T rue, Getmin S andO dist from①\n643\trepeat\n644\tfori= 1ton−1\n645\tford=iton−1\n646\tComputeS(F eat P c\n647\ti , F eatP c\n648\ti+d).\n649\tifB t =T ruethenmin S+=∆|Sc −min(S h)|, Odist ↑\n650\telseB t =T ruethenmin S-=∆|Sc −min(S h)|, Odist ↓\n651\tt++untilt=t total\n652\t4\n653\t220\n654\t221\n655\t222\n656\t223\n657\t224\n658\t225\n659\t226\n660\t227\n661\t228\n662\t229\n663\t230\n664\t231\n665\t232\n666\t233\n667\t234\n668\t235\n669\t236\n670\t237\n671\t238\n672\t239\n673\t240\n674\t241\n675\t242\n676\t243\n677\t244\n678\t245\n679\t246\n680\t247\n681\t248\n682\t249\n683\t250\n684\t251\n685\t252\n686\t253\n687\t254\n688\t255\n689\t256\n690\t257\n691\t258\n692\t259\n693\t260\n694\t261\n695\t262\n696\t263\n697\t264\n698\t265\n699\t266\n700\t267\n701\t268\n702\t269\n703\t270\n704\t271\n705\t272\n706\t273\n707\t274\n708\tSubmission and Formatting Instructions for ICML 2026\n709\tID:72ID:45ID:37\n710\tDraft TokenVerify Token\n711\tTop-KRetrieval\n712\tAction\n713\tVectorDB\n714\ta1a2a3a4a5a6a7\n715\tDefineXYZRXRYRZG\n716\ta1a2a3a4a5a6a7Seq 1Seq 2Seq 3XYZRXRYRZG\n717\tSeq 1Top-1\n718\tPosition-RelatedAngle-RelatedGripper\n719\tKDetail Seq 1Top-2Seq 2Top-1Seq 2Top-2Seq 2Top-3Seq 2Top-1Seq 2Top-2Seq 2Top-3Seq 3Top-1Seq 3Top-2Seq 3Top-3Seq 3Top-1Seq 3Top-2Seq 3Top-3\n720\tRoot\n721\tSeq-Wise Tree Decoding\n722\tUseTop-KSeqtobuildtheTree\n723\tSeq 1Top-1 Seq 1Top-2Seq 2Top-1Seq 2Top-2Seq 2Top-3Seq 2Top-1Seq 2Top-2Seq 2Top-3Seq 3Top-1Seq 3Top-2Seq 3Top-3Seq 3Top-1Seq 3Top-2Seq 3Top-3\n724\tRootDecoding of a Chaina1a2a3a4a5a6a7Seq 1Top-1Seq 2Top-1\n725\tVar:0\n726\ta'1a'2a'3a'4a'5a'6a'7\n727\tID:150ID:55ID:160\n728\tID:148ID:40ID:180ID:72ID:35ID:39\n729\t…ID:60\n730\tSeq-WiseRelaxAcceptance\n731\tDepth-FirstDecodingVar:10ID:91Var:2Var:2Var:15Var:20Var:31SmallToken Var.Small Seq Var.\n732\tHighToken Var.High Seq Var.\n733\tFigure 4.Sequence-Wise Relaxed Acceptance Strategy\n734\tand point distance after each task to enhance its performance\n735\tin subsequent tasks, as shown in the online stage of Alg. 1.\n736\tThis adaptive adjustment mechanism enables the skipping\n737\tof some trajectory point verification while allowing dynamic\n738\tadjustments, thereby achieving minimal accuracy loss.\n739\t4.2. Sequence-Wise Relaxed Acceptance Strategy\n740\tMerely addressing the issue that drafts fail to pass verifi-\n741\tcation is insufficient; retrieval-based SD also confronts the\n742\tproblem of persistent errors. If errors arise in the retrieved\n743\tdrafts, the database lacks correction capability, resulting\n744\tin repeated retrieval of the same erroneous drafts. Conse-\n745\tquently, the VLA model necessitates repeated verification,\n746\tfailing to achieve acceleration effects. To solve this problem,\n747\twe propose a sequence-wise relaxed acceptance strategy.\n748\tSpecifically, we first expand the retrieval draft by modify-\n749\ting the original Top-1 retrieval to Top-K matching. This\n750\tapproach can enhance the diversity of retrieved drafts. Fur-\n751\tthermore, we define sequences in the draft as a group that\n752\tcontains tokens with strong kinematic correlation. As shown\n753\tin Fig. 4, X, Y and Z denote the end-gripper positions (all\n754\tposition-related) and are thus grouped into a sequence; sim-\n755\tilarly, rX, rY and rZ represent the joint rotation angles (all\n756\tangle-related) and are also packed into a sequence. For G,\n757\twhich means the binary control signal of the gripper, we\n758\ttreat it as a separate sequence.\n759\tAfter that, we inherit the tree decoding backbone from Eagle-\n760\t2 (Li et al., 2024b). The key difference is that we construct\n761\tthe tree in a sequence-wise rather than a token-wise man-\n762\tner. Furthermore, when constructing the tree, we allow se-\n763\tquences from different retrieval results to connect with each\n764\tother to maximize the potential for draft generation, except\n765\tfor the sequence represented by the gripper. This exception\n766\tis justified by the strong correlation between the gripper\n767\tstate and task success rate. We verify each chain starting\n768\tfrom the root node in a depth-first manner. In this process,\n769\ta sequence-wise relaxed acceptance strategy is adopted to\n770\tincrease the probability of accepting diverse drafts, thereby\n771\treducing persistent errors. As shown in Fig. 4, we calculate\n772\tLargeRadius\n773\tY-Dim\n774\tZ-Dim\n775\tX-Dim\n776\t①\n777\t①\n778\t②③\n779\t④\n780\t②\n781\t③\n782\t④\n783\t⑤\n784\t⑤\n785\t①\n786\t②③④⑤\n787\tVLA InferenceDB Retrieval\n788\tSmallRadius\n789\tLargeDisplacement\n790\tSmallDisplacement\n791\tFusion\n792\tR[w]\n793\tD[w]D[w]\n794\tR[w]\n795\tRetrieval-BasedSD\n796\tDrafter-BasedSD\n797\tLargeRadiusSmallRadius\n798\tThreshold\n799\tLargeRadius\n800\tSmallRadius\n801\tFusion\n802\tVLA Inference–Curvature RadiusDB Retrieval–Curvature Radius\n803\tLargeDisplacementLargeDisplacementSmallDisplacement\n804\tVLA Inference–Cumulative DisplacementDB Retrieval–Cumulative Displacement\n805\tVLA Inference–FusedMetricDB Retrieval–Fused Metric\n806\tSmallDisplacement\n807\tEnd-point\n808\tEnd-point\n809\tFigure 5.Kinematic-Based Metric for Achieving Hybrid SD\n810\tthe index bias bias of each draft token and each verify token.\n811\tWhen the deviation of the entire sequence biasseq and that\n812\tof individual tokens biasaj are maintained within a specific\n813\trange, the entire sequence is accepted by enforcement. Note\n814\tthat we allow biasaj > biasseq, meaning a single token\n815\tmay exhibit a larger bias provided that the overall bias of\n816\tthe sequence remains small, which differs distinctly from ex-\n817\tisting token-level relaxed acceptance. After multiple trials,\n818\twe select biasseq = 30 and biasaj = 15 , which achieves\n819\tthe optimal trade-off between accuracy and speed. After all\n820\tchains are validated, if all candidates for a given sequence\n821\tare rejected, the VLA model is directly activated to generate\n822\tsubsequent tokens. This strategy, which combines top-K\n823\tretrieval with sequence-wise relaxed acceptance, effectively\n824\tmitigates the issue of persistent errors. In particular, no\n825\tdeviation is allowed for binary grippers, as the correctness\n826\tof the gripper is critical to task success.\n827\t5. Metric for Determining Hybrid Boundary\n828\tAfter optimizing retrieval-based SD, this section proposes\n829\ta novel kinematic-based metric to achieve hybrid SD and\n830\tautomatically determine its boundary during step-by-step\n831\tVLA model inference.\n832\t5.1. Issue Definition and Design Insights\n833\tAforementioned analysis in Section 3 shows that trajec-\n834\ttories from successful database retrievals exhibit greater\n835\toverlap with VLA model inference trajectories, whereas\n836\tthose from failed retrievals show less overlap. However,\n837\ttrajectory points are generated incrementally, and the com-\n838\tplete trajectory cannot be obtained during the multi-step\n839\tinference process. Therefore, a method is required to de-\n840\ttermine the hybrid boundary, i.e., which steps should adopt\n841\tretrieval-based SD and which should use drafter-based SD.\n842\tThrough in-depth analysis, we identify that these trajectory\n843\tsegments exhibit inherent kinematic characteristics (shown\n844\tin Fig. 5): Overlapping trajectory segments (green region)\n845\texhibit a larger curvature radius and cumulative displace-\n846\tment, whereas biased segments (red region) show a smaller\n847\t5\n848\t275\n849\t276\n850\t277\n851\t278\n852\t279\n853\t280\n854\t281\n855\t282\n856\t283\n857\t284\n858\t285\n859\t286\n860\t287\n861\t288\n862\t289\n863\t290\n864\t291\n865\t292\n866\t293\n867\t294\n868\t295\n869\t296\n870\t297\n871\t298\n872\t299\n873\t300\n874\t301\n875\t302\n876\t303\n877\t304\n878\t305\n879\t306\n880\t307\n881\t308\n882\t309\n883\t310\n884\t311\n885\t312\n886\t313\n887\t314\n888\t315\n889\t316\n890\t317\n891\t318\n892\t319\n893\t320\n894\t321\n895\t322\n896\t323\n897\t324\n898\t325\n899\t326\n900\t327\n901\t328\n902\t329\n903\tSubmission and Formatting Instructions for ICML 2026\n904\tone. Therefore, we decided to use these two characteristics\n905\tto design a metric to help determine the hybrid boundary.\n906\t5.2. Kinematic Characteristics of Trajectory Segments\n907\tAssuming that the trajectory context sliding window is w,\n908\teach trajectory point in the coordinate systemT(λ;O γ) con-\n909\ttains spatial position x, y, z, where λ represents the distance\n910\tscale and Oγ represents the origin point. First, we calculate\n911\tthe geometric center C= (u c, vc) of trajectory segments\n912\tand project it into 2-dimensional space to obtain the ba-\n913\tsis vector (u[w]\n914\ti , v[w]\n915\ti ), shown in Eq. (4). We use Eq. (5)\n916\tto iteratively update the optimal geometric center, which\n917\tEuclid\n918\t2-dim\n919\t(·;·) means 2-dimensional euclidean distance, and µ\n920\trepresents the mean. After that, we use Eq. (6) to calculate\n921\tthe curvature radius R[w]\n922\ti . In this way, we can scan the\n923\tchange ofR [w]\n924\ti in a sliding windoww.\n925\t(u[w]\n926\ti , v[w]\n927\ti ) =P roj\n928\t\u0000\n929\tP i\n930\tx,y,z − 1\n931\tw\n932\tw−1X\n933\ti\n934\tP i\n935\tx,y,z\n936\t\f\f ∈ T\n937\t\u0001\n938\t.(4)\n939\t(ˆuc,ˆvc) = min\n940\tC\n941\tw−1X\n942\ti\n943\t\u0010\n944\tEuclid\n945\t2-dim\n946\t\u0000\n947\t(u[w]\n948\ti , v[w]\n949\ti );C"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e6527c94-f67f-47a9-849d-c5fe31116d02","uuid":"44e3c344-82c6-4882-a088-f992ee3aeacb","timestamp":"2026-04-25T20:01:54.670Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/papers/41c60725-bb92-47f2-acf8-07f0b99647fb.txt","content":"failed but inference succeeded), such overlaps are scarce,\nresulting in endpoint mismatch.\nThus, we argue that database retrieval should be employed\nTable 2.Performance Comparison of Two Types of SD\nDataset VLA+SD (SpecVLA) Retrieval-Based SD\nSR AL Speed SR AL Speed\nLIBERO-Goal 71.0% 2.97 1.00× 77.0% 1.03 0.94×\nLIBERO-Object 62.4% 3.25 1.00× 76.0% 0.93 0.92×\nLIBERO-Spatial 80.4% 3.27 1.00× 78.0% 0.81 0.78×\nLIBERO-Long 46.2% 2.82 1.00× 50.2% 0.82 0.97×\n3\n165\n166\n167\n168\n169\n170\n171\n172\n173\n174\n175\n176\n177\n178\n179\n180\n181\n182\n183\n184\n185\n186\n187\n188\n189\n190\n191\n192\n193\n194\n195\n196\n197\n198\n199\n200\n201\n202\n203\n204\n205\n206\n207\n208\n209\n210\n211\n212\n213\n214\n215\n216\n217\n218\n219\nSubmission and Formatting Instructions for ICML 2026\nAction\nVLAModelViTLLMDe-TokenHistoricalTrajectorySegments\nLLM Block\nHook Feature for Each Trajectory Point\n①\n0.420.980.890.61\nFeatureof①Featureof②Featureof③Featureof④Featureof⑤\n②③④⑤ AttnFFNlm_headDe-TokenFeature Similarity\nHighLow\nFeature similarityrelated to thepoint distance\n0.970. 92\nFeatureof③Featureof④Featureof⑤…\nWhenFacingNewTask\n(a)\n(b)HistoricalFeatureSimilarityofTrajectoryPoints\nVerify\nVerifySkip\nVerifySkipSkipVerifySkipSkipVerify\nVerifySkipSkipVerifySkip\n…AdaptiveVerify-SkipVerifySkipVerify\n1～n2～n3～n4～n\nOnHistoricalTrajectoriesinDB\n①②③④⑤ AdaptiveAlgorithmIndicators\n…\nFigure 3.Adaptive Verify-Skip Mechanism\nfor overlapping trajectory segments, while VLA inference\nis suitable for non-overlapping parts. The effectiveness of\ndatabase retrieval for overlapping segments is validated in\nboth simulated and real-world environments. As shown in\nFig. 2 (c), database retrieval results for overlapping segments\nexhibit high similarity to those from VLA inference in terms\nof start points, end points, and motion trajectories, but with\nhigher speed. Guided by this conclusion, implementing\nhybrid SD in VLA inference is a promising approach: it\nemploys retrieval-based SD in green regions and drafter-\nbased SD in red regions, thereby preserving accuracy while\nfurther enhancing speed to achieve a new Pareto Frontier.\n3.3. Challenges of Achieving Hybrid SD\nHowever, achieving hybrid SD in VLA inference is non-\ntrivial, facing several challenges. First, as shown in Tab. 2,\nachieving theoretical acceleration with retrieval-based SD\nfor VLA models is hard, due to the following reasons: (1)\nThe distribution of retrieved drafts mismatches that of VLA\ninference results; thus, even if the trajectories overlap, re-\ntrieved drafts rarely pass strict verification, leading to low\naccept length (AL) and poor speedup. (2) Furthermore, due\nto the absence of a drafter, the system repeatedly retrieves\nidentical results from the database, leading to persistent re-\njects. Second, automatically determining the boundary of\nhybrid SD remains challenging. Although trajectory seg-\nmentation is highly effective, the inability to predict the\ncomplete trajectory during inference complicates the deter-\nmination of segmentation boundaries.\n4. Retrieval-Based SD Optimization\nIn this section, we propose a novel verify-skip mechanism\nand a seq-wise relax acceptance strategy, aiming to boost\nretrieval-based SD to its theoretical speed.\n4.1. Adaptive Verify-Skip Mechanism\nDue to distributional misalignment with VLA inference\noutputs, retrieved drafts often fail verification. Given the in-\nherent multi-solution nature of embodied tasks, we propose\nomitting specific verification processes when such drafts are\nsufficiently accurate. Therefore, a model-free selection strat-\negy is required in retrieval-based SD to identify which steps’\nverification should be skipped. To achieve this, we capture\nthe input features of the final layer (denoted as lm head)\nduring the verification process of each retrieved draft. Exist-\ning work (Zhang et al., 2025) proves that the input features\nof the final layer in VLA models are the most critical and\nmost relevant to downstream robotic tasks.\nAs shown in Fig. 3 (a), the feature similarity of trajectory\npoints correlates with their distance: closer trajectory points\nexhibit higher feature similarity and should theoretically\nbe directly accepted without verification, whereas farther\ntrajectory points show lower similarity and should be less\nlikely to skip verification. Inspired by these, we conduct\na verify-skip mechanism based on the feature similarity\npatterns of trajectory points. Specifically, we calculate the\nfeature similarity for each track point based on the historical\ntracks in the database. During this process, we collect the\nminimum acceptable similarity and its corresponding point\ndistance, as illustrated in the offline stage of Alg. 1.\nWhen confronting a new task, we reuse the minimum accept-\nable similarity and point distance from historical informa-\ntion to automatically determine which trajectory points in\nthe new task are excessively similar and thus can be skipped.\nMeanwhile, feedback signals are incorporated based on task\ncompletion performance. Using these signals, the algorithm\nautomatically updates the minimum acceptable similarity\nAlgorithm 1Adaptive Verify-Skip Mechanism\n①Offline Stage:\nInput:Historical Trajectory Point P h\ni , Number of Trajectory\nPoint n, Distance d, Input Feature of lm head Layer F eatP h\ni\n,\nPre-Sampling Similarity BoundaryT.\nInit: F eatph\ni\n←Hook(lm head) after Inf er(P h\ni |P h\n1∼i−1);\nInitializeS(·,·) = 0,min S = 0andO dist = 0.\nfori= 1ton−1\nford=iton−1\nComputeS(F eat P h\ni\n, F eatP h\ni+d\n).\nifmin S > S(F eat P h\ni\n, F eatP h\ni+d\n)> Tthen\nminS, Odist ←S(F eat P h\ni\n, F eatP h\ni+d\n), d\n②Online Stage:\nInput:Total Task Trials ttotal, Trajectory Points of Current\nTask P c\ni , Number of Trajectory Points n, Last Task Feedback\nBool SignalB t\nInit:InitializeB n =T rue, Getmin S andO dist from①\nrepeat\nfori= 1ton−1\nford=iton−1\nComputeS(F eat P c\ni , F eatP c\ni+d).\nifB t =T ruethenmin S+=∆|Sc −min(S h)|, Odist ↑\nelseB t =T ruethenmin S-=∆|Sc −min(S h)|, Odist ↓\nt++untilt=t total\n4\n220\n221\n222\n223\n224\n225\n226\n227\n228\n229\n230\n231\n232\n233\n234\n235\n236\n237\n238\n239\n240\n241\n242\n243\n244\n245\n246\n247\n248\n249\n250\n251\n252\n253\n254\n255\n256\n257\n258\n259\n260\n261\n262\n263\n264\n265\n266\n267\n268\n269\n270\n271\n272\n273\n274\nSubmission and Formatting Instructions for ICML 2026\nID:72ID:45ID:37\nDraft TokenVerify Token\nTop-KRetrieval\nAction\nVectorDB\na1a2a3a4a5a6a7\nDefineXYZRXRYRZG\na1a2a3a4a5a6a7Seq 1Seq 2Seq 3XYZRXRYRZG\nSeq 1Top-1\nPosition-RelatedAngle-RelatedGripper\nKDetail Seq 1Top-2Seq 2Top-1Seq 2Top-2Seq 2Top-3Seq 2Top-1Seq 2Top-2Seq 2Top-3Seq 3Top-1Seq 3Top-2Seq 3Top-3Seq 3Top-1Seq 3Top-2Seq 3Top-3\nRoot\nSeq-Wise Tree Decoding\nUseTop-KSeqtobuildtheTree\nSeq 1Top-1 Seq 1Top-2Seq 2Top-1Seq 2Top-2Seq 2Top-3Seq 2Top-1Seq 2Top-2Seq 2Top-3Seq 3Top-1Seq 3Top-2Seq 3Top-3Seq 3Top-1Seq 3Top-2Seq 3Top-3\nRootDecoding of a Chaina1a2a3a4a5a6a7Seq 1Top-1Seq 2Top-1\nVar:0\na'1a'2a'3a'4a'5a'6a'7\nID:150ID:55ID:160\nID:148ID:40ID:180ID:72ID:35ID:39\n…ID:60\nSeq-WiseRelaxAcceptance\nDepth-FirstDecodingVar:10ID:91Var:2Var:2Var:15Var:20Var:31SmallToken Var.Small Seq Var.\nHighToken Var.High Seq Var.\nFigure 4.Sequence-Wise Relaxed Acceptance Strategy\nand point distance after each task to enhance its performance\nin subsequent tasks, as shown in the online stage of Alg. 1.\nThis adaptive adjustment mechanism enables the skipping\nof some trajectory point verification while allowing dynamic\nadjustments, thereby achieving minimal accuracy loss.\n4.2. Sequence-Wise Relaxed Acceptance Strategy\nMerely addressing the issue that drafts fail to pass verifi-\ncation is insufficient; retrieval-based SD also confronts the\nproblem of persistent errors. If errors arise in the retrieved\ndrafts, the database lacks correction capability, resulting\nin repeated retrieval of the same erroneous drafts. Conse-\nquently, the VLA model necessitates repeated verification,\nfailing to achieve acceleration effects. To solve this problem,\nwe propose a sequence-wise relaxed acceptance strategy.\nSpecifically, we first expand the retrieval draft by modify-\ning the original Top-1 retrieval to Top-K matching. This\napproach can enhance the diversity of retrieved drafts. Fur-\nthermore, we define sequences in the draft as a group that\ncontains tokens with strong kinematic correlation. As shown\nin Fig. 4, X, Y and Z denote the end-gripper positions (all\nposition-related) and are thus grouped into a sequence; sim-\nilarly, rX, rY and rZ represent the joint rotation angles (all\nangle-related) and are also packed into a sequence. For G,\nwhich means the binary control signal of the gripper, we\ntreat it as a separate sequence.\nAfter that, we inherit the tree decoding backbone from Eagle-\n2 (Li et al., 2024b). The key difference is that we construct\nthe tree in a sequence-wise rather than a token-wise man-\nner. Furthermore, when constructing the tree, we allow se-\nquences from different retrieval results to connect with each\nother to maximize the potential for draft generation, except\nfor the sequence represented by the gripper. This exception\nis justified by the strong correlation between the gripper\nstate and task success rate. We verify each chain starting\nfrom the root node in a depth-first manner. In this process,\na sequence-wise relaxed acceptance strategy is adopted to\nincrease the probability of accepting diverse drafts, thereby\nreducing persistent errors. As shown in Fig. 4, we calculate\nLargeRadius\nY-Dim\nZ-Dim\nX-Dim\n①\n①\n②③\n④\n②\n③\n④\n⑤\n⑤\n①\n②③④⑤\nVLA InferenceDB Retrieval\nSmallRadius\nLargeDisplacement\nSmallDisplacement\nFusion\nR[w]\nD[w]D[w]\nR[w]\nRetrieval-BasedSD\nDrafter-BasedSD\nLargeRadiusSmallRadius\nThreshold\nLargeRadius\nSmallRadius\nFusion\nVLA Inference–Curvature RadiusDB Retrieval–Curvature Radius\nLargeDisplacementLargeDisplacementSmallDisplacement\nVLA Inference–Cumulative DisplacementDB Retrieval–Cumulative Displacement\nVLA Inference–FusedMetricDB Retrieval–Fused Metric\nSmallDisplacement\nEnd-point\nEnd-point\nFigure 5.Kinematic-Based Metric for Achieving Hybrid SD\nthe index bias bias of each draft token and each verify token.\nWhen the deviation of the entire sequence biasseq and that\nof individual tokens biasaj are maintained within a specific\nrange, the entire sequence is accepted by enforcement. Note\nthat we allow biasaj > biasseq, meaning a single token\nmay exhibit a larger bias provided that the overall bias of\nthe sequence remains small, which differs distinctly from ex-\nisting token-level relaxed acceptance. After multiple trials,\nwe select biasseq = 30 and biasaj = 15 , which achieves\nthe optimal trade-off between accuracy and speed. After all\nchains are validated, if all candidates for a given sequence\nare rejected, the VLA model is directly activated to generate\nsubsequent tokens. This strategy, which combines top-K\nretrieval with sequence-wise relaxed acceptance, effectively\nmitigates the issue of persistent errors. In particular, no\ndeviation is allowed for binary grippers, as the correctness\nof the gripper is critical to task success.\n5. Metric for Determining Hybrid Boundary\nAfter optimizing retrieval-based SD, this section proposes\na novel kinematic-based metric to achieve hybrid SD and\nautomatically determine its boundary during step-by-step\nVLA model inference.\n5.1. Issue Definition and Design Insights\nAforementioned analysis in Section 3 shows that trajec-\ntories from successful database retrievals exhibit greater\noverlap with VLA model inference trajectories, whereas\nthose from failed retrievals show less overlap. However,\ntrajectory points are generated incrementally, and the com-\nplete trajectory cannot be obtained during the multi-step\ninference process. Therefore, a method is required to de-\ntermine the hybrid boundary, i.e., which steps should adopt\nretrieval-based SD and which should use drafter-based SD.\nThrough in-depth analysis, we identify that these trajectory\nsegments exhibit inherent kinematic characteristics (shown\nin Fig. 5): Overlapping trajectory segments (green region)\nexhibit a larger curvature radius and cumulative displace-\nment, whereas biased segments (red region) show a smaller\n5\n275\n276\n277\n278\n279\n280\n281\n282\n283\n284\n285\n286\n287\n288\n289\n290\n291\n292\n293\n294\n295\n296\n297\n298\n299\n300\n301\n302\n303\n304\n305\n306\n307\n308\n309\n310\n311\n312\n313\n314\n315\n316\n317\n318\n319\n320\n321\n322\n323\n324\n325\n326\n327\n328\n329\nSubmission and Formatting Instructions for ICML 2026\none. Therefore, we decided to use these two characteristics\nto design a metric to help determine the hybrid boundary.\n5.2. Kinematic Characteristics of Trajectory Segments\nAssuming that the trajectory context sliding window is w,\neach trajectory point in the coordinate systemT(λ;O γ) con-\ntains spatial position x, y, z, where λ represents the distance\nscale and Oγ represents the origin point. First, we calculate\nthe geometric center C= (u c, vc) of trajectory segments\nand project it into 2-dimensional space to obtain the ba-\nsis vector (u[w]\ni , v[w]\ni ), shown in Eq. (4). We use Eq. (5)\nto iteratively update the optimal geometric center, which\nEuclid\n2-dim\n(·;·) means 2-dimensional euclidean distance, and µ\nrepresents the mean. After that, we use Eq. (6) to calculate\nthe curvature radius R[w]\ni . In this way, we can scan the\nchange ofR [w]\ni in a sliding windoww.\n(u[w]\ni , v[w]\ni ) =P roj\n\u0000\nP i\nx,y,z − 1\nw\nw−1X\ni\nP i\nx,y,z\n\f\f ∈ T\n\u0001\n.(4)\n(ˆuc,ˆvc) = min\nC\nw−1X\ni\n\u0010\nEuclid\n2-dim\n\u0000\n(u[w]\ni , v[w]\ni );C","numLines":500,"startLine":450,"totalLines":2667}}}
