{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01VdEnvvh8iHrZtVcVDNHxwJ","type":"tool_result","content":"950\t\u0001\n951\t−µ\n952\t\u00112\n953\t.(5)\n954\tR[w] = 1\n955\tw\n956\tw−1X\n957\ti\n958\tEuclid\n959\t2-dim\n960\t\u0010\n961\t(u[w]\n962\ti , v[w]\n963\ti ); (ˆuc,ˆvc)\n964\t\u0011\n965\t.(6)\n966\tAssume D[w] means the cumulative displacement in the slid-\n967\ting window w. We use Euclid\n968\t3-dim\n969\t(·;·) to calculate the displace-\n970\tment between two adjacent points. Then, we summarize all\n971\tthe displacements to obtain D[w] (Eq. 7). Considering that\n972\tthe robot sometimes performs round-trip or circular motion,\n973\tD[w] does not consider the displacement direction.\n974\tD[w] =\n975\tw−1X\n976\ti\n977\tEuclid\n978\t3-dim\n979\t\u0010\n980\t(P i\n981\tx,y,z\n982\t\f\f ∈ T);\n983\t\u0000\n984\tP i+1\n985\tx,y,z\n986\t\f\f ∈ T)\n987\t\u0011\n988\t.(7)\n989\t5.3. Kinematic-Based Fused Metric\n990\tWe fuse R[w] and D[w] based on Eq. (8) to obtain a fused\n991\tmetric F [w]. N orm(·) means the normalization operation,\n992\twhich is detailed in Appendix D. Conceptually, a larger\n993\tF [w] means faster movement and a trajectory closer to a\n994\tstraight line (representing coarse-grained action); a smaller\n995\tF [w] results in slower movement, a more curved trajectory,\n996\tand fine-grained operation.\n997\tF [w] =α·N orm\n998\t\u0000\n999\tR[w]\n1000\ti\n1001\t\u0001\n1002\t+ (1−α)·N orm\n1003\t\u0000\n1004\tD[w]\n1005\ti\n1006\t\u0001\n1007\t.(8)\n1008\tAs shown in Fig. 5, F [w] integrates R[w]\n1009\ti and D[w]\n1010\ti to com-\n1011\tprehensively characterize the trajectory. We identify a\n1012\tthreshold to serve as the demarcation between retrieval-\n1013\tbased SD and drafter-based SD. Specifically, whenF [w] at\n1014\tMetricDatabaseViT DraftLLMEmbedViTForward()\n1015\tRetriSimilarity()Top-K()\n1016\tAction\n1017\tVerifyLLMForward()\n1018\tCPUGPU\n1019\tRobot\n1020\tExeDe-Token()Control()\n1021\tVisionInfo.\n1022\tGenDrafterForward()\n1023\tVLAPeakDBPeakGPUTypeGPUGMEMResult\n1024\t16.6GB8.8GB\n1025\tRTX309024GBOOM\n1026\t❌RTX409024GBOOM\n1027\t❌RTX509024GB/32GBOOM\n1028\t❌A10040GB/80GBOK\n1029\t✅H10080GB/94GBOK\n1030\t✅\n1031\tOffloadingtheDatabasetoCPU\n1032\tHeiSDFrameworkComputationFlow\n1033\tEmbeddings｜fromGPU to CPU:Embed-dim= 4352-dim Vec @FP16Latency = 0.25ms (BW 32GB/s)Retrieved Draft｜fromCPU to GPU:Draft-dim = 7-dim Vec @FP16Latency: Negligible(BW 32GB/s)\n1034\tDataMovement – ACase\n1035\tSeq-WiseRelaxedAccept\n1036\tDafter\n1037\tIfR-SD\n1038\tElse S-SDDraftLLMVerifyLLMForward()\n1039\tIfVerify-SkipElse\n1040\tFigure 6.System Implementation ofHeiSDFramework\n1041\tthe current step exceeds the threshold, retrieval-based SD\n1042\tis selected, as bothR [w]\n1043\ti andD [w]\n1044\ti at this step are relatively\n1045\tlarge, which should align with the trajectory inferred by\n1046\tVLA; otherwise, drafter-based SD is chosen.\n1047\t6.HeiSDFramework Implementation\n1048\tThis section outlines key considerations forHeiSDframe-\n1049\twork implementation, covering cost accounting, hardware\n1050\tmapping and overall computation flow.\n1051\t6.1. Cost Accounting and Hardware Mapping\n1052\tWe develop pre-implementation cost accounting (Fig. 6) to\n1053\treveal that most consumer GPUs encounter Out-of-Memory\n1054\t(OOM) issues when hosting both the database component\n1055\tand the VLA model; thus, to ensure compatibility with\n1056\tmainstream hardware, the database is deployed in CPU\n1057\tmemory to reduce GPU memory overhead. This hetero-\n1058\tgeneous collaborative deployment necessitates GPU-CPU\n1059\tcommunications, whose detailed costing (Fig. 6) shows neg-\n1060\tligible overhead (>100 ms) in a single inference process,\n1061\tfar below that of model inference, validating the feasibility\n1062\tand effectiveness of this deployment strategy.\n1063\t6.2. Overall Computation Flow\n1064\tWe use 5000 lines of code to implement theHeiSDframe-\n1065\twork. Its overall computation flow is shown in Fig. 6. First,\n1066\tvisual information is encoded into embeddings using a ViT\n1067\ton the GPU. Then, based on the prior trajectory, our fused\n1068\tmetric determines the type of SD to be adopted. If the\n1069\tretrieval-based SD is used, the embeddings are transmitted\n1070\tto the CPU for retrieval, which includes similarity com-\n1071\tputation and Top-K selection. When drafter-based SD is\n1072\temployed, the embeddings remain on the GPU and are input\n1073\tto the drafter for draft generation. For the retrieved drafts,\n1074\tthey are first moved back to the GPU. Then the adaptive\n1075\tverify-skip mechanism determines whether a draft should\n1076\tskip verification. If skipped, the draft is executed directly;\n1077\t6\n1078\t330\n1079\t331\n1080\t332\n1081\t333\n1082\t334\n1083\t335\n1084\t336\n1085\t337\n1086\t338\n1087\t339\n1088\t340\n1089\t341\n1090\t342\n1091\t343\n1092\t344\n1093\t345\n1094\t346\n1095\t347\n1096\t348\n1097\t349\n1098\t350\n1099\t351\n1100\t352\n1101\t353\n1102\t354\n1103\t355\n1104\t356\n1105\t357\n1106\t358\n1107\t359\n1108\t360\n1109\t361\n1110\t362\n1111\t363\n1112\t364\n1113\t365\n1114\t366\n1115\t367\n1116\t368\n1117\t369\n1118\t370\n1119\t371\n1120\t372\n1121\t373\n1122\t374\n1123\t375\n1124\t376\n1125\t377\n1126\t378\n1127\t379\n1128\t380\n1129\t381\n1130\t382\n1131\t383\n1132\t384\n1133\tSubmission and Formatting Instructions for ICML 2026\n1134\totherwise, verification is performed under our sequence-\n1135\twise relaxed acceptance strategy. For drafts generated by\n1136\tthe drafter, since they already reside on the GPU, we directly\n1137\tperform verification. All verification processes occur on the\n1138\tGPU. We will show that this CPU+GPU implementation\n1139\toffers advantages over the GPU-only deployment below.\n1140\t7. Experiments\n1141\t7.1. Setup\n1142\tWe testHeiSDbased on OpenVLA (Kim et al., 2024) model\n1143\tclusters in LIBERO (Liu et al., 2023) simulation benchmark\n1144\tand real-world environment. We build a single LLaMA\n1145\tblock (Touvron et al., 2023) as a draft model to build drafter-\n1146\tbased SD. We train the draft models based on the Deep-\n1147\tSpeed (Rasley et al., 2020) framework, which takes 8 hours\n1148\twith 2*NVIDIA A100 GPUs. We build retrieval-based SD\n1149\tusing the pre-built database. Both types of SD are appli-\n1150\tcable to OpenVLA as the validation model. Since there is\n1151\tno similar work, we choose pure drafter-based SD (Pure\n1152\tD-SD), pure retrieval-based SD (Pure R-SD), and SOTA\n1153\twork SpecVLA (Wang et al., 2025) with token-level relaxed\n1154\tacceptance as the baselines. We use an Nvidia A100 GPU\n1155\tand an Intel Xeon Silver 4410T as hardware platform.\n1156\t7.2. Evaluation Results\n1157\tSimulation Results.We utilize four LIBERO task suites\n1158\tto evaluateHeiSDand each suite contains 10 tasks. For\n1159\teach task, we conduct 50 trials for testing. We report the\n1160\tresults in Tab. 3. Compared with autoregressive inference,\n1161\tHeiSDachieves 1.79 ×∼2.45× speed up. Compared with\n1162\tPure D-SD and Pure R-SD,HeiSDalso delivers significant\n1163\tacceleration effects. This confirms that our choice to hy-\n1164\tbridize two types of SD during VLA reasoning is highly\n1165\teffective. Moreover, even compared with SOTA works like\n1166\tSpecVLA,HeiSDachieves 1.51 ×∼2.22× speedup with bet-\n1167\tter SR. This demonstrates that the hybrid use of two SD\n1168\tmethods in the VLA reasoning process yields a superior\n1169\tPareto frontier. Fig. 7 presents the proportions of two types\n1170\tof SD and verify-skip across four environments, explaining\n1171\tthe source of acceleration. Moreover,HeiSDachieves an\n1172\tincreased acceptance length (AL) of about 4.75∼4.96. The\n1173\timprovement in AL primarily stems from our optimization\n1174\tof retrieval-based SD. First, our verify-skip mechanism ef-\n1175\tfectively extends AL, as drafts with skipped verification are\n1176\ttreated as fully accepted. Second, our proposed sequence-\n1177\twise relaxed acceptance strategy allows some biased tokens\n1178\tto be accepted alongside the sequence.\n1179\tReal-World Results.We construct a tabletop operating en-\n1180\tvironment (Appendix E.1), and employ the AgileX PIPER\n1181\trobot arm (Appendix E.2) to testHeiSD’s performance in\n1182\treal-world scenarios. We build various manipulation tasks\n1183\tLIBERO-Goal LIBERO-SpatialLIBERO-ObjectLIBERO-Long\n1184\tD-SD R-SDSkipVerifyR-SDw/Verify\n1185\tFigure 7.Discussion of Hyper-ParameterwinHeiSD\n1186\t(Appendix E.3). We collect massive human demonstration\n1187\tdata (Appendix E.4) to rebuild the database and fine-tune the\n1188\tmodels. After that, we deployHeiSDinto the real world and\n1189\ttest its performance. The results are shown in Tab. 4. On\n1190\tthe three task categories we defined (with SR of 87.2%,\n1191\t77.3%, and 71.7% after fine-tuning),HeiSDachieves a\n1192\t2.06×∼2.41× speedup with minor SR loss (1.2%∼3.9%).\n1193\tWe also represent an example real-world task completion\n1194\tprocess in Fig. 8 to show the performance.\n1195\tAblation Studies.We conduct ablation studies on the\n1196\tLIBERO-Goal benchmark to evaluate the effects ofHeiSD’s\n1197\tcomponents, with corresponding results reported in Tab. 4.\n1198\tWhen Hybrid SD is implemented solely based on fusion met-\n1199\trics, the boundaries between retrieval-based SD and drafter-\n1200\tbased SD are defined; however, the overall performance\n1201\tremains suboptimal due to unresolved issues in retrieval-\n1202\tbased SD. Specifically, it achieves an SR of 74.0% but\n1203\texhibits nearly no acceleration, with an average accepted\n1204\tlength of only 1.05. Building on this foundation, we incorpo-\n1205\trate the adaptive verify-skip mechanism, which significantly\n1206\tenhances performance. It achieves a 2.08 × speedup with\n1207\tonly a slight drop (1.0%) in accuracy, while the AL is also\n1208\tincreased to 4.04. Further, after adding the sequence-wise\n1209\trelaxed acceptance, it achieves 2.38 × speedup (0.3× in-\n1210\tcreasing) and an AL of 4.50, while maintaining 73.0% SR.\n1211\tTable 3.Simulation Results ofHeiSD\n1212\tEnv. Method SR Speed AL Steps HW\n1213\tLIBERO-Goal\n1214\tAR w/o SD 77.0% 1.00× – 157.6 GPU\n1215\tPure R-SD 77.0% 0.96× 1.03 152.6 CPU+GPU\n1216\tPure D-SD 76.2% 0.87× 1.68 159.2 GPU\n1217\tSpecVLA 71.0% 1.23× 3.63 166.8 GPU\n1218\tHeiSD 73.0% 2.38× 4.75 156.3 CPU+GPU\n1219\tLIBERO-Object\n1220\tAR w/o SD 71.2% 1.00× – 191.7 GPU\n1221\tPure R-SD 76.0% 0.98× 0.93 195.4 GPU\n1222\tPure D-SD 68.6% 0.96× 1.84 195.9 GPU\n1223\tSpecVLA 62.4% 1.10× 3.91 214.5 GPU\n1224\tHeiSD 71.0% 2.45× 4.94 189.6 CPU+GPU\n1225\tLIBERO-Spatial\n1226\tAR w/o SD 82.8% 1.00× – 126.9 GPU\n1227\tpure R-SD 78.0% 1.15× 0.81 123.5 GPU\n1228\tPure D-SD 82.8% 0.98× 1.65 127.3 GPU\n1229\tSpecVLA 80.4% 1.26× 3.80 128.7 GPU\n1230\tHeiSD 78.0% 1.90× 4.83 127.8 CPU+GPU\n1231\tLIBERO-Long\n1232\tAR w/o SD 54.4% 1.00× – 393.2 GPU\n1233\tPure R-SD 50.0% 0.99× 0.81 399.3 GPU\n1234\tPure D-SD 50.2% 0.91× 1.59 400.7 GPU\n1235\tSpecVLA 46.2% 1.13× 3.63 439.6 GPU\n1236\tHeiSD 47.0% 1.79× 4.96 428.0 CPU+GPU\n1237\t7\n1238\t385\n1239\t386\n1240\t387\n1241\t388\n1242\t389\n1243\t390\n1244\t391\n1245\t392\n1246\t393\n1247\t394\n1248\t395\n1249\t396\n1250\t397\n1251\t398\n1252\t399\n1253\t400\n1254\t401\n1255\t402\n1256\t403\n1257\t404\n1258\t405\n1259\t406\n1260\t407\n1261\t408\n1262\t409\n1263\t410\n1264\t411\n1265\t412\n1266\t413\n1267\t414\n1268\t415\n1269\t416\n1270\t417\n1271\t418\n1272\t419\n1273\t420\n1274\t421\n1275\t422\n1276\t423\n1277\t424\n1278\t425\n1279\t426\n1280\t427\n1281\t428\n1282\t429\n1283\t430\n1284\t431\n1285\t432\n1286\t433\n1287\t434\n1288\t435\n1289\t436\n1290\t437\n1291\t438\n1292\t439\n1293\tSubmission and Formatting Instructions for ICML 2026\n1294\tRetrieval-BasedSDDrafter-BasedSD\n1295\tSkippingVerify Retrieval-BasedSDDrafter-BasedSDSkippingVerifyHybridHybridHybridHeiSD\n1296\tFigure 8.A Case ofHeiSDFramework Completing Real-World Tasks (Task Name: Pick up the Banana and Put It on the Plate)\n1297\tTable 4.Real-World Results ofHeiSD\n1298\tTask Category Fine-Tune HeiSDSR HeiSDSpeedup HeiSDAL\n1299\tAtomic Grasping 87.2% 86.0% 2.33× 4.47\n1300\tSpatial Displacement 77.3% 75.1% 2.41× 4.39\n1301\tComposite Sequential 71.7% 67.8% 2.06× 4.15\n1302\t40.00%\n1303\t45.00%\n1304\t50.00%\n1305\t1.55\n1306\t1.60\n1307\t1.65\n1308\t0.30.40.50.60.7\n1309\tLIBERO-LongSpeedSR\n1310\t60.00%\n1311\t70.00%\n1312\t80.00%\n1313\t1.80\n1314\t2.00\n1315\t2.20\n1316\t0.30.40.50.60.7\n1317\tLIBERO-GoalSpeedSR\n1318\t60.00%\n1319\t70.00%\n1320\t80.00%\n1321\t1.00\n1322\t2.00\n1323\t3.00\n1324\t0.30.40.50.60.7\n1325\tLIBERO-ObjectSpeedSR\n1326\t65.00%\n1327\t70.00%\n1328\t75.00%\n1329\t80.00%\n1330\t1.60\n1331\t1.80\n1332\t2.00\n1333\t0.30.40.50.60.7\n1334\tLIBERO-SpatialSpeedSR\n1335\tHeiSD’s Selection HeiSD’s Selection\n1336\tHeiSD’s SelectionHeiSD’s Selection\n1337\tFigure 9.Discussion of Hyper-ParameterwinHeiSD\n1338\t7.3. Discussion\n1339\tHyper-Parameters.HeiSDinvolves two hyper-parameters:\n1340\tthe sliding window size w for trajectory points and α in\n1341\tthe fused metric. We evaluateHeiSD’s performance across\n1342\tvarious hyper-parameters on the LIBERO-Goal benchmark,\n1343\twith the results presented in Fig. 10. As illustrated in Fig. 10,\n1344\twe test the results under different values of w across four\n1345\tsimulation environments. We find that the value of w exerts\n1346\ta significant influence on speed and SR, as it alters the\n1347\tdistribution of the fused metric. Considering both the SR\n1348\tand speed comprehensively, we selectw= 15 as the default\n1349\tvalue forHeiSD. Fig. 9 shows the results under different\n1350\tvalues of α. Similarly, α also influences the SR and speed.\n1351\tWe select α= 0.5 to ensure equal attention is allocated to\n1352\tthe curvature radius and cumulative displacement.\n1353\tHardware Implementation Analysis.We testHeiSD’s\n1354\tend-to-end latency (50 trials) on different hardware plat-\n1355\tforms in both four simulation benchmarks. Results in Tab. 6\n1356\tshow that offload database into CPU brings a little accelera-\n1357\ttion (1.04×∼1.09×). This demonstrates that the CPU ex-\n1358\thibits higher execution efficiency than the GPU for database\n1359\tTable 5.Ablation Studies ofHeiSDon LIBERO-Goal Benchmark\n1360\tSR Speedup AL\n1361\tOnly Hybrid SD 74.0% 1.05× 1.05\n1362\t+ Adaptive Verify-Skip 73.0%↓1.0% 2.08× ↑1.03× 4.04↑2.99\n1363\t+ Seq-Wise Relaxed Acceptance 73.0%↑0.0% 2.38× ↑0.30× 4.50↑0.46\n1364\t60.00%\n1365\t70.00%\n1366\t80.00%\n1367\t2.10\n1368\t2.30\n1369\t2.50\n1370\t1113151719\n1371\tLIBERO-GoalSpeedSR\n1372\t65.00%\n1373\t70.00%\n1374\t75.00%\n1375\t2.10\n1376\t2.30\n1377\t2.50\n1378\t1113151719\n1379\tLIBERO-ObjectSpeedSR\n1380\t70.00%\n1381\t75.00%\n1382\t80.00%\n1383\t1.60\n1384\t1.80\n1385\t2.00\n1386\t1113151719\n1387\tLIBERO-SpatialSpeedSR\n1388\t44.00%\n1389\t46.00%\n1390\t48.00%\n1391\t1.40\n1392\t1.60\n1393\t1.80\n1394\t1113151719\n1395\tLIBERO-LongSpeedSR\n1396\tHeiSD’s SelectionHeiSD’s Selection\n1397\tHeiSD’s SelectionHeiSD’s Selection\n1398\tFigure 10.Discussion of Hyper-ParameterαinHeiSD\n1399\tretrieval-related operations without specific optimization.\n1400\tMore critically, offloading databases to the CPU signifi-\n1401\tcantly saves GPU memory and better accommodates com-\n1402\tputing hardware of multiple specifications.Generality.Our\n1403\twork focuses exclusively on autoregressive VLAs and is not\n1404\tapplicable to those incorporating diffusion models, as SD\n1405\tcan only function in autoregressive models. The proposed\n1406\tHeiSDframework exhibits good generality and imposes no\n1407\tspecific requirements on autoregressive VLAs, task cate-\n1408\tgories, or robot platforms.\n1409\tScope.We do not design an automatic hyperparameter de-\n1410\ttermination method, mainly because established standards\n1411\tfor current embodied intelligence are lacking. Automatic\n1412\thyper-parameter selection is therefore designated as future\n1413\twork, to be addressed once environmental standards are\n1414\testablished. Additionally, the core purpose ofHeiSDis to\n1415\tachieve acceleration while ensuring SR, rather than to guar-\n1416\tantee strictly homogeneous distribution of draft and infer-\n1417\tence results. Thus, the impact of verify-skip and sequence-\n1418\twise relaxed acceptance on the output distribution is not\n1419\tconsidered in this paper as it falls outside the scope.\n1420\t8. Conclusion\n1421\tIn this paper, we first construct a database, design tests, iden-\n1422\ttify the trajectory overlapping regularity, and derive insights\n1423\tTable 6.Hardware Implementation Analysis ofHeiSD\n1424\tDetails Goal Object Spatial Long\n1425\tHeiSDon GPU 7388.9 s 7731.7 s 6557.0 s 23318.5 s\n1426\tHeiSDon CPU+GPU 7113.6 s 7328.4 s 6238.5 s 21352.7 s\n1427\tAcceleration 1.04× 1.06× 1.05× 1.09×\n1428\t8\n1429\t440\n1430\t441\n1431\t442\n1432\t443\n1433\t444\n1434\t445\n1435\t446\n1436\t447\n1437\t448\n1438\t449\n1439\t450\n1440\t451\n1441\t452\n1442\t453\n1443\t454\n1444\t455\n1445\t456\n1446\t457\n1447\t458\n1448\t459\n1449\t460\n1450\t461\n1451\t462\n1452\t463\n1453\t464\n1454\t465\n1455\t466\n1456\t467\n1457\t468\n1458\t469\n1459\t470\n1460\t471\n1461\t472\n1462\t473\n1463\t474\n1464\t475\n1465\t476\n1466\t477\n1467\t478\n1468\t479\n1469\t480\n1470\t481\n1471\t482\n1472\t483\n1473\t484\n1474\t485\n1475\t486\n1476\t487\n1477\t488\n1478\t489\n1479\t490\n1480\t491\n1481\t492\n1482\t493\n1483\t494\n1484\tSubmission and Formatting Instructions for ICML 2026\n1485\tfor implementing hybrid SD. Then we introduce an adaptive\n1486\tverify-skip mechanism and a sequence-wise relaxed accep-\n1487\ttance strategy to address limitations in retrieval-based SD.\n1488\tAdditionally, we develop a kinematic-based fusion metric\n1489\tto determine the hybrid boundary, formingHeiSDframe-\n1490\twork. Experiments show thatHeiSDattains a speedup of\n1491\tup to 2.45× in simulation benchmarks and 2.06×∼2.41×\n1492\tin real-world scenarios, while sustaining a high SR.\n1493\tImpact Statement\n1494\tThis paper presents work whose goal is to advance the field\n1495\tof machine learning. There are many potential societal\n1496\tconsequences of our work, none of which we feel must be\n1497\tspecifically highlighted here.\n1498\tReferences\n1499\tBudzianowski, P., Maa, W., Freed, M., Mo, J., Hsiao, W.,\n1500\tXie, A., Młoduchowski, T., Tipnis, V ., and Bolte, B.\n1501\tEdgevla: Efficient vision-language-action models.arXiv\n1502\tpreprint arXiv:2507.14049, 2025.\n1503\tCho, S., Choi, S., Hwang, T., Seo, J., Jeong, S., Lee, H.,\n1504\tSong, H., Park, J. C., and Kwon, Y . Lossless accelera-\n1505\ttion of large language models with hierarchical drafting\n1506\tbased on temporal locality in speculative decoding.arXiv\n1507\tpreprint arXiv:2502.05609, 2025.\n1508\tDing, N., Qin, Y ., Yang, G., Wei, F., Yang, Z., Su, Y ., Hu,\n1509\tS., Chen, Y ., Chan, C.-M., Chen, W., et al. Parameter-\n1510\tefficient fine-tuning of large-scale pre-trained language\n1511\tmodels.Nature machine intelligence, 5(3):220–235,\n1512\t2023.\n1513\tHan, Z., Gao, C., Liu, J., Zhang, J., and Zhang, S. Q.\n1514\tParameter-efficient fine-tuning for large models: A com-\n1515\tprehensive survey.arXiv preprint arXiv:2403.14608,\n1516\t2024.\n1517\tHe, Z., Zhong, Z., Cai, T., Lee, J., and He, D. Rest:\n1518\tRetrieval-based speculative decoding. InProceedings\n1519\tof the 2024 conference of the North American chapter\n1520\tof the association for computational linguistics: Human\n1521\tlanguage technologies (volume 1: long papers), pp. 1582–\n1522\t1595, 2024.\n1523\tHu, E. J., Shen, Y ., Wallis, P., Allen-Zhu, Z., Li, Y ., Wang,\n1524\tS., Wang, L., Chen, W., et al. Lora: Low-rank adaptation\n1525\tof large language models.ICLR, 1(2):3, 2022.\n1526\tKim, M. J., Pertsch, K., Karamcheti, S., Xiao, T., Balakr-\n1527\tishna, A., Nair, S., Rafailov, R., Foster, E., Lam, G., San-\n1528\tketi, P., et al. Openvla: An open-source vision-language-\n1529\taction model.arXiv preprint arXiv:2406.09246, 2024.\n1530\tKwon, O., George, A., Bartsch, A., and Farimani, A. B.\n1531\tRt-cache: Training-free retrieval for real-time manipula-\n1532\ttion. In2025 IEEE-RAS 24th International Conference\n1533\ton Humanoid Robots (Humanoids), pp. 1–8, 2025. doi:\n1534\t10.1109/Humanoids65713.2025.11203198.\n1535\tLee, A. C.-M., Cheng, W.-S., and Chan, C. C.-K.\n1536\tPROMTEC: Fast LLM inference decoding using prompt\n1537\tmulti-lookup with template database and common se-\n1538\tquences. In Che, W., Nabende, J., Shutova, E.,\n1539\tand Pilehvar, M. T. (eds.),Findings of the Asso-\n1540\tciation for Computational Linguistics: ACL 2025,\n1541\tpp. 6830–6842, Vienna, Austria, July 2025. Asso-\n1542\tciation for Computational Linguistics. ISBN 979-\n1543\t8-89176-256-5. doi: 10.18653/v1/2025.findings-acl.\n1544\t355. URL https://aclanthology.org/2025.\n1545\tfindings-acl.355/.\n1546\tLi, S., Hu, Y ., Ning, X., Liu, X., Hong, K., Jia, X., Li, X.,\n1547\tYan, Y ., Ran, P., Dai, G., et al. Mbq: Modality-balanced\n1548\tquantization for large vision-language models. InPro-\n1549\tceedings of the Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e6527c94-f67f-47a9-849d-c5fe31116d02","uuid":"a2b2bcd3-2bd9-4d6b-9043-6ea73ec72608","timestamp":"2026-04-25T20:01:58.246Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/papers/41c60725-bb92-47f2-acf8-07f0b99647fb.txt","content":"\u0001\n−µ\n\u00112\n.(5)\nR[w] = 1\nw\nw−1X\ni\nEuclid\n2-dim\n\u0010\n(u[w]\ni , v[w]\ni ); (ˆuc,ˆvc)\n\u0011\n.(6)\nAssume D[w] means the cumulative displacement in the slid-\ning window w. We use Euclid\n3-dim\n(·;·) to calculate the displace-\nment between two adjacent points. Then, we summarize all\nthe displacements to obtain D[w] (Eq. 7). Considering that\nthe robot sometimes performs round-trip or circular motion,\nD[w] does not consider the displacement direction.\nD[w] =\nw−1X\ni\nEuclid\n3-dim\n\u0010\n(P i\nx,y,z\n\f\f ∈ T);\n\u0000\nP i+1\nx,y,z\n\f\f ∈ T)\n\u0011\n.(7)\n5.3. Kinematic-Based Fused Metric\nWe fuse R[w] and D[w] based on Eq. (8) to obtain a fused\nmetric F [w]. N orm(·) means the normalization operation,\nwhich is detailed in Appendix D. Conceptually, a larger\nF [w] means faster movement and a trajectory closer to a\nstraight line (representing coarse-grained action); a smaller\nF [w] results in slower movement, a more curved trajectory,\nand fine-grained operation.\nF [w] =α·N orm\n\u0000\nR[w]\ni\n\u0001\n+ (1−α)·N orm\n\u0000\nD[w]\ni\n\u0001\n.(8)\nAs shown in Fig. 5, F [w] integrates R[w]\ni and D[w]\ni to com-\nprehensively characterize the trajectory. We identify a\nthreshold to serve as the demarcation between retrieval-\nbased SD and drafter-based SD. Specifically, whenF [w] at\nMetricDatabaseViT DraftLLMEmbedViTForward()\nRetriSimilarity()Top-K()\nAction\nVerifyLLMForward()\nCPUGPU\nRobot\nExeDe-Token()Control()\nVisionInfo.\nGenDrafterForward()\nVLAPeakDBPeakGPUTypeGPUGMEMResult\n16.6GB8.8GB\nRTX309024GBOOM\n❌RTX409024GBOOM\n❌RTX509024GB/32GBOOM\n❌A10040GB/80GBOK\n✅H10080GB/94GBOK\n✅\nOffloadingtheDatabasetoCPU\nHeiSDFrameworkComputationFlow\nEmbeddings｜fromGPU to CPU:Embed-dim= 4352-dim Vec @FP16Latency = 0.25ms (BW 32GB/s)Retrieved Draft｜fromCPU to GPU:Draft-dim = 7-dim Vec @FP16Latency: Negligible(BW 32GB/s)\nDataMovement – ACase\nSeq-WiseRelaxedAccept\nDafter\nIfR-SD\nElse S-SDDraftLLMVerifyLLMForward()\nIfVerify-SkipElse\nFigure 6.System Implementation ofHeiSDFramework\nthe current step exceeds the threshold, retrieval-based SD\nis selected, as bothR [w]\ni andD [w]\ni at this step are relatively\nlarge, which should align with the trajectory inferred by\nVLA; otherwise, drafter-based SD is chosen.\n6.HeiSDFramework Implementation\nThis section outlines key considerations forHeiSDframe-\nwork implementation, covering cost accounting, hardware\nmapping and overall computation flow.\n6.1. Cost Accounting and Hardware Mapping\nWe develop pre-implementation cost accounting (Fig. 6) to\nreveal that most consumer GPUs encounter Out-of-Memory\n(OOM) issues when hosting both the database component\nand the VLA model; thus, to ensure compatibility with\nmainstream hardware, the database is deployed in CPU\nmemory to reduce GPU memory overhead. This hetero-\ngeneous collaborative deployment necessitates GPU-CPU\ncommunications, whose detailed costing (Fig. 6) shows neg-\nligible overhead (>100 ms) in a single inference process,\nfar below that of model inference, validating the feasibility\nand effectiveness of this deployment strategy.\n6.2. Overall Computation Flow\nWe use 5000 lines of code to implement theHeiSDframe-\nwork. Its overall computation flow is shown in Fig. 6. First,\nvisual information is encoded into embeddings using a ViT\non the GPU. Then, based on the prior trajectory, our fused\nmetric determines the type of SD to be adopted. If the\nretrieval-based SD is used, the embeddings are transmitted\nto the CPU for retrieval, which includes similarity com-\nputation and Top-K selection. When drafter-based SD is\nemployed, the embeddings remain on the GPU and are input\nto the drafter for draft generation. For the retrieved drafts,\nthey are first moved back to the GPU. Then the adaptive\nverify-skip mechanism determines whether a draft should\nskip verification. If skipped, the draft is executed directly;\n6\n330\n331\n332\n333\n334\n335\n336\n337\n338\n339\n340\n341\n342\n343\n344\n345\n346\n347\n348\n349\n350\n351\n352\n353\n354\n355\n356\n357\n358\n359\n360\n361\n362\n363\n364\n365\n366\n367\n368\n369\n370\n371\n372\n373\n374\n375\n376\n377\n378\n379\n380\n381\n382\n383\n384\nSubmission and Formatting Instructions for ICML 2026\notherwise, verification is performed under our sequence-\nwise relaxed acceptance strategy. For drafts generated by\nthe drafter, since they already reside on the GPU, we directly\nperform verification. All verification processes occur on the\nGPU. We will show that this CPU+GPU implementation\noffers advantages over the GPU-only deployment below.\n7. Experiments\n7.1. Setup\nWe testHeiSDbased on OpenVLA (Kim et al., 2024) model\nclusters in LIBERO (Liu et al., 2023) simulation benchmark\nand real-world environment. We build a single LLaMA\nblock (Touvron et al., 2023) as a draft model to build drafter-\nbased SD. We train the draft models based on the Deep-\nSpeed (Rasley et al., 2020) framework, which takes 8 hours\nwith 2*NVIDIA A100 GPUs. We build retrieval-based SD\nusing the pre-built database. Both types of SD are appli-\ncable to OpenVLA as the validation model. Since there is\nno similar work, we choose pure drafter-based SD (Pure\nD-SD), pure retrieval-based SD (Pure R-SD), and SOTA\nwork SpecVLA (Wang et al., 2025) with token-level relaxed\nacceptance as the baselines. We use an Nvidia A100 GPU\nand an Intel Xeon Silver 4410T as hardware platform.\n7.2. Evaluation Results\nSimulation Results.We utilize four LIBERO task suites\nto evaluateHeiSDand each suite contains 10 tasks. For\neach task, we conduct 50 trials for testing. We report the\nresults in Tab. 3. Compared with autoregressive inference,\nHeiSDachieves 1.79 ×∼2.45× speed up. Compared with\nPure D-SD and Pure R-SD,HeiSDalso delivers significant\nacceleration effects. This confirms that our choice to hy-\nbridize two types of SD during VLA reasoning is highly\neffective. Moreover, even compared with SOTA works like\nSpecVLA,HeiSDachieves 1.51 ×∼2.22× speedup with bet-\nter SR. This demonstrates that the hybrid use of two SD\nmethods in the VLA reasoning process yields a superior\nPareto frontier. Fig. 7 presents the proportions of two types\nof SD and verify-skip across four environments, explaining\nthe source of acceleration. Moreover,HeiSDachieves an\nincreased acceptance length (AL) of about 4.75∼4.96. The\nimprovement in AL primarily stems from our optimization\nof retrieval-based SD. First, our verify-skip mechanism ef-\nfectively extends AL, as drafts with skipped verification are\ntreated as fully accepted. Second, our proposed sequence-\nwise relaxed acceptance strategy allows some biased tokens\nto be accepted alongside the sequence.\nReal-World Results.We construct a tabletop operating en-\nvironment (Appendix E.1), and employ the AgileX PIPER\nrobot arm (Appendix E.2) to testHeiSD’s performance in\nreal-world scenarios. We build various manipulation tasks\nLIBERO-Goal LIBERO-SpatialLIBERO-ObjectLIBERO-Long\nD-SD R-SDSkipVerifyR-SDw/Verify\nFigure 7.Discussion of Hyper-ParameterwinHeiSD\n(Appendix E.3). We collect massive human demonstration\ndata (Appendix E.4) to rebuild the database and fine-tune the\nmodels. After that, we deployHeiSDinto the real world and\ntest its performance. The results are shown in Tab. 4. On\nthe three task categories we defined (with SR of 87.2%,\n77.3%, and 71.7% after fine-tuning),HeiSDachieves a\n2.06×∼2.41× speedup with minor SR loss (1.2%∼3.9%).\nWe also represent an example real-world task completion\nprocess in Fig. 8 to show the performance.\nAblation Studies.We conduct ablation studies on the\nLIBERO-Goal benchmark to evaluate the effects ofHeiSD’s\ncomponents, with corresponding results reported in Tab. 4.\nWhen Hybrid SD is implemented solely based on fusion met-\nrics, the boundaries between retrieval-based SD and drafter-\nbased SD are defined; however, the overall performance\nremains suboptimal due to unresolved issues in retrieval-\nbased SD. Specifically, it achieves an SR of 74.0% but\nexhibits nearly no acceleration, with an average accepted\nlength of only 1.05. Building on this foundation, we incorpo-\nrate the adaptive verify-skip mechanism, which significantly\nenhances performance. It achieves a 2.08 × speedup with\nonly a slight drop (1.0%) in accuracy, while the AL is also\nincreased to 4.04. Further, after adding the sequence-wise\nrelaxed acceptance, it achieves 2.38 × speedup (0.3× in-\ncreasing) and an AL of 4.50, while maintaining 73.0% SR.\nTable 3.Simulation Results ofHeiSD\nEnv. Method SR Speed AL Steps HW\nLIBERO-Goal\nAR w/o SD 77.0% 1.00× – 157.6 GPU\nPure R-SD 77.0% 0.96× 1.03 152.6 CPU+GPU\nPure D-SD 76.2% 0.87× 1.68 159.2 GPU\nSpecVLA 71.0% 1.23× 3.63 166.8 GPU\nHeiSD 73.0% 2.38× 4.75 156.3 CPU+GPU\nLIBERO-Object\nAR w/o SD 71.2% 1.00× – 191.7 GPU\nPure R-SD 76.0% 0.98× 0.93 195.4 GPU\nPure D-SD 68.6% 0.96× 1.84 195.9 GPU\nSpecVLA 62.4% 1.10× 3.91 214.5 GPU\nHeiSD 71.0% 2.45× 4.94 189.6 CPU+GPU\nLIBERO-Spatial\nAR w/o SD 82.8% 1.00× – 126.9 GPU\npure R-SD 78.0% 1.15× 0.81 123.5 GPU\nPure D-SD 82.8% 0.98× 1.65 127.3 GPU\nSpecVLA 80.4% 1.26× 3.80 128.7 GPU\nHeiSD 78.0% 1.90× 4.83 127.8 CPU+GPU\nLIBERO-Long\nAR w/o SD 54.4% 1.00× – 393.2 GPU\nPure R-SD 50.0% 0.99× 0.81 399.3 GPU\nPure D-SD 50.2% 0.91× 1.59 400.7 GPU\nSpecVLA 46.2% 1.13× 3.63 439.6 GPU\nHeiSD 47.0% 1.79× 4.96 428.0 CPU+GPU\n7\n385\n386\n387\n388\n389\n390\n391\n392\n393\n394\n395\n396\n397\n398\n399\n400\n401\n402\n403\n404\n405\n406\n407\n408\n409\n410\n411\n412\n413\n414\n415\n416\n417\n418\n419\n420\n421\n422\n423\n424\n425\n426\n427\n428\n429\n430\n431\n432\n433\n434\n435\n436\n437\n438\n439\nSubmission and Formatting Instructions for ICML 2026\nRetrieval-BasedSDDrafter-BasedSD\nSkippingVerify Retrieval-BasedSDDrafter-BasedSDSkippingVerifyHybridHybridHybridHeiSD\nFigure 8.A Case ofHeiSDFramework Completing Real-World Tasks (Task Name: Pick up the Banana and Put It on the Plate)\nTable 4.Real-World Results ofHeiSD\nTask Category Fine-Tune HeiSDSR HeiSDSpeedup HeiSDAL\nAtomic Grasping 87.2% 86.0% 2.33× 4.47\nSpatial Displacement 77.3% 75.1% 2.41× 4.39\nComposite Sequential 71.7% 67.8% 2.06× 4.15\n40.00%\n45.00%\n50.00%\n1.55\n1.60\n1.65\n0.30.40.50.60.7\nLIBERO-LongSpeedSR\n60.00%\n70.00%\n80.00%\n1.80\n2.00\n2.20\n0.30.40.50.60.7\nLIBERO-GoalSpeedSR\n60.00%\n70.00%\n80.00%\n1.00\n2.00\n3.00\n0.30.40.50.60.7\nLIBERO-ObjectSpeedSR\n65.00%\n70.00%\n75.00%\n80.00%\n1.60\n1.80\n2.00\n0.30.40.50.60.7\nLIBERO-SpatialSpeedSR\nHeiSD’s Selection HeiSD’s Selection\nHeiSD’s SelectionHeiSD’s Selection\nFigure 9.Discussion of Hyper-ParameterwinHeiSD\n7.3. Discussion\nHyper-Parameters.HeiSDinvolves two hyper-parameters:\nthe sliding window size w for trajectory points and α in\nthe fused metric. We evaluateHeiSD’s performance across\nvarious hyper-parameters on the LIBERO-Goal benchmark,\nwith the results presented in Fig. 10. As illustrated in Fig. 10,\nwe test the results under different values of w across four\nsimulation environments. We find that the value of w exerts\na significant influence on speed and SR, as it alters the\ndistribution of the fused metric. Considering both the SR\nand speed comprehensively, we selectw= 15 as the default\nvalue forHeiSD. Fig. 9 shows the results under different\nvalues of α. Similarly, α also influences the SR and speed.\nWe select α= 0.5 to ensure equal attention is allocated to\nthe curvature radius and cumulative displacement.\nHardware Implementation Analysis.We testHeiSD’s\nend-to-end latency (50 trials) on different hardware plat-\nforms in both four simulation benchmarks. Results in Tab. 6\nshow that offload database into CPU brings a little accelera-\ntion (1.04×∼1.09×). This demonstrates that the CPU ex-\nhibits higher execution efficiency than the GPU for database\nTable 5.Ablation Studies ofHeiSDon LIBERO-Goal Benchmark\nSR Speedup AL\nOnly Hybrid SD 74.0% 1.05× 1.05\n+ Adaptive Verify-Skip 73.0%↓1.0% 2.08× ↑1.03× 4.04↑2.99\n+ Seq-Wise Relaxed Acceptance 73.0%↑0.0% 2.38× ↑0.30× 4.50↑0.46\n60.00%\n70.00%\n80.00%\n2.10\n2.30\n2.50\n1113151719\nLIBERO-GoalSpeedSR\n65.00%\n70.00%\n75.00%\n2.10\n2.30\n2.50\n1113151719\nLIBERO-ObjectSpeedSR\n70.00%\n75.00%\n80.00%\n1.60\n1.80\n2.00\n1113151719\nLIBERO-SpatialSpeedSR\n44.00%\n46.00%\n48.00%\n1.40\n1.60\n1.80\n1113151719\nLIBERO-LongSpeedSR\nHeiSD’s SelectionHeiSD’s Selection\nHeiSD’s SelectionHeiSD’s Selection\nFigure 10.Discussion of Hyper-ParameterαinHeiSD\nretrieval-related operations without specific optimization.\nMore critically, offloading databases to the CPU signifi-\ncantly saves GPU memory and better accommodates com-\nputing hardware of multiple specifications.Generality.Our\nwork focuses exclusively on autoregressive VLAs and is not\napplicable to those incorporating diffusion models, as SD\ncan only function in autoregressive models. The proposed\nHeiSDframework exhibits good generality and imposes no\nspecific requirements on autoregressive VLAs, task cate-\ngories, or robot platforms.\nScope.We do not design an automatic hyperparameter de-\ntermination method, mainly because established standards\nfor current embodied intelligence are lacking. Automatic\nhyper-parameter selection is therefore designated as future\nwork, to be addressed once environmental standards are\nestablished. Additionally, the core purpose ofHeiSDis to\nachieve acceleration while ensuring SR, rather than to guar-\nantee strictly homogeneous distribution of draft and infer-\nence results. Thus, the impact of verify-skip and sequence-\nwise relaxed acceptance on the output distribution is not\nconsidered in this paper as it falls outside the scope.\n8. Conclusion\nIn this paper, we first construct a database, design tests, iden-\ntify the trajectory overlapping regularity, and derive insights\nTable 6.Hardware Implementation Analysis ofHeiSD\nDetails Goal Object Spatial Long\nHeiSDon GPU 7388.9 s 7731.7 s 6557.0 s 23318.5 s\nHeiSDon CPU+GPU 7113.6 s 7328.4 s 6238.5 s 21352.7 s\nAcceleration 1.04× 1.06× 1.05× 1.09×\n8\n440\n441\n442\n443\n444\n445\n446\n447\n448\n449\n450\n451\n452\n453\n454\n455\n456\n457\n458\n459\n460\n461\n462\n463\n464\n465\n466\n467\n468\n469\n470\n471\n472\n473\n474\n475\n476\n477\n478\n479\n480\n481\n482\n483\n484\n485\n486\n487\n488\n489\n490\n491\n492\n493\n494\nSubmission and Formatting Instructions for ICML 2026\nfor implementing hybrid SD. Then we introduce an adaptive\nverify-skip mechanism and a sequence-wise relaxed accep-\ntance strategy to address limitations in retrieval-based SD.\nAdditionally, we develop a kinematic-based fusion metric\nto determine the hybrid boundary, formingHeiSDframe-\nwork. Experiments show thatHeiSDattains a speedup of\nup to 2.45× in simulation benchmarks and 2.06×∼2.41×\nin real-world scenarios, while sustaining a high SR.\nImpact Statement\nThis paper presents work whose goal is to advance the field\nof machine learning. There are many potential societal\nconsequences of our work, none of which we feel must be\nspecifically highlighted here.\nReferences\nBudzianowski, P., Maa, W., Freed, M., Mo, J., Hsiao, W.,\nXie, A., Młoduchowski, T., Tipnis, V ., and Bolte, B.\nEdgevla: Efficient vision-language-action models.arXiv\npreprint arXiv:2507.14049, 2025.\nCho, S., Choi, S., Hwang, T., Seo, J., Jeong, S., Lee, H.,\nSong, H., Park, J. C., and Kwon, Y . Lossless accelera-\ntion of large language models with hierarchical drafting\nbased on temporal locality in speculative decoding.arXiv\npreprint arXiv:2502.05609, 2025.\nDing, N., Qin, Y ., Yang, G., Wei, F., Yang, Z., Su, Y ., Hu,\nS., Chen, Y ., Chan, C.-M., Chen, W., et al. Parameter-\nefficient fine-tuning of large-scale pre-trained language\nmodels.Nature machine intelligence, 5(3):220–235,\n2023.\nHan, Z., Gao, C., Liu, J., Zhang, J., and Zhang, S. Q.\nParameter-efficient fine-tuning for large models: A com-\nprehensive survey.arXiv preprint arXiv:2403.14608,\n2024.\nHe, Z., Zhong, Z., Cai, T., Lee, J., and He, D. Rest:\nRetrieval-based speculative decoding. InProceedings\nof the 2024 conference of the North American chapter\nof the association for computational linguistics: Human\nlanguage technologies (volume 1: long papers), pp. 1582–\n1595, 2024.\nHu, E. J., Shen, Y ., Wallis, P., Allen-Zhu, Z., Li, Y ., Wang,\nS., Wang, L., Chen, W., et al. Lora: Low-rank adaptation\nof large language models.ICLR, 1(2):3, 2022.\nKim, M. J., Pertsch, K., Karamcheti, S., Xiao, T., Balakr-\nishna, A., Nair, S., Rafailov, R., Foster, E., Lam, G., San-\nketi, P., et al. Openvla: An open-source vision-language-\naction model.arXiv preprint arXiv:2406.09246, 2024.\nKwon, O., George, A., Bartsch, A., and Farimani, A. B.\nRt-cache: Training-free retrieval for real-time manipula-\ntion. In2025 IEEE-RAS 24th International Conference\non Humanoid Robots (Humanoids), pp. 1–8, 2025. doi:\n10.1109/Humanoids65713.2025.11203198.\nLee, A. C.-M., Cheng, W.-S., and Chan, C. C.-K.\nPROMTEC: Fast LLM inference decoding using prompt\nmulti-lookup with template database and common se-\nquences. In Che, W., Nabende, J., Shutova, E.,\nand Pilehvar, M. T. (eds.),Findings of the Asso-\nciation for Computational Linguistics: ACL 2025,\npp. 6830–6842, Vienna, Austria, July 2025. Asso-\nciation for Computational Linguistics. ISBN 979-\n8-89176-256-5. doi: 10.18653/v1/2025.findings-acl.\n355. URL https://aclanthology.org/2025.\nfindings-acl.355/.\nLi, S., Hu, Y ., Ning, X., Liu, X., Hong, K., Jia, X., Li, X.,\nYan, Y ., Ran, P., Dai, G., et al. Mbq: Modality-balanced\nquantization for large vision-language models. InPro-\nceedings of the Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition","numLines":600,"startLine":950,"totalLines":2667}}}
